mmissioner for Transport|Transport]] and [[European Commissioner for Consumer Protection|consumer protection]]\n|[[Karel Van Miert]]\n|{{BEL}}\n|[[Socialist Party (Belgium)|SP]]\n|---- bgcolor=#FFE8E8\n|[[European Commissioner for Regional Policy|Regional Policy]]\n|[[Bruce Millan]]\n|{{UK}}\n|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|---- bgcolor=#FFE8E8\n|[[European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs & Equal Opportunities|Employment, industrial relations and social affairs]]\n|[[Vasso Papandreou]]\n|{{GRE}}\n|[[Panhellenic Socialist Movement|PASOK]]\n|---- bgcolor=#FFE8E8\n|[[European Commissioner for the Environment|Environment]], [[European Commissioner for Energy|nuclear safety]] and civil protection\n|[[Carlo Ripa di Meana]]\n|{{ITA}}\n|[[Italian Socialist Party|PSI]]\n|---- bgcolor=#DDEEFF\n|[[European Commissioner for Financial Programming & the Budget|Budget]]\n|[[Peter Schmidhuber]]\n|{{DEU}}\n|[[Christian Social Union in Bavaria|CSU]]\n|---- bgcolor=#FFFFDD\n|[[European Commissioner for Taxation & Customs Union|Taxation and customs union]]\n|[[Christiane Scrivener]]\n|{{FRA}}\n|[[Republican Party (France)|Republican Party]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===Third college===\nThis Commission served from 1993 to 1994. It was the first Commission of the [[European Union]], with the [[Maastricht Treaty]] coming into force. Its short tenure was designed to bring the mandates of the Commission into line with those of the European Parliament.\n\n{| class=wikitable width=100%\n|-\n!width=40%|Portfolio\n!Name\n!State\n!Party\n|---- bgcolor=#FFE8E8\n|[[President of the European Commission|President]]\n|[[Jacques Delors]]\n|{{FRA}}\n|[[Socialist Party (France)|PS]]\n|---- bgcolor=#FFFFDD\n|[[Vice-President of the European Commission|Vice-President]]<br>[[European Commissioner for Internal Market & Services|Internal market]], [[European Commissioner for Enterprise & Industry|industrial affairs]] and [[European Commissioner for Information Society & Media|ICT]]\n|[[Martin Bangemann]]\n|{{DEU}}\n|[[Freie Demokratische Partei|FDP]]\n|---- bgcolor=#DDEEFF\n|[[Vice-President of the European Commission|Vice-President]]<br>[[European Commissioner for Trade|External economic affairs and trade policy]]\n|[[Leon Brittan|Sir Leon Brittan]]\n|{{UK}}\n|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|---- bgcolor=#FFFFDD\n|[[Vice-President of the European Commission|Vice-President]]<br>[[European Commissioner for Economic & Financial Affairs|Economic and financial affairs]]\n|[[Henning Christophersen]]\n|{{DNK}}\n|[[Venstre (Denmark)|Venstre]]\n|---- bgcolor=#FFE8E8\n|[[Vice-President of the European Commission|Vice-President]]<br>[[European Commissioner for Development & Humanitarian Aid|Cooperation, development and humanitarian aid]]\n|[[Manuel Marin]]\n|{{ESP}}\n|[[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party|PSOE]]\n|---- bgcolor=#FFE8E8\n|[[Vice-President of the European Commission|Vice-President]]<br>[[European Commissioner for Competition|Competition]]\n|[[Karel Van Miert]]\n|{{BEL}}\n|[[Socialist Party (Belgium)|SP]]\n|---- bgcolor=#FFE8E8\n|[[Vice-President of the European Commission|Vice-President]]<br>[[European Commissioner for Science & Research|Science, research, technological development]] and [[European Commissioner for Education, Training & Culture|education]]\n|[[Antonio Ruberti]]\n|{{ITA}}\n||[[Italian Socialist Party|PSI]]\n|---- bgcolor=#DDEEFF\n|[[European Commissioner for Transport|Transport]] and [[European Commissioner for Energy|energy]]\n|[[Marcelino Oreja]]<ref>After April 1994, replacing [[Abel Matutes]]</ref>\n|{{ESP}}\n|[[People's Party (Spain)|People's Party]]\n|---- bgcolor=#DDEEFF\n|[[European Commissioner for the Environment|Environment]], [[European Commissioner for Fisheries & Maritime Affairs|fisheries]]\n|[[Ioannis Paleokrassas]]\n|{{GRE}}\n|[[New Democracy (Greece)|ND]]\n|---- New Democracy (Greece)\n|---- bgcolor=#DDEEFF\n|[[European Commissioner for Agriculture & Rural Development|Agriculture and rural development]]\n|[[Ren\u00e9 Steichen]]\n|{{LUX}}\n|[[Christian Social People's Party|CSV]]\n|---- bgcolor=#DDEEFF\n|[[European Commissioner for Transport|Transport]] and [[European Commissioner for Energy|energy]]\n|[[Abel Matutes]]<ref>Until April 1994, replaced by [[Marcelino Oreja]]</ref>\n|{{ESP}}\n|[[People's Party (Spain)|People's Party]]\n|-\n|[[European Commissioner for Administrative Affairs, Audit and Anti-Fraud|Institutional reform]], [[European Commissioner for Internal Market & Services|internal market]] and [[European Commissioner for Enterprise & Industry|enterprise]]\n|[[Raniero Vanni d'Archirafi]]\n|{{ITA}}\n|None\n|---- bgcolor=#FFFFDD\n|[[European Commissioner for Taxation & Customs Union|Taxation, customs union]] and [[European Commissioner for Consumer Protection|consumer policies]]\n|[[Christiane Scrivener]]\n|{{FRA}}\n|[[Liberal Democracy (France)|Liberal]]\n|---- bgcolor=#DDEEFF\n|[[European Commissioner for Financial Programming & the Budget|Budget, financial control and the cohesion fund]]\n|[[Peter Schmidhuber]]\n|{{DEU}}\n|[[Christian Social Union in Bavaria|CSU]]\n|---- bgcolor=#DDEEFF\n|[[European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs & Equal Opportunities|Social affairs and employment]]\n|[[P\u00e1draig Flynn]]\n|{{IRL}}\n|[[Fianna F\u00e1il]]\n|---- bgcolor=#DDEEFF\n|[[European Commissioner for Inter-Institutional Relations and Administration|Relations with Parliament]], [[European Commissioner for Education, Training & Culture|culture]] and [[European Commissioner for Information Society & Media|audiovisual]]\n|[[Jo\u00e3o de Deus Pinheiro]]\n|{{PRT}}\n|[[Social Democratic Party (Portugal)|PSD]]/[[People's Party (Portugal)|PP]]\n|---- bgcolor=#DDEEFF\n|[[European Commissioner for External Relations|External relations]] and [[European Commissioner for Enlargement|enlargement]]\n|[[Hans van den Broek]]\n|{{NLD}}\n|[[Christen-Democratisch App\u00e8l|CDA]]\n|---- bgcolor=#FFE8E8\n|[[European Commissioner for Regional Policy|Regional policy and cohesion]]\n|[[Bruce Millan]]\n|{{UK}}\n|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===Key===\nThe colour of the row indicates the approximate political leaning of the office holder using the following scheme:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Affiliation\n!First term\n!Second term\n!Third term\n|---- bgcolor=#DDEEFF\n|[[right-wing politics|Right]] leaning / Conservative\n| 9\n| 7\n| 8\n|---- bgcolor=#FFE8E8\n|[[Left-wing politics|Left]] leaning / Socialist\n| 6\n| 7\n| 5\n|---- bgcolor=#FFFFDD\n|Centrist / Liberal\n| 2\n| 3\n| 3\n|---- bgcolor=#FFFFFF\n| Other / Unknown\n| 1\n| 1\n| 1\n|}\n\n===Secretary-General===\nThe [[Secretary-General of the European Commission]] throughout the three Delors Commissions was [[David Williamson, Baron Williamson of Horton|David Williamson]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Single European Act]]\n*[[Treaty of Maastricht]]\n*[[Economic and Monetary Union of the European Union|EMU]]\n*[[Delors building]]\n* [[European Navigator]]\n\n== Footnotes ==\n<!--This article uses the Cite.php citation mechanism. If you would like more information on how to add footnotes to this article, please see http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Cite/Cite.php -->\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n* [[European Commission]] archive of the Delors I Commission. \"[http://ec.europa.eu/avservices/photo/photo.cfm?id=1565&sitelang=en]\" Retrieved 17 March 2007.\n* EU Press release (1988). \"[http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=IP/88/825&format=HTML&aged=1&language=EN&guiLanguage=en Responsibilities of the members of the new commission]\". Retrieved 24 March 2005.\n* EU Press release (1992). \"[http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=IP/92/1080&format=HTML&aged=0&language=EN&guiLanguage=en Composition of the new Commission]\". Retrieved 17 March 2007.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://ec.europa.eu/economy_finance/euro/emu/road/delors_report_en.htm Delors Report] ec.europa.eu\n*[http://ec.europa.eu/avservices/photo/photo.cfm?id=1565&si