{"title_page": "Jeddah Tower", "text_new": "{{redirect-distinguish|Kingdom Tower|Jeddah TV Tower|Kingdom Centre|Mile High Illinois}}\n{{short description|Skyscraper under construction in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox Building\n| name = Jeddah Tower\n| native_name = \u0628\u0631\u062c \u062c\u062f\u0629\n| status = On Hold<ref name=\"CNNDavosInterview\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/videos/business/2019/01/21/saudi-arabia-kingdom-holding.cnn-business|publisher=CNN|title=CNN Interview with Company Chairman|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n| image = Jeddah Tower August 2019 S.Nitzold.jpg\n| caption = Jeddah Tower in August 2019\n| location = [[Jeddah]], Saudi Arabia\n| coordinates = {{coord|21.734063|39.082758|region:SA-02_type:landmark |display=title,inline}}\n| start_date = {{Start date|df=yes|2013|04|01}}\n| architect = [[Adrian Smith (architect)|Adrian D. Smith]], [[Adrian Smith + Gordon Gill Architecture]]\n| owner = Jeddah Economic Company;\tKingdom Real Estate Development\n| cost = [[Saudi riyal|SR]]10&nbsp;billion (US$10.23&nbsp;billion)<ref name=\"wallstreetjournalaugust3\">{{cite news | author=Summer Said | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424053111903341404576483540742054836?mod=WSJ_World_LEFTSecondNews |title=Saudis Plan World's Tallest Tower|date=3 August 2011| work=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=3 August 2011}}</ref> (preliminary)\n| floor_area = {{cvt|243,866|sqm}}\n| top_floor = {{cvt|668|m|ft|0}} (if completed as planned)\n| floor_count = 200+ (2 basements)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2015/jun/04/jeddahs-kingdom-tower-how-much-higher-can-skyscrapers-go-a-history-of-cities-in-50-buildings-day-50|title=Jeddah's Kingdom Tower: how much higher can skyscrapers go? A history of cities in 50 buildings, day 50|work=the Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/style/amp/jeddah-tower-saudi-arabia-new/index.html|title=Jeddah Tower: What does the world's next tallest skyscraper look like now?|work=CNN}}</ref>\n| references = <ref name=skyscraperCenter>{{cite web|url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/jeddah/kingdom-tower/2 |title=Jeddah Tower \u2013 The Skyscraper Center |publisher=Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat}}</ref><ref name=\"milehightowerssp\">{{cite web|url=http://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=82759|title=Mile-High Tower|publisher=[[SkyscraperPage]]|accessdate=10 August 2011}}</ref>\n| building_type = Mixed-use: office, hotel, residential, apartments, observation, retail\n| architectural_style = [[Neo-futurism]]<br>\n| structural_system = Reinforced concrete and steel, all-glass fa\u00e7ade\n| architectural = At least {{cvt|1000|m}}\n| roof = At least {{cvt|1000|m}}\n| observatory = {{cvt|652|m}}\n| elevator_count = 59 (55 single deck and 4 double deck),<ref name=skyscraperCenter/><ref>{{cite web|title=Kingdom Tower Jeddah, Saudi Arabia|url=http://smithgill.com/media/pdfs/Kingdom_for_web_7.pdf|publisher=Adrian Smith + Gordon Gill Architecture LLP|accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> made by [[KONE]]<ref>{{cite web|title=KONE wins order for Saudi Arabia's Kingdom Tower, the world's tallest building|url=http://www.kone.com/en/media/releases/kone-wins-order-for-saudi-arabia-s-kingdom-tower--the-world-s-tallest-building-2014-06-05.aspx|publisher=KONE Corporation|accessdate=23 August 2017}}</ref>\n| structural_engineer = [[Thornton Tomasetti]]\n| main_contractor = [[Saudi Binladin Group]]\n| image_size = \n| est_completion = Unknown\n| opening = Unknown\n| engineer = Langan International (sub-grade and transportation planning)<ref name=\"langanwebsite\">{{cite web|title=Langan Website|url=http://www.langan.com/web/|publisher=Langan International|year=2011|accessdate=5 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806204935/http://www.langan.com/web/|archivedate=6 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| developer = Jeddah Economic Company (JEC)<ref name=\"emirates24/7august2.2\">{{cite news | url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/region/kingdom-tower-to-pip-reigning-champ-burj-khalifa-by-173m-2011-08-02-1.411064 | title=Kingdom Tower to pip reigning champ Burj Khalifa by 173m | work=Emirates 24/7 | date=2 August 2011 | accessdate=3 August 2011 | author=Nambiar, Sona | publisher=Dubai Media Incorporated}}</ref>\n| management = [[CBRE Group]]\n| stop_date = 25 January 2018 (Planned to start again in 2020)<ref> https://www.enr.com/articles/48077-owner-may-ramp-up-construction-of-jeddah-tower-planned-to-be-over-1-km}} </ref>\n| completion_date = \n}}\n\n'''Jeddah Tower''' ({{lang-ar|\u0628\u0631\u062c \u062c\u062f\u0629}}),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingdom.com.sa/jec-alinma-investment-in-an-sar-8-4-billion-real-estate-fund-deal-fund-objective-is-to-develop-jeddah-tower-and-the-jeddah-economic-city-infrastructure|title=8.4&nbsp;billion real estate deal objective is to develop Jeddah Tower and the Jeddah Economic City|publisher=Kingdom Holding Company|date=29 November 2015|accessdate=30 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151130183439/http://www.kingdom.com.sa/jec-alinma-investment-in-an-sar-8-4-billion-real-estate-fund-deal-fund-objective-is-to-develop-jeddah-tower-and-the-jeddah-economic-city-infrastructure|archive-date=30 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> previously known as '''Kingdom Tower''' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0645\u0644\u0643\u0629}}) and '''Mile-High Tower''' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0644}}), is a planned skyscraper on the north side of [[Jeddah]], [[Saudi Arabia]]. It is planned to be the world's first {{convert|1|km|ft|abbr=on|0}} high building, and the centrepiece and first phase of a development and tourist attraction known as [[Jeddah Economic City]].<ref name=\"meconstruction\">{{cite web|url=http://meconstructionnews.com/story/4705/saudis-kingdom-tower-how-worlds-tallest-building-will-benefit-jeddah |title=Saudi's Kingdom Tower: How world\u2019s tallest building will benefit Jeddah |date=24 June 2015|author=Jerusha Sequeira |publisher=[[CPI Media Group]] |website=MEConstructionNews.com|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nInitial plans called for a mile-high structure,<ref name=\"arabnewsaugust2\">{{cite news|url=http://arabnews.com/saudiarabia/article481836.ece |title=Kingdom Holding to build world's tallest tower in Jeddah |work=Arab News |date=3 August 2011 |accessdate=10 August 2011 |author=Khan, Ghazanfar Ali |author2=Abbas, Maher |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319084546/http://arabnews.com/saudiarabia/article481836.ece |archivedate=19 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> but the geology of the area proved unsuitable. The current design, created by American architect [[Adrian Smith (architect)|Adrian Smith]], who also designed [[Burj Khalifa]], incorporates many unique structural and aesthetic features. The creator and leader of the project is Saudi Arabian prince [[Al-Waleed bin Talal]],<ref name=\"alarabiya1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alarabiya.net/articles/2011/04/04/144136.html|title=Bin Talal remains richest Arab in 2011: report|author=Farid, Sonia|publisher=Alarabiya.net|date=4 April 2011|accessdate=10 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123074502/http://www.alarabiya.net/articles/2011/04/04/144136.html|archive-date=23 November 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Descendants of Ibn Saud|a grandson]] of [[Ibn Saud]], and nephew of the [[King of Saudi Arabia#Kings of Saudi Arabia (1932\u2013present)|Kings of Saudi Arabia]] before him. Al-Waleed is the chairman of [[Kingdom Holding Company]] (KHC),<ref name=\"businesswireaugust5\" /> which is a partner in the Jeddah Economic Company (JEC), which was formed in 2009 for the development of Jeddah Tower and City.<ref name=\"businesswireaugust5\" />\n\n==Overview==\nThe building has been scaled down from its initial one mile high (5,280&nbsp;ft) proposal, which was never fully designed, to a height of at least {{convert|1000|m|ft|0}} (the exact height is being kept private while in development, similar to the [[Burj Khalifa]]).{{ref label|note01|A|b}}<ref name=\"arabnewsaugust2\"/> At about one kilometre,<ref name=\"miamiheraldaugust7\">{{cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2011/08/07/v-print/2348937/worlds-tallest-tower-to-go-up.html#ixzz1UNEiWijY|title=World's tallest tower to go up in Saudi in 5 years|date=7 August 2011|author=[[The Associated Press]]|publisher=The [[Miami Herald]]|accessdate=7 August 2011}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Jeddah Tower would still be by far the [[List of tallest buildings and structures in the world|tallest building or structure in the world]] to date,<ref>{{cite news |author=AFP |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,23363844-25658,00.html |title=Saudi mile-high tower plan raises bar |work=The Australian |date=13 March 2008 |accessdate=3 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307043204/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,23363844-25658,00.html |archive-date=7 March 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> standing {{convert|180|m|ft|abbr=on|0|}} taller than the Burj Khalifa in [[Dubai]], United Arab Emirates.<ref name=\"chicagotribuneaugust2\" />\nJeddah Tower's {{Convert|50|ha|acre|adj=on}} plot with surrounding buildings will be the first of a three phase Jeddah Economic City development. The three phase project proposed for a large area of undeveloped waterfront land with an area of {{convert|5.2|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"telegraphaugust11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/saudiarabia/8678426/Saudi-skyscraper-facts-and-figures.html|title=Saudi skyscraper: facts and figures|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=11 August 2011|accessdate=11 August 2011|location=London}}</ref> It was originally planned to cover {{convert|23|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} and cost SR100&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"dailymailoctober2008\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1077109/Saudi-Arabia-build-worlds-tallest-building.html|publisher=Daily Mail|date=13 October 2008|title=Saudi Arabia to build world's tallest building|accessdate=19 October 2011|location=London}}</ref> The area is located roughly {{convert|20|km|abbr=on|0}} north of the port city of Jeddah. Jeddah Economic City was designed by [[HOK Architects]],<ref name=\"globestaugust11\" /> and is estimated to cost at least SR75&nbsp;billion (US$20&nbsp;billion) and take around ten&nbsp;years to build.<ref name=\"truthdiveaugust6\">{{cite web | url=http://truthdive.com/2011/08/06/worlds-tallest-tower-to-be-built-for-1-2-bn-in-saudi-arabia.html | title=World's tallest tower to be built for $1.2 bn in Saudi Arabia | publisher=TruthDive | date=6 August 2011 | accessdate=6 August 2011 | author=Devi, Kanchana | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321234147/http://truthdive.com/2011/08/06/worlds-tallest-tower-to-be-built-for-1-2-bn-in-saudi-arabia.html | archive-date=21 March 2012 | url-status=usurped | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe development is envisioned to grow into a new district of Jeddah.<ref name=\"metroaugust11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/news/872134-kingdom-tower-in-saudi-arabia-to-be-worlds-next-tallest-building|title=Kingdom Tower in Saudi Arabia to be world's next tallest building|author=Radnedge, Aidan|publisher=[[Metro.co.uk]]|date=11 August 2011|accessdate=11 August 2011}}</ref> The second phase of the project will be the infrastructure development needed to support the city, and the third phase has not yet been revealed.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13crown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13537-crown-of-the-kingdom/|title=Crown of the Kingdom|author=Roberts, Ben|date=13 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe focal point of the development and Jeddah Tower's primary use will be to house a [[Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts|Four Seasons hotel]], Four Seasons [[serviced apartment]]s, Class A office space, and luxury condominiums. The tower will also have the world's highest [[observatory]].<ref name=\"dezeen august 2\">{{cite web|last=Etherington|first=Rose|title=First image of world's tallest building, to be built in Jeddah|url=http://www.dezeen.com/2011/08/02/first-image-of-worlds-tallest-buildingto-be-built-in-jeddah/|date=2 August 2011|publisher=Dezeen|accessdate=2 August 2011}}</ref> Although the Jeddah Economic City plot is nearly isolated from the current urban core of Jeddah, no land tracts of such size were available closer to the city.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13crown\" /> Northward is generally considered the direction in which the city will spread in the future.\n\nThe primary designer of Jeddah Tower is Chicago based architect [[Adrian Smith (architect)|Adrian Smith]] of [[Adrian Smith + Gordon Gill Architecture]] (AS + GG),<ref name=\"chicagotribuneaugust2\">{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/breaking/chi-110802-kingdom-tower-pictures,0,2908125.photogallery |title=Kingdom Tower: Tallest of the tall |author= |date=2 August 2011 |work=The Chicago Tribune |accessdate=2 August 2011}}</ref> the same architect who designed the Burj Khalifa while he was working for [[Skidmore, Owings & Merrill]] (SOM),<ref name=\"gulfnews102010\">{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/property/gulf/tallest-tower-plan-in-jeddah-on-track-1.700123|title=Tallest tower plan in Jeddah on track|date=22 October 2010|work=Gulf News|accessdate=31 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101027103105/http://gulfnews.com/business/property/gulf/tallest-tower-plan-in-jeddah-on-track-1.700123|archivedate=27 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> for which he worked almost 40 years.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13king\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13532-king-of-skyscrapers/|title=King of skyscrapers|author=Ephgrave, Oliver|date=13 August 2011|accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref> AS + GG was formed in 2006 by Adrian Smith, Gordon Gill, and Robert Forest.<ref name=\"worldpropertychannelaugust3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldpropertychannel.com/international-markets/commercial-real-estate/kingdom-tower-tallest-building-in-the-world-adrian-smith-gordon-gill-architecture-saudi-arabia-skyscrapers-burj-khalifa-prince-alwaleed-bin-talal-bin-abdulaziz-alsaud-saudi-prince-asgg-king-abdullah-kingdom-holding-company-4618.php|title=Saudi Arabia's Kingdom Tower Announced, World's Newest Tallest Tower|author=Gerrity, Michael|date=3 August 2011|publisher=WorldPropertyChannel|accessdate=13 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930081758/http://www.worldpropertychannel.com/international-markets/commercial-real-estate/kingdom-tower-tallest-building-in-the-world-adrian-smith-gordon-gill-architecture-saudi-arabia-skyscrapers-burj-khalifa-prince-alwaleed-bin-talal-bin-abdulaziz-alsaud-saudi-prince-asgg-king-abdullah-kingdom-holding-company-4618.php|archive-date=30 September 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The development of the tower is being managed by Emaar Properties PJSC.<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-22/alwaleed-picks-burj-khalifa-architect-adrian-smith-to-design-kingdom-tower.html|title=Alwaleed Picks Burj Khalifa Architect Adrian Smith to Design Kingdom Tower |date=22 October 2010 |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=22 October 2010 |first=Arif |last=Sharif}}</ref> [[Thornton Tomasetti]] has been selected as the structural engineering firm,<ref name=\"newswireaugust2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/prince-alwaleed-signs-sr46billion-contract-for-worlds-tallest-1000-meters-tower-1st-phase-of-jeddah-development-126570338.html|title= Prince Alwaleed Signs SR4.6Billion Contract for World's Tallest 1,000 meters Tower 1st Phase of Jeddah Development |date=2 August 2011 |work=PR Newswire|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> and Environmental Systems Design, Inc. (ESD)<ref name=\"CWesd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13502-kingdom-tower-esd-wins-building-systems-contract/|title=Kingdom Tower: ESD wins building systems contract|date=9 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|author=Abdulla, Hannah-Farah|accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref> is a part of the AS + GG design team that serves as the building services engineering consultants.<ref name=\"urukiaaugust3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.urukia.com/kingdom-tower/|title=Kingdom Tower World's Tallest Skyscraper in Jeddah|publisher=Urukia Magazine|date=3 August 2011|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 August 2011, it was publicly announced by Kingdom Holding, the investment company, that a contract had been signed by [[Saudi Binladin Group]] (SBG), that construction was going to start soon, and that the tower was expected to take 63 months to complete.<ref name=\"wallstreetjournalaugust2\">{{cite news|url=https://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20110802-709579.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105064534/http://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20110802-709579.html |archive-date=5 January 2012 |title=Kingdom's Alwaleed: Tallest Tower To Provide Sustainable Profit |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=2 August 2011 |accessdate=2 August 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/kerryadolan/2011/08/02/saudi-prince-alwaleed-to-build-worlds-tallest-tower-with-bin-laden-group/#2715e4857a0b1c2bf4aa6de7 Saudi Prince Alwaleed To Build World's Tallest Tower With Binladen Group] Kerry A. Dolan, [[Forbes]], 2 August 2011 @ 01:04&nbsp;pm</ref><ref>[http://www.kingdom.com.sa/building-a-landmark-jeddah-tower-the-worlds-tallest-building Building a landmark: Kingdom Tower, The world\u2019s tallest building] Kingdom Holding Company. 26 December 2011</ref>\n\n[[Besix]] Group (Belgian Six Construct), which constructed the Burj Khalifa, was previously considered for the contract, but did not win, partially because SBG invested in Jeddah Economic Company (JEC),<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13471-besix-kingdom-towers-big-challenge-is-logistics/|title=Besix: Kingdom Tower's big challenge is logistics|author=Gerhard Hope|date=7 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> contributing SR1.5&nbsp;billion (US$400&nbsp;million) towards the development of the project,<ref name=\"saudibusinessaugust7\">{{cite web|url=http://arabianbusiness.com/kingdom-eyes-loans-cash-build-world-s-tallest-tower--414491.html|title=Kingdom eyes loans, cash to build world's tallest tower|publisher=Arabian Business|date=7 August 2011|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> and holding a 16.6 percent stake in Jeddah Economic Company.<ref name=\"dailymailaugust9\" /> Besix admitted in 2010 that they expected Binladin Group to win the contract.<ref name=\"constructionweeknovember2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-10206-besix-we-expect-binladin-to-win-kingdom-tower/|date=21 November 2010|title=Besix: we expect Binladin to win Kingdom Tower|author=Broomhall, Elizabeth|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> Jeddah Economic Company is a [[closed joint stock company]] (PJSC) formed in 2009 as a financial entity for Jeddah Tower and Jeddah Economic City. It is made up primarily of financiers (stakeholders) Kingdom Holding Company (33.35%), Abrar Holding Company (33.35%), which is owned by Samaual Bakhsh and businessman Abdulrahman Hassan Sharbately (16.67%), as well as the tower's own contractor, Saudi Binladin Group (16.63%).<ref name=\"earthtechlingaugust12\">{{cite web|url=http://www.earthtechling.com/2011/08/planned-green-skyscraper-really-really-tall/|title=Planned Green Skyscraper Really, Really Tall|author=DeFreitas, Susan|publisher=EarthTechling LLC|date=12 August 2011|accessdate=12 August 2011}}</ref> JEC's assets have a book value of nearly SR9&nbsp;billion, broken down between a [[Land banking|land bank]] of over {{convert|5300000|m2|ft2|0|abbr=on}} (the Jeddah Economic City plot) with a value of SR7.3&nbsp;billion that will be used as [[collateral (finance)|collateral]] to attain bank loans, and SR1.5&nbsp;billion in cash.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13crown\" /> Kingdom Holding is an [[investment company]] founded in 1980 and 95% owned by [[Al-Waleed bin Talal]]<ref name=\"albawabaaugust8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.albawaba.com/main-headlines/alwaleed-bin-talal-companies-build-tallest-tower-world-387307|title=Alwaleed bin Talal companies to build the tallest tower in the world|publisher=[[Al Bawaba]]|date=8 August 2011|accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref> that has assets valued at over $25&nbsp;billion, with interests in many major companies such as [[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney]], [[Pepsico]], [[Kodak]], [[Apple Computers|Apple]], [[Hewlett Packard]], [[Motorola]], [[Time Warner]], [[Newscorp]], Pinnacle Infotech Solutions and [[Citigroup]], as well as real estate in London through its Songbird Estates division.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust16rollcall\" />\n\n==Construction history==\nIn May 2008, [[geotechnical investigation|soil testing]] in the area cast doubt over whether the proposed location could support a skyscraper of the proposed one-mile height, and [[MEED]] reported that the project had been scaled back, making it \"up to {{convert|500|m|ft|0}} shorter.\"<ref name=\"tallestbuildingintheworld\">{{cite web | url=http://www.tallestbuildingintheworld.com/building_id_108_Mile+High+Tower+(working+name).php | title=Mile High Tower (working name) \u2013 Jeddah | publisher=Tallest Building in the World.com | accessdate=3 August 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716192034/http://www.tallestbuildingintheworld.com/building_id_108_Mile+High+Tower+%28working+name%29.php | archive-date=16 July 2011 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nReports in 2009 suggested that the project had been put on hold due to the [[Global financial crisis of 2008\u20132009]] and that [[Bechtel]] (the former engineering firm) was \"in the process of ending its involvement with the project.\"<ref name=menainfra>{{cite news|author=Timon Singh|url=http://www.menainfra.com/news/mile-high-tower/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130128165945/http://www.menainfra.com/news/mile-high-tower/|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 January 2013|title=Has the Mile High Tower been shelved?|work=MENA Infrastructure|publisher=GDS Publishing Ltd.|accessdate=11 January 2011}}</ref><ref name=stall>{{cite web|url=http://www.nce.co.uk/news/2009/02/saudi_milehigh_tower_latest_skyscraper_to_stall.html|title=Saudi mile-high tower latest skyscraper to stall|publisher=New Civil Engineer (Emap)|accessdate=23 February 2009}}</ref> Kingdom Holding Company quickly criticized the news reports, insisting that the project had not been shelved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/547358-kingdom-holding-says-tower-not-on-hold|title=Kingdom Holding says tower not on hold|work=Arabian Business|accessdate=23 February 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091126203038/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/547358-kingdom-holding-says-tower-not-on-hold|archive-date=26 November 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Architect selected ===\nIn March 2010, Adrian Smith of Adrian Smith + Gordon Gill Architecture (AS + GG) was selected as the preliminary architect (though they deny involvement in the earlier, mile-high designs).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ameinfo.com/226876.html |title=US firm to design world's tallest tower in Saudi |date=16 March 2010 |work=AMEnfo |accessdate=11 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322204608/http://www.ameinfo.com/226876.html |archivedate=22 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Later, when the proposal was more serious, they won a design competition between eight leading architectural firms including [[Kohn Pedersen Fox]], Pickard Chilton, Pelli Clarke Pelli, and [[Foster + Partners]], as well as the firm Smith formerly worked for [[Skidmore, Owings and Merrill]],<ref name=\"azobuild\" /> which was the final competitor in the competition before AS + GG was chosen.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> In addition to Burj Khalifa, Adrian Smith has designed several other recent towers; the [[Zifeng Tower]] in [[Nanjing]], China, the [[Trump International Hotel and Tower (Chicago)|Trump International Hotel & Tower]] in Chicago, and the [[Jin Mao Tower]] in Shanghai,<ref name=\"artinfoaugust5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artinfo.com/news/story/38286/bin-laden-group-plans-to-build-the-worlds-tallest-super-skyscraper-in-jeddah/|title=Bin Laden Group Plans to Build the World's Tallest Super Skyscraper in Jeddah|author=Janelle Zara|date=5 August 2011|publisher=Art Info|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> as well as the [[Pearl River Tower]] in [[Guangzhou]], China.<ref name=\"earchitectaugust2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.e-architect.co.uk/saudi_arabia/kingdom_tower_jeddah.htm|title=Kingdom Tower Jeddah, Saudi Arabia: to be the world's tallest building|publisher=e-architect|date=2 August 2011|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> The four buildings are all among the top eleven tallest in the world. Furthermore, the Pearl River Tower is a unique tower that was originally designed to use zero net energy by drawing all its needed power from [[wind power|wind]], [[solar power|sunlight]], and [[geothermal energy|geothermal mass]],<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13king\" /> though this design goal was not fully achieved.<ref name=\"Frechette-Gilchrist\">{{cite journal|last=Frechette|first=R|authorlink=|author2=Gilchrist, R|date=March 2008|title=Towards Zero Energy: A case study of the Pearl River Tower, Guangzhou, China|trans-title=|journal=Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat|volume=|issue=|pages=pg. 9|id=|accessdate=30 March 2015|url=http://ctbuh.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=%2bpedN46s7Es%3d&tabid=486&language=en-US/|publisher=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526235034/http://ctbuh.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=%2BpedN46s7Es%3D&tabid=486&language=en-US%2F|archive-date=26 May 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, the owners (Kingdom Holding Company) signed a development agreement with [[Emaar Properties]] PJSC. The final height of the building was questionable, but it was still listed to be over 1 kilometre.<ref>{{cite news | title=Emaar Sign Agreement For 1000m Tower | url=http://www.skyscrapernews.com/news.php?ref=2682 | work=Skyscrapernews | date=22 October 2010 | accessdate=2 August 2011}}</ref> Kingdom Holding said construction was progressing.<ref name=\"gulfnews102010\" /><ref>{{cite news |author=Blair Kamin |url=http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/theskyline/2010/10/chicago-architects-working-on-a-mile-high-tower-can-it-be-built-repeat-after-me-chicago-spire-.html |title=Saudi mega-tower designed by Chicago architects moving ahead |date=22 October 2010 |work=The Chicago Tribune |accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Approvals ===\nIn March and April 2011, several news agencies reported that the Mile-High Tower design had been approved at that height and that the building would cost almost US$30&nbsp;billion (SR112.5&nbsp;billion).<ref name=sydherald>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/milehigh-building-gets-approval-20110417-1djg4.html|title=The tallest building in the world|date=17 April 2011 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=21 April 2011}}</ref> This design was going to be drastically larger than the current design, with a floor area of {{convert|38000000|ft2|m2|abbr=on|0|order=flip }} and would have used futuristic wind aversion and energy producing technology for sustainability. It and the surrounding City would have had the ability to accommodate 80,000 residents and one million visitors,<ref name=\"singularityhubmarch2011\">{{cite web|url=http://singularityhub.com/2011/03/29/jeddah%E2%80%99s-kingdom-tower-world%E2%80%99s-tallest-building-given-the-go-ahead/|title=Jeddah's Kingdom Tower, World's Tallest Building Given the Go Ahead|author=Louie Helm|publisher=SingularityHub|date=29 March 2011|accessdate=9 August 2011|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120717213006/http://singularityhub.com/2011/03/29/jeddah%E2%80%99s-kingdom-tower-world%E2%80%99s-tallest-building-given-the-go-ahead/|archive-date=17 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> according to [[RIA Novosti]].<ref name=sydherald /> Many things were rumoured about the mile-high designs, such as that it would be so high the top would freeze at night, helicopters would be used for construction, parachutes would be part of the fire escape plan, and that an elevator ride to the top would take 12 minutes (multiple transfers would be required)<ref name=\"dailymailapril12\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1375790/Saudi-Royal-family-plans-mile-high-building.html|title=Mile-high business hub: Saudi Royal family plans \u00a312billion building so tall it will take 12 MINUTES to reach top by lift|publisher=Dailly Mail|date=12 April 2011|accessdate=9 August 2011|location=London}}</ref> in a typical elevator and five minutes in a high-speed elevator.<ref name=\"singularityhubmarch2011\" /> Adrian Smith denied that he was a part of any of the earlier designs, which had been purported in the media.<ref name=\"wiredapril11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2011-04/11/mile-high-tower|title=Saudi Arabia's mile-high Kingdom Tower gets green-lit|date=11 April 2011|publisher=Wired.co.uk|author=Mark Brown|accessdate=6 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723225443/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2011-04/11/mile-high-tower|archive-date=23 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> One source even corrected its article and clarified the misunderstanding.<ref name=\"dviceapril72011\">{{cite web|url=http://dvice.com/archives/2011/04/kingdom-tower-w.php|title=Kingdom Tower will make the Burj Khalifa look short, reach one mile up|publisher=[[Dvice.com]]|author=Wong, Raymond|date=7 April 2011|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Contractors selected ===\nIn early August 2011, the [[Binladin Group]] was chosen as the main construction contractor with the signing of an SR4.6&nbsp;billion ({{US$|1.23 billion}}) contract,<ref name=\"wallstreetjournalaugust3\" /> which is less than it cost to build the Burj Khalifa (US$1.5&nbsp;billion).<ref name=\"constructionweekcheap\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13451-kingdom-tower-cheaper-to-build-than-burj-khalifa/|title=Kingdom Tower cheaper to build than Burj Khalifa|author=CW Staff|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|date=4 August 2011|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> New renderings were revealed, and on 2 August it was widely reported that the project was a go at the {{convert|1000|m|ft|abbr=on|0}} height{{ref label|note01|A|c}} with a building area of {{convert|530000|m2|ft2|0}},{{ref label|note02|B|b}}<ref name=\"economictimesaugust2\">{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/et-cetera/kingdom-holding-co-signs-12-billion-deal-with-saudi-binladen-group-to-build-worlds-tallest-tower/articleshow/9456039.cms|title=Kingdom Holding Co signs US$1.2&nbsp;billion deal with Saudi Binladen Group to build world's tallest tower|date=2 August 2011 |work=The Economic Times |accessdate=2 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"tradenewswireaugust2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tradenewswire.net/2011/binladen-group-awarded-1-2bn-contract-awarded-to-build-worlds-tallest-tower/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120419001107/http://www.tradenewswire.net/2011/binladen-group-awarded-1-2bn-contract-awarded-to-build-worlds-tallest-tower/|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 April 2012|title=Binladen Group Awarded $1.2bn Contract Awarded to Build World's Tallest Tower|work=Trade Newswire|date=2 August 2011|accessdate=2 August 2011}}</ref> and will take 63 months to complete.<ref name=\"arabnewsaugust2\" /> The announcement of the main construction contract signing caused Kingdom Holding Company's stock to jump 3.2% in one day,<ref name=\"bloombergstock\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-02/kingdom-holding-s-stock-jumps-on-contract-for-record-high-tower.html|title=Kingdom Holding's Stock Jumps on Contract for Record-High Tower|author=Zahra Hankir|date=2 August 2011|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=2 August 2011}}</ref> in addition to KHC already having reported a 21% rise in second-quarter net profit.<ref name=\"financialtimesaugust\">{{cite web|url=http://ft.com/cms/s/0/71eef532-bcf6-11e0-bdb1-00144feabdc0.html|title=Saudi Arabia plans world's tallest tower|author=Abeer Allam|publisher=[[Financial Times]]|date=2 August 2011|accessdate=4 August 2011}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Also, for the first time, architects Gordon Gill and Adrian Smith officially announced their involvement in the project.<ref name=\"smithaugust2\">{{cite press release | url=http://smithgill.com/#/news/kingdom_tower_announcement/|title=AS+GG Designs Kingdom Tower, to Be the World's Tallest Building|date=2 August 2011| publisher=Adrian Smith + Gordon Gill Architecture |accessdate=3 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 August 2012, it was announced that the [[landscape design|landscaping contract]] for the Jeddah Tower was to be awarded to Landtech Designs, a US-based company, who will be responsible for irrigating {{convert|8.5|acre|ha|order=flip}} of green space by using the latest technology in sustainable irrigation. The supply of water to irrigate the green space would be collected through rainwater.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-18126-landtech-wins-kingdom-tower-irrigation-contract/|title=Landtech wins Kingdom Tower irrigation contract|author=CW Staff|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://landtechdesign.com/2012/08/landech-to-design-irrigation-system-for-kingdom-tower-to-be-the-worlds-tallest-building/|title=Landech to Design Irrigation System for Kingdom Tower, Soon to be the World's Tallest Building|work=Landtech Design}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 September 2012, it was announced that financing for the Jeddah Tower was complete. Talal Al Maiman, chief executive officer and managing director of Kingdom Real Estate Development Co. said in an interview \"We have all the investors, all the finance, all the money we need,\" Al Maiman said. \"It took us beyond 20 months to convince investors, working every detail and aspect of financing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/property/general/kingdom-tower-financing-complete-1.1079352 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-10-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001203020/http://gulfnews.com/business/property/general/kingdom-tower-financing-complete-1.1079352 |archivedate= 1 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn 10 October 2012, Kingdom Holding awarded contracts totalling $98&nbsp;million. Kingdom Holding Co. has signed a deal with Subul Development Company for the sale of land in the Kingdom Riyadh Land project for $66.5&nbsp;million. The Kingdom Riyadh Land project, a mixed-use commercial and residential development, will generate more than $5.33&nbsp;billion of total investment and will house up to 75,000 people. The final master plan contract was awarded to Omrania & Associates and Barton Willmore.<ref name=\"USSA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.us-sabc.org/custom/news/details.cfm?id=1356|title=Kingdom Holding Awards Contracts Worth $98 Million|publisher=U.S.-Saudi Arabian Business Council|date=10 October 2012|accessdate=7 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108013729/http://www.us-sabc.org/custom/news/details.cfm?id=1356|archive-date=8 November 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bauer, a German Foundations equipment manufacturer and contractor was awarded a US$32&nbsp;million contract to support the initial phases of construction of the Jeddah Tower. This includes the installation of 270 bored piles with diameters of 1.5 metres and 1.8 metres. The enabling works are expected to begin before the end of 2012 and take about 10 months to complete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khl.com/magazines/international-construction/detail/item79730/Bauer-awarded-Kingdom-Tower-contract|title=Bauer awarded Kingdom Tower contract \u2013 KHL Group|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 February 2013, the Jeddah Economic Company (JEC) announced that it had appointed an [[EC Harris]]/[[Mace (construction company)|Mace]] joint venture team to project manage the iconic Jeddah Tower project. The team will be providing project, commercial and design management for the Jeddah Tower development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echarris.com/reference/news/kingdom_tower.aspx|title=We are now Arcadis|publisher=}}</ref> CEO of JEC, Waleed Abduljaleel Batterjee said that the reason Mace was hired is to use the same team that worked for [[The Shard]] in London. On the other hand, EC Harris also has a long list of projects in the region including the Grand Millenium Al-Wahda Hotel, [[Abu Dhabi]]'s largest hotel complex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingdomtowerskyscraper.com/EC-Harris-and-Mace-will-manage-Kingdom-Tower-project.html|title=EC Harris and Mace will manage Kingdom Tower project|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 April 2013, news was reported that the Saudi Water Company had signed a 2.2&nbsp;billion-riyal ($587&nbsp;million) supply deal with Jeddah Economic Co. for the Jeddah tower project. The 25-year agreement to supply 156,000 cubic metres of treated and drinking water a day, enough for 62 Olympic-size pools, was signed by the chief executive of the Jeddah-based developer, Waleed Batraji, and Loay al-Musallam, head of National Water Company.<ref name=\"BloombergBusiness\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-04-29/saudi-water-company-signs-587-million-jeddah-tower-deal|title=Saudi Water Company Signs $587 Million Jeddah Tower Deal|author=Deema Almashabi|date=29 April 2013|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Construction begins ===\nConstruction started on 1 April 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/emaar-considering-tower-higher-than-1km-tall-kingdom-tower-2013-05-01-1.504820|title=Emaar 'considering' tower higher than 1km-tall Kingdom Tower|author=Staff|work=Emirates 24-7}}</ref> Piling was completed in December 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingdom.com.sa/jeddah-economic-company-board-of-directors-appoints-new-ceo-jec-announces-completion-of-pilling-of-tallest-tower-in-the-world|title=Jeddah Economic Company Board of Directors Appoints New CEO JEC Announces Completion of Pilling of Tallest Tower in the World|date=4 December 2013|publisher=Kingdom Holdings|accessdate=9 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215020859/http://www.kingdom.com.sa/jeddah-economic-company-board-of-directors-appoints-new-ceo-jec-announces-completion-of-pilling-of-tallest-tower-in-the-world|archive-date=15 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Above ground construction commenced in September 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url =http://www.ctbuh.org/News/GlobalTallNews/tabid/4810/Category/37/language/en-US/Saudi-Arabia.aspx|title =Jeddah's Kingdom Tower to use World's Tallest Construction Crane|last = |first = |date =19 September 2014|work  = |publisher =CTBUH|accessdate =9 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2017, the owner of Kingdom Holding Co, which owns 33% of the tower, and the chairman of the Saudi Binladen Group, which owns 17% and is the primary contractor, were arrested as part of the [[2017 Saudi Arabian purge]]. Construction of the tower continued,<ref>{{cite news|title=Jeddah Tower going ahead after Saudi corruption purge|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/construction/389437-jeddah-tower-going-ahead-after-saudi-corruption-purge|website=[[Arabian Business]]|publisher=[[ITP Media Group]]|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=23 April 2018|language=en|date=8 February 2018}}</ref> although some senior managers at Kingdom Holding were redirected to other projects.<ref name=Parasie>{{cite news|last1=Parasie|first1=Nicolas|last2=Said|first2=Summer|title=Crown Prince's Decision-Making Power Reaches Deep into Companies|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/crown-prince-takes-decision-making-power-over-saudi-arabias-biggest-businesses-1520856082|accessdate=23 April 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|date=12 March 2018|quote=At his Kingdom Holding conglomerate, Prince al-Waleed and his team remain nominally in charge. But the Saudi government demonstrated its new influence in February when it ordered some of his senior managers to leave his biggest new project, Jeddah Tower, slated to be the tallest building in the world at over 3,000 feet high. The government directed them instead to work on construction of Neom, a new, high-tech Saudi city envisioned by Prince Mohammed, said people familiar with the directive, who understood it to be in line with the prince's wishes.}}</ref> In February 2018, Mounib Hammoud, CEO of Jeddah Economic City, said that construction is continuing and that they hoped to open the tower by 2020.<ref name=ict />\n\nIn March 2018, Kingdom Holding Company signed a deal with [[Orange Business Services]] to provide [[IT infrastructure|information and communication technology (ICT) infrastructure]] to Jeddah Tower.<ref name=ict>{{cite web |title=Smart services deal signed for $1.5bn Jeddah Tower project |url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/technology/391920-smart-services-deal-signed-for-15bn-jeddah-tower-project |website=ArabianBusiness.com |accessdate=11 June 2018 |language=en |date=23 Mar 2018}}</ref> On March 12 construction of the tower moved forward after the delay.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2018/03/12/worlds-tallest-skyscraper-jeddah-tower-adrian-smith-gordon-gill/|title=Construction of world's tallest tower restarts after delays|date=2018-03-12|work=Dezeen|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Building freeze ===\nIn mid-2018, all work was paused with the tower about one-third completed due to labor issues with a contractor following the [[2017\u201319 Saudi Arabian purge]].<ref name=\"CNNDavosInterview\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/videos/business/2019/01/21/saudi-arabia-kingdom-holding.cnn-business|publisher=CNN|title=CNN Interview with Company Chairman|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Kingdom Tower, Jeddah, render 2.jpg|thumb|left|135px|Detailed rendering of Jeddah Tower cut out to show floors]]\n\n=== Challenges ===\nSustainability of such a tall building would include issues such as vertical transportation limitations, with elevators only being able to go so far; building sway, caused by wind; and super column settling, which occurs because concrete tends to shrink as it hydrates and settles under load, whereas steel is dimensionally stable, thereby causing the floors to become uneven.<ref>Wells, Matthew. ''Skyscrapers: Structure and Design.'' Laurence King Publishing, 2005 (p. 154)</ref> Additionally, a very large core size is required in very tall buildings to support the structure as well as to house the [[Skyscraper design and construction#The elevator conundrum|large number of elevators needed]]. The core size consumes a significant amount of the space on the lower and middle floors.<ref name=\"independent2008\" /> One of the ways Jeddah Tower attempts to overcome these issues is with its smooth, sloped-exterior design, which, although more expensive to build, offers superior aerodynamic performance over \"stepped\" designs such as the Burj Khalifa, allowing it to have a more conservative core overall. This was determined by wind tunnel tests performed at Burj Khalifa. Jeddah Tower will also use copious stiffening materials to prevent the excessive sway that would otherwise make the occupants of upper floors nauseated on windy days,<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13tallorder\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13533-tall-order/|title=Tall order|author=Ephgrave, Oliver|date=13 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref> including very high strength concrete that will be up to several metres thick in certain parts of the core. This, along with the highly integrated steel frame and [[shear wall]]s, is also intended to prevent catastrophic failure of the structure in the event of a terrorist attack.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> Traditionally, the space consumed by elevators was considered to make a building become increasingly less profitable past 80 floors or so. More recently, it has been the advent of truly mixed-use design such as [[Shanghai Tower]] and Burj Khalifa, as well as improved building technology, that have outdated this rule of thumb, which generally applied to single use buildings.<ref name=\"nymagaugust14\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/arts/architecture/reviews/supertall-davidson-review-2011-8/|title=Higher: At the Skyscraper Museum, a reminder of why we keep reaching for the clouds|author=Davidson, Justin|date=14 August 2011|publisher=[[NY Mag]]|accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nLike Burj Khalifa, Jeddah employs a similar Y-shaped, triangular footprint which promotes stability<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> and increases window views,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/columnists/kamin/ct-ae-lake-point-tower-anniversary-0923-story.html |title=50 years later, Lake Point Tower is a singular achievement \u2014 and let's hope it stays that way |last=Kamin |first=Blair |work=Chicago Tribune |access-date=2018-09-23 |language=en-US}}</ref> as well as a tapering form,<ref name=\"constructionweektapering\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13521-experts-tapered-form-of-kingdom-tower-is-ideal/|title=Experts: tapered form of Kingdom Tower is ideal|author=Oliver Ephgrave|date=10 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=11 August 2011}}</ref> with the sheer height and wind being the biggest structural design challenge.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust7\" /> The smooth, sloped fa\u00e7ade of Kingdom Tower particularly induces a beneficial phenomenon known as \"wind vortex shedding.\"<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13hypertall\" /> Normally when wind swirls around the [[leeward]] side of a building, rushing in from both sides to fill the low pressure zone, it would create tornado like vortices, which would rock the building from side to side due to variations in pressure, direction and velocity. The dynamic fa\u00e7ade of Kingdom Tower, however, creates an infinite timing differential (whereas Burj Khalifa is limited by the number of steps) in air pressure exertion in any one particular direction, thus creating a more stable structure, as there is no broad area of outstanding pressure or depression at any given time.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> Put simply, a smooth taper is more aerodynamic than an irregular or jagged taper, while both are advantageous over rectangular geometries. At Jeddah Tower's height, it is considered essentially unfeasible to use a traditional square design.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13tallorder\" />\n\n=== External form ===\nThe triangular footprint and sloped exterior of Jeddah Tower is designed to reduce [[wind load]]s; its high surface area also makes it ideal for residential use.<ref name=\"khlaugust4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.khl.com/magazines/international-construction/detail/item66227/AS-GG-named-as-architect-for-1-km-Kingdom-Tower/|title=AS+GG named as architect for 1 km Kingdom Tower|author=Chris Sleight|date=4 August 2011|publisher=KHL Group|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> The overall design of the tower, which will be located near both the [[Red Sea]] and the mouth of the [[Obhur Creek]] (Sharm Ob'hur) where it widens as it meets the Red Sea,<ref name=\"azobuild\">{{cite web|url=http://www.azobuild.com/news.asp?newsID=14284|title=Kingdom Holding Contracts Construction of World's Tallest Tower|author=Joel Scanlon|publisher=AZoBuild|date=4 August 2011|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> as well as having frontage on a man-made waterway and harbour that will be built around it,<ref name=\"businessinsideraugust4\" /> is intended to look like a desert plant shooting upwards as a symbol of Saudi Arabia's growth and future, as well as to add prominence to Jeddah's status as the gateway into the holy city of [[Mecca]].<ref name=\"arabnewsaugust4\">{{cite web|url=http://arabnews.com/opinion/editorial/article483104.ece|title=Exciting project|publisher=Arab News|date=4 August 2011|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> The designer's vision was \"one that represents the new spirit in Saudi Arabia\" (Smith).<ref name=\"industryleadersaugust5\" /> The 23 hectare (57 acre) area around Jeddah Tower will contain public space and a shopping mall, as well as other residential and commercial developments, and be known as the Jeddah Tower Water Front District,<ref name=\"azobuild\" /> of which, the tower's site alone will take up {{convert|500000|m2|ft2|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13hypertall\" /> As with many other very tall skyscrapers, including the [[Kingdom Centre]] in [[Riyadh]], which is generally considered to have sparked the recent significant commercial developments around it in the district of [[Olaya (Riyadh)|Olaya]],<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13crown\" /> much of the intention of Jeddah Tower is to be symbolic as well as to raise the surrounding land value rather than its own profitability.<ref name=\"chicagotribuneaugust3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-xpm-2011-08-03-ct-biz-0803-chicago-architects-talles20110803-story.html|title=Chicago firm's design towers over the rest|author=Ryan Haggerty|date=21 October 2018|work=The Chicago Tribune|accessdate=3 August 2011}}</ref> To that effect, the tower's architect, Adrian Smith, said that the tower \"evokes a bundle of leaves shooting up from the ground; a burst of new life that heralds more growth all around it\".<ref name=\"industryleadersaugust5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.industryleadersmagazine.com/kingdom-tower-by-bin-laden-group-will-be-the-worlds-tallest-building/|title=Kingdom Tower by Bin Laden Group will be the World's Tallest Building|author=Vrushti Mawani|publisher=Industry Leaders Magazine|date=5 August 2011|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> Smith states that the tower will create a landmark in which it and the surrounding Jeddah Economic City are interdependent.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> Talal Al Maiman, a board member of Jeddah Economic Company, said, \"Jeddah Tower will be a landmark structure that will greatly increase the value of the hundreds of other properties around it in Jeddah Economic City and indeed throughout North Jeddah.\"<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13hypertall\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13530-city-of-the-hyper-tall/|title=City of the hyper tall|author=Matthews, Stuart|date=13 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref> The concept of profitability derived from building high density developments and malls around such a landmark was taken from the Burj Khalifa, where it has proven successful, as its surrounding malls, hotels and condominiums in the area known as [[Downtown Dubai]]<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13kingdombeckons\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13535-the-kingdom-beckons/|title=The Kingdom beckons|author=Hope, Gerhard|date=13 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref> have generated the most considerable revenue out of that project as a whole,<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13hypertall\" /> while the Burj Khalifa itself made little or no profit.<ref name=\"bdonlineaugust16\">{{cite web|url=http://bdonline.co.uk/5022966.article?|title=Should the Kingdom Tower be built?|date=16 August 2011|publisher=bdonline.com|accessdate=16 August 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Kingdom Tower sky terrace fair use.jpg|thumb|right|235px|A rendering showing the bottom of the unique, glass-floored, circular sky terrace that will overlook the Red Sea from over {{convert|2000|ft|m|0|order=flip}}]]\n\n=== Elevators ===\n[[File:Kingdom Tower balcony fair use.jpg|thumb|right|170px|The large, outdoor sky terrace will overlook the Red Sea and have an area of over {{convert|7500|ft2|m2|0|order=flip}}{{ref label|note04|D|a}}]]\n\nThe building will have a total of 59 elevators, five of which will be [[double-deck elevator]]s, as well as 12&nbsp;escalators. The elevators are made by the Finnish company [[Kone]]. It will also have the highest observation deck in the world, to which high speed elevators will travel at up to 10 metres (33&nbsp;feet) per second (slightly over {{convert|22|mph|abbr=on|0|order=flip|disp=x|, or }}) in both directions.<ref name=\"ASGGpdf\" /> The elevators cannot go faster because the change in air pressure at such a rapid speed could cause [[nausea]]; at {{convert|3000|ft|m|abbr=on|0|order=flip}}, the air pressure is over 10 kPa (1.5 psi) lower than at ground level (a 10% reduction in air pressure).<ref name=\"engineeringtoolboxairpressure\">{{cite web|url=http://www.engineeringtoolbox.com/air-altitude-pressure-d_462.html|title=Air Pressure and Altitude above Sea Level|publisher=The Engineering ToolBox|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> They must also be efficient so the cables are not unbearably heavy.<ref name=\"independent2008\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/features/milehigh-tower-wars-how-tall-is-too-tall-849088.html|title=Mile-high tower wars: How tall is too tall?|publisher=The Independent|date=18 June 2008|accessdate=6 August 2011|location=London}}</ref> Jeddah Tower will have three [[sky lobby|sky lobbies]] where elevator transfers can be made, and no elevator will go from the bottom to the highest occupied floor.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> No official floor count has been given; however, Smith stated in a television interview that it will be about 50 floors more than the Burj Khalifa, which has 163&nbsp;occupied floors,<ref name=\"ctbuhburjkhalifa\">{{cite web|url=http://buildingdb.ctbuh.org/?do=building&building_id=3|title=Burj Khalifa|publisher=[[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]]|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> leading to the inference that Jeddah Tower will have over 200&nbsp;floors.{{ref label|note05|E|b}}<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> The tower will also feature a large, roughly {{convert|30|m|ft|abbr=on}} diameter outdoor balcony, known as the sky terrace, on one side of the building for private use by the penthouse floor at level 157;<ref name=\"ASGGpdf\">{{cite web |url=http://smithgill.com/media/pdfs/Kingdom_for_web4.pdf |title=Kingdom Tower |publisher=Adrian Smith+Gordon Gill Architecture | format=.PDF |accessdate=3 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"worldarchitecturenewsaugust2\">{{cite news | author=Sian Disson |url=http://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/index.php?fuseaction=wanappln.projectview&upload_id=17218 |title=After months of rumour and suspicion, AS+GG confirms it is designing a $1.2bn, 1000+m tower in Jeddah |work=World Architecture News |date=2 August 2011 |accessdate=3 August 2011}}</ref> it is not the observation deck.<ref name=\"gizmodoaugust8\">{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/5828801/the-new-images-of-the-kingdom-tower-are-simply-insane/gallery/|title=The New Images of the World's Newest Tallest Building Are Simply Insane|author=Jesus Diaz|publisher=[[Gizmodo]]|date=8 August 2011|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref> It was originally intended to be a [[helipad]], but it was revealed to be an unsuitable landing environment by helicopter pilots.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\">{{cite web|url=http://chicagotonight.wttw.com/2011/08/04/architect-adrian-smith|title=4 August 2011 -Architect Adrian Smith -Chicago Tonight Video -WTTW|publisher=[[WTTW]]|date=4 August 2011|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> The building's large notches will also serve as shaded terraces for other areas of the tower and the exterior of the building will use low-conductivity glass to save on cooling costs by reducing thermal loads.<ref name=\"singularityhubaugust4\" /> In addition, the lower air density, exacerbated by the thin desert atmosphere, will cause the outdoor air temperature towards the top of the tower to be lower than the ground level air, which will provide natural cooling. There is also significantly more air flow (wind) at heights, which is very strong at one kilometre and had a large impact on the structural design of the tower.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> The Burj Khalifa actually takes in the cooler, cleaner air from the top floors and uses it to air condition the building.<ref name=\"timeoutdubaijanuary2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.timeoutdubai.com/knowledge/features/12706-khalifa-creators|title=Burj Khalifa: We speak to the people who made it possible|publisher=Time Out Dubai|author=Lucas, Becky|date=11 January 2010|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> Jeddah Tower will be oriented such that no fa\u00e7ade directly faces the sun; it will also use the condensate water from the air conditioning system for [[irrigation]] and other purposes throughout the building.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust27\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13708-kingdom-tower-to-mimise-stack-effect-says-eds/|title=Kingdom Tower to minimise stack effect, says ESD|author=Davids, Gavin|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|date=27 August 2011|accessdate=27 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nTo overcome elevator issues, the tower will use its large number of efficient elevators as well as its three [[sky lobby|sky lobbies]], which allows transfers to be made between elevators serving a specific area with no elevator being overburdened. Much was learned from Burj Khalifa that helped with the design of Jeddah Tower<ref name=\"constructionweektapering\" /> not only structurally, but in methods for designing practical mechanical, electrical, and plumbing (MEP) systems, as well as adhering to local regulations and international [[building code]]s.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust24\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13693-burj-khalifa-provides-kingdom-tower-mep-template/|title=Burj Khalifa provides Kingdom Tower MEP template|author=Davids, Gavin|date=24 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref> Despite all the physical challenges, Adrian Smith states that practicality is still the greater challenge over structural durability, even in such super-tall designs, and that as with all buildings, Jeddah Tower's form was primarily derived respective of what the building's uses would be, then in accordance with the structural factors that would have to be considered to deliver it.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> [[Orange S.A.]] are designing the [[Information and communications technology|information and communications]] infrastructure of the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/sectors/technology/digital-transformation-is-key-to-future-development-1.2204217|title=Digital transformation is \u2018key to future development\u2019|last=Reporter|first=Naushad K. CherrayilStaff|date=12 April 2018|website=Gulfnews.com|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Internal systems ===\nChicago-based<ref name=\"investigesd\">{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=4393963|title=Environmental Design Systems, Inc.|publisher=Bloomerg|year=2011|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> Environmental Systems Design, Inc. will provide mechanical, plumbing, electrical and fire protection engineering,<ref name=\"businesswireaugust5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110805005139/en/ESD-Designing-Building-Systems-Kingdom-Tower|title=ESD Designing Building Systems for Kingdom Tower|publisher=Business Wire|date=5 August 2011|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> as well as teledata, audio/visual, security systems, and acoustics.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust9\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13502-kingdom-tower-esd-wins-building-systems-contract/|title=Kingdom Tower: ESD wins building systems contract|author=Hannah-Farah Abdulla|date=9 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=9 August 2011}}</ref> Langan International will be responsible for [[geotechnical engineering]] as well as some ground level site work such as [[transportation engineering]] and parking,<ref name=\"langanwebsite\" /> including the design of the proposed 3,000\u20134,700 car underground parking garage<ref name=\"langanpdf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.langan.com/web/tour/pdf/1502|title=Portfolio (PDF)|year=2011|publisher=Langan International|accessdate=5 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929031557/http://www.langan.com/web/tour/pdf/1502|archive-date=29 September 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> that will be located near, but not under the tower for terrorism reasons.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> Langan also designed the tower's foundation, which has to be able to support the tower despite the less than optimal subsurface conditions, such as soft rock and permeable coral, which could cause the piles to settle.<ref name=\"prnewswireaugust16\">{{cite news|url=http://prnewswire.com/news-releases/langan-international-designs-foundation-for-worlds-tallest-tower-127864738.html|title=Langan International Designs Foundation for World's Tallest Tower|date=16 August 2011|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=16 August 2011}}</ref> Thornton Tomasetti has provided the structural engineering for two of the previous world's tallest building title holders, the [[Petronas Towers]] in Kuala Lumpur, and the [[Taipei 101]] in Taiwan, as well as the under construction [[Ping An Finance Centre]] in [[Shenzhen]], which will be the second tallest building in China after completion.<ref name=\"newswireaugust2\" /> [[Saudi Binladin Group]] is the largest construction firm in the Middle East, with over 35,000 workers and hundreds of projects. They recently constructed the topped-out {{convert|1972|ft|m|0|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[Abraj Al-Bait]] Clock Tower in Mecca, which is the tallest building in Saudi Arabia and third tallest in the world, as well as the largest skyscraper in the world by floor area and volume. Aside from buildings, the firm has also constructed many major infrastructure projects, such as the [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|King Abdulaziz (Jeddah) International Airport]] expansion and the {{convert|775|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} six lane Al Qassim Expressway through Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust16rollcall\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13592-role-call/2/|title=Roll call|author=CW staff|date=16 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=16 August 2011}}</ref> Saudi Binladin Group is owned by the family of the late al-Qaeda leader [[Osama bin Laden]].<ref name=\"newsfeedresearcher\">{{cite web|url=http://newsfeedresearcher.com/data/articles_b32/tower-kingdom-saudi.html |title=Saudi prince developing world's tallest building |publisher=NewsFeed Researcher |date=3 August 2011 |accessdate=9 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014161147/http://newsfeedresearcher.com/data/articles_b32/tower-kingdom-saudi.html |archivedate=14 October 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> As a result, it has sparked some minor media buzz.<ref name=\"chicagodailyheraldaugust7\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20110807/business/708079963/|title=Alwaleed hires Saudi Binladin to build world's tallest tower|author=Bloomberg News|date=7 August 2011|publisher=[[Chicago Daily Herald]]|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> When asked his thoughts about this in an interview, Adrian Smith simply stated that they are the largest construction firm in the Middle East, most significant work in Saudi Arabia was done by them, and that it is a very large family that shouldn't be stereotyped by one of its members.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> Furthermore, in January 2012, New York City judge [[George B. Daniels]] ruled that no charges could be filed against SBG to repay the victims of 9/11 as there is no evidence of the construction firm financially supporting bin Laden after he was removed as a shareholder following the [[1993 World Trade Center bombing|1993 World Trade Centre bombing]].<ref name=\"nochargesbinladen\">{{cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/01/11/2584568/ny-judge-drops-binladen-group.html |title=NY judge drops Binladen Group as 9/11 defendant |date=11 January 2012 |publisher=[[The Miami Herald]] |author=Neimeister, Larry |accessdate=11 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121202128/http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/01/11/2584568/ny-judge-drops-binladen-group.html |archivedate=21 January 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n=== Economic viability ===\nIn addition to its primary functions, the building is slated to include a significant amount of retail as well as a wide variety of other unique amenities with the intention that it functions as a nearly self-sustaining entity, approaching the concept of a \"[[vertical city]]\".<ref name=\"businessinsideraugust4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/waleeds-mega-tower-is-even-cooler-than-you-think-2011-8|title=Waleed's Saudi Mega Tower is Even Cooler Than You Think|author=Jeffery Townson|publisher=[[The Business Insider]]|date=3 August 2011|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> The building's design has been applauded as simple and feasible, yet bold, brilliantly sculpted, and high-tech,<ref name=\"worldarchitecturenewsaugust2\" /> with AS + GG describing it as \"an elegant, cost-efficient and highly constructible design.\"<ref name=\"khlaugust4\" /> The estimated construction cost of US$1.23&nbsp;billion, which is less than that of the Burj Khalifa (US$1.5&nbsp;billion), can be attributed to cheap labour in the Middle East, particularly Saudi Arabia, and that three shifts will work around the clock to expedite the process.<ref name=\"constructionweekcheap\" /> Construction costs have also declined since the global financial crisis.<ref name=\"arabianbusinessaugust15\">{{cite web|url=http://arabianbusiness.com/no-hurdle-kingdom-tower-hitting-2km-415705.html|title=No hurdle to Kingdom Tower hitting 2km|author=Staff writer|date=15 August 2011|publisher=ArabianBusiness.com|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, a report by consultancy EC Harris found that Saudi Arabia is the cheapest country in the Middle East to build in, half as expensive as [[Bahrain]], and 34% cheaper than the [[United Arab Emirates]], where Burj Khalifa is located.<ref name=\"arabbusinesscheaper\">{{cite web|url=http://arabianbusiness.com/kingdom-tower-cheaper-build-than-burj-khalifa-414170.html|title=Kingdom Tower cheaper to build than Burj Khalifa|publisher=Arab Business|date=4 August 2011|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> The future towers' site is located in very close proximity to [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|King Abdulaziz (Jeddah) International Airport]], whose runways nearly align with the towers' site, which will have an effect on the airspace.<ref name=\"businessinsideraugust4\" /> While skyscraper experts have stated that towers well over one kilometre, even two kilometres (6,562 feet) high, are technically feasible, physical sustainability and practicality issues come into play in towers of this height.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13463-skyscraper-expert-says-2km-tower-is-now-possible/|title=Skyscraper experts say 2km tower is now possible|author=Oliver Ephgrave|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|date=4 August 2011|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> As for physical restraints, Bart Leclercq, head of structures for WSP Middle East recently said, \"I truly believe that 1 mile, 1.6 kilometres, is within range. Over that, it may be possible if there are improvements in concrete quality. But 2&nbsp;km is too big a figure; it's just a step too far at the moment.\"<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13tallorder\" />\n\n==Impact==\nThere is an impending [[real estate bubble|real estate boom]] in Saudi Arabia, with increasing demand and rising prices due to high population growth and a short supply of housing, which may include a demand for high-end luxury units, such as those in Jeddah Tower. To boost growth, the Saudi Arabian government is going to invest US$67&nbsp;billion (SR251&nbsp;billion) in building 500,000&nbsp;homes throughout the country.<ref name=\"gulfnewsmidnight\">{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/property/saudi-real-estate-market-poised-for-boom-1.847379|title=Saudi real estate market poised for boom|date=5 August 2011|author=Aya Lowe|publisher=Gulf News|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> According to Saudi officials, about 900 new homes are needed a day to meet the demand of the rapidly growing population, which has nearly quadrupled in the past four decades.<ref name=\"hautelivingaugust10\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hauteliving.com/2011/08/the-kingdom-tower-to-overtake-burj-khalifa-as-dubais-tallest-tower/|title=The Kingdom Tower To Overtake Burj Khalifa As Dubai's Tallest Tower|author=Mahbubani, Rhea|publisher=Haute Living|date=10 August 2011|accessdate=10 August 2011}}</ref> Jeddah Tower is also an attempt to diversify Saudi Arabia's economy, which, holding a quarter of the world's [[oil reserve]]s and being one of the founding [[OPEC]] states, is currently largely dependent on its [[crude oil]] exports,<ref name=\"singularityhubaugust4\">{{cite web|url=http://singularityhub.com/2011/08/04/saudi-arabia-begins-construction-of-world%E2%80%99s-tallest-building-the-kingdom-tower/|title=Saudi Arabia Begins Construction of World's Tallest Building \u2013The Kingdom Tower|author=Peter Murray|date=4 August 2011|publisher=Singularity Hub|accessdate=5 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807115627/http://singularityhub.com/2011/08/04/saudi-arabia-begins-construction-of-world%E2%80%99s-tallest-building-the-kingdom-tower/|archive-date=7 August 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> which accounts for nearly 75% of government revenues and 90% of exports. This generates enough income to support Saudi Arabia as a [[welfare state]],<ref name=\"welfarestate\">{{cite web|url=http://portal.mofa.gov.sa/Detail.asp?InSectionID=1516&InNewsItemID=1746|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824235352/http://portal.mofa.gov.sa/Detail.asp?InSectionID=1516&InNewsItemID=1746|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 August 2011|title=The Kingdom of Saudi Arabia -A Welfare State|author=Royal Embassy of Saudi Arabia London|publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs]]|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> which spends billions of dollars on job creation and housing for its lower income residents.<ref name=\"dailymailaugust9\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2024188/Kingdom-Tower-Stunning-new-images-worlds-tallest-tower-Saudi-Arabia.html?ito=feeds-newsxml|title=High and mighty: Stunning new images of world's tallest tower|author=Lee Moran|publisher=Daily Mail|date=9 August 2011|accessdate=9 August 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nJust as the Jeddah Tower will complement the Jeddah Economic City development that will be built around it, there are many infrastructure and revitalisation projects underway and planned throughout Saudi Arabia, such as the US$7.2&nbsp;billion (SR27.1&nbsp;billion) new airport terminal under construction at [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|King Abdulaziz (Jeddah) International Airport]],<ref name=\"googlenewsjanuary\">{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iaYHQfKsttfAgoHg0m006s46K4dA?docId=CNG.1ec18a5caf14b98341da0879e29e0574.7f1|title=Saudi begins building new $7.2 bn Jeddah airport|date=11 January 2011|publisher=[[Google News]]|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> that will complement the Jeddah Economic City as well as develop Saudi Arabia, which has been likened to a Third World country with crumbling infrastructure and widespread disasters, including severe flooding,<ref name=\"forbesaugust2\">{{cite news|url=https://blogs.forbes.com/jamesmarshallcrotty/2011/08/02/kingdom-tower-worlds-tallest-building-coming-to-saudi-arabia-is-real-education-soon-to-follow/|title=World's Tallest Building Coming to Saudi Arabia. Is Education Soon To Follow?|author=James Marshall Crotty|publisher=Forbes|date=2 August 2011|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> such as the flash floods in early 2011 that damaged 90% of the roads and over 27,000 buildings in Jeddah.<ref name=\"msnbcaugust2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/43988244|title=World's tallest building coming to Saudi Arabia|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=2 August 2011|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> According to a representative of [[Standard Chartered]], which invested US$75&nbsp;million in Saudi Binladin Group, Saudi Arabia is going to spend over US$400&nbsp;billion (SR1.5&nbsp;trillion) on infrastructure over the next few years.<ref name=\"gulfnewsaugust9\">{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/construction/standard-chartered-buys-equity-stake-in-saudi-bin-laden-unit-1.849093|title=Standard Chartered buys equity stake in Saudi Bin Laden unit|author=Bloomberg|publisher=Gulf News|date=8 August 2011|accessdate=9 August 2011}}</ref> According to reports by [[Citi Investment Research & Analysis]], $220&nbsp;billion worth of development, accounting for 36% of all construction spending in the [[MENA]] region, will be directly or indirectly beneficial to Jeddah Tower.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13kingdombeckons\" /> Jeddah Tower and City themselves are intended to set an example of green development, using modern technology and having a low [[carbon footprint]] relative to the number of people they will support.<ref name=\"bdonlineaugust16\" /> However, there is also an increasing problem of poor education levels in Arab countries due to a lack of spending in research and education, which it is argued should be invested in rather than building skyscrapers,<ref name=\"dawnaugust5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/2011/08/05/we-need-education-not-skyscrapers.html|title=We need education, not skyscrapers|date=5 August 2011|author=Khawaja Umer Farooq|publisher=Dawn.com|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> and that the tower is nothing more than a symbol of [[hubris]].<ref name=\"nymagaugust14\" /> It has even been likened to the [[Tower of Babel]].<ref name=\"winnipegfreepressaugust6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/opinion/fyi/the-world-has-forgotten-what-happened-in-babel-127059103.html?device=mobile&c=y|title=The world has forgotten what happened in Babel|author=Tom Oleson|publisher=[[Winnipeg Free Press]]|date=6 August 2011|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, economists have found large new skyscrapers to be a negative economic indicator,<ref name=\"moneyweek2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moneyweek.com/news-and-charts/economics/a-recession-indicator-thats-hard-to-miss|title=A recession indicator that's hard to miss|publisher=[[MoneyWeek]]|date=11 February 2008|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref> with several instances of new tallest buildings being finished and opening into a bad economy,<ref name=\"theatlanticaugust8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2011/08/a-new-tallest-building-another-sign-of-economic-doom/243284/|title=A New Tallest Building, Another Sign of Economic Doom|author=Rebecca J. Rosen|publisher=[[The Atlantic]]|date=8 August 2011|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref> as they generally start during a financial boom when money is easy and investment is strong, but do not finish until the bubble has burst. Examples include the [[Singer Building]] and [[Metropolitan Life Insurance Company Tower|Metropolitan Life Insurance Building]] after the [[Panic of 1907]], [[40 Wall Street]], the [[Chrysler Building]] and the [[Empire State Building]] built during the [[Great Depression]], the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] and [[Sears Tower]] built during the 1970s economic downturn, the [[Petronas Towers]] built during the [[1997 Asian financial crisis|Asian Crisis]] of the late 1990s and the Burj Khalifa built during the [[Great Recession]].<ref name=\"marketurbanism2008\">{{cite web|url=http://marketurbanism.com/2008/08/26/skyscrapers-as-economic-indicators/|title=Skyscrapers as Economic Indicators|date=26 August 2008|publisher=Market Urbanism|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref> Much of the study on this phenomenon was done in 1999 by Andrew Lawrence, a research director at [[Deutsche Bank]] who created the \"skyscraper index,\" originally as a joke; however, it illustrated the observation that many of the world's tallest buildings have been built on the eve of financial collapse.<ref name=\"chicagomagaugust11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/The-312/August-2011/The-Kingdom-Tower-Skyscraper-for-the-Next-Financial-Collapse/|title=The Kingdom Tower: Skyscraper for the Next Financial Collapse?|author=Moser, Whet|date=11 August 2011|accessdate=11 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\nThe developers' theory is that the international attention gained through large developments and having the world's tallest building will incur [[gentrification]] of the country<ref name=\"arabianomics\">{{cite web|url=http://arabianomics.com/2011/04/15/%E2%80%98world%E2%80%99s-tallest-building%E2%80%99-crown-is-coming-to-saudi-arabia/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429061811/http://arabianomics.com/2011/04/15/%E2%80%98world%E2%80%99s-tallest-building%E2%80%99-crown-is-coming-to-saudi-arabia/|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 April 2014|title='World's Tallest Building' Crown is Coming to Saudi Arabia|publisher=Arabianomics|date=15 April 2011|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> and even be a financial success in the long run. Rory Olcayto, deputy editor of ''The Architects\u2019 Journal,'' said \"The race to build the highest skyscraper is quite futile; where do you stop? These buildings are a symbol of an old-fashioned way of thinking,\"<ref name=\"singularityhubaugust4\" /> while architect Adrian Smith, the designer of the tower, states, \"...this tower symbolizes the Kingdom as an important global business and cultural leader, and demonstrates the strength and creative vision of its people. It represents new growth and high-performance technology fused into one powerful iconic form.\"<ref name=\"industryleadersaugust5\" /> However, Bob Sinn, principal engineer at Thornton Tomasetti, stated that the practical challenges of building very tall buildings are greater than the structural challenges.<ref name=\"constructionweekchallenges\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13529-engineer-kingdom-tower-is-practical-challenge/|date=11 August 2011|title=Engineer: Kingdom Tower is practical challenge|author=Oliver Ephgrave|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=11 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n\"We intend [Jeddah] Tower to become both an economic engine and a proud symbol of the kingdom's economic and cultural stature in the world community,\" said Talal Al Maiman, a board member of both Kingdom Holding Company and Jeddah Economic Company.<ref name=\"msnbcaugust2\" /> He continued, \"We envision [Jeddah] Tower as a new iconic marker of Jeddah's historic importance as the traditional gateway to the holy city of Mecca.\"<ref name=\"singularityhubaugust4\" /> The project's primary proponent, [[Prince Al-Waleed]] said, \"Building this tower in Jeddah sends a financial and economic message that should not be ignored. It has a political depth to it to tell the world that we Saudis invest in our country.\"<ref name=\"wallstreetjournalaugust3\" />\n\n[[Alain Robert]], also known as the French Spiderman, expressed his willingness to climb Jeddah Tower after completion if he were given official approval, despite the fact that he would be well into his fifties. When he heard that it might be up to 1,600 metres, he said, \"That doesn't make much sense,\" but he said that if the height were 1,000 metres, then it would be achievable.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust10\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13514-french-spiderman-up-for-challenge-of-kingdom-tower/|title=French spiderman up for challenge of Kingdom Tower|author=Carlin Gerbich|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|date=10 August 2011|accessdate=10 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Jeddah Tower Building Progress 2016-04-14 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Construction site as seen from a plane, April 2016]]\nWhile the official construction estimate is five years and three months (63 months), others calculate that it will take significantly longer, over seven years, based on the duration of Burj Khalifa's construction,<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13458-how-long-will-kingdom-tower-take-to-construct/|title=How long will Kingdom Tower take to construct?|author=Stuart Matthews|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|date=3 August 2011|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> which was over six years (with the help of CQC Department).\n\n[[Geotechnical investigation]] (soil testing) took place in 2008. Work on the foundation was scheduled to begin towards the end of 2012.<ref name=\"Bauer\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bauer.de/en/investor_relations/releases/press/2012_10_08_kingdomtower.html |title=BAUER Group again provides foundations for world's tallest building in Saudi Arabia |publisher=Bauer group |accessdate=14 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013010552/http://www.bauer.de/en/investor_relations/releases/press/2012_10_08_kingdomtower.html |archivedate=13 October 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Statements that construction would soon begin were made starting in 2008. In August 2011, the start of construction was slated as \"no later than December,\"<ref name=\"chicagotribuneaugust3\" /> with some saying \"immediately,\" and that construction was imminent.<ref name=\"singularityhubaugust4\" /> This meant the tower was expected to be completed in 2017, though at that time it was also possible that it could still have been completed by the date the media continued to publish, which was the prior estimate of late 2016.<ref name=\"hautelivingaugust10\" /> Only if construction had begun promptly and gone smoothly could a late 2016 completion have been achieved.<ref name=\"globestaugust11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globest.com/news/1975_1975/middleeast/313018-1.html|title=JEC ASSEMBLES TEAM FOR $1.2B TOWER|author=Carr, Robert|date=11 August 2011|publisher=Globest.com|accessdate=11 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927182401/http://www.globest.com/news/1975_1975/middleeast/313018-1.html|archive-date=27 September 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDesigns for the foundation were in place by early August 2011 and the contract for the [[piling]] was tendered.<ref name=\"khlaugust4\" /> On 16 August 2011, Langan International officially announced their involvement and that the foundation and piling had to be uniquely designed to overcome subsurface issues such as soft [[bedrock]] and [[Porosity|porous]] coral rock, which normally could not support a skyscraper without settling.<ref name=\"prnewswireaugust16\" /> The foundation is similar to that of the Burj Khalifa, but larger; it is expected to average around {{convert|4.5|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} deep with a concrete pad of area around {{convert|7500|m2|ft2|abbr=on}}. The concrete must have low [[Permeation|permeability]] to keep out corrosive [[Seawater|salt water]] from the Red Sea. Its depth and size are also considered to be an indicator of what the tower's final height will be.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust14higherandfaster\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13534-higher-and-faster/|title=Higher and faster|author=White, Stephen|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|date=14 August 2011|accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref> The piles will be up to {{convert|200|m|ft|abbr=on}} deep and the pad over {{convert|90|m|abbr=on}} across, yet the building, which will weigh over {{convert|900000|t}}, is expected to settle. The idea is that it settles evenly enough so that the building doesn't tip or put undue stress on the [[superstructure]]. Computer modelling programmes performed tests at the site to confirm that the foundation design would work.<ref name=\"huffingtonaugust25\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jacob-slevin/kingdom-tower-worlds-newe_b_935861.html|title=Kingdom Tower: World's Newest Tallest Building for 2016|author=Slevin, Jacob|publisher=Huffington Post|date=25 August 2011|accessdate=25 August 2011}}</ref> A later design for the foundation, to be constructed by Bauer in 2013, calls for 270 bored piles up to {{convert|110|m|ft|abbr=on}} deep which have to be installed into the difficult ground conditions.<ref name=\"Bauer\" /> Some materials needed for the structure are {{convert|500000|m3|cuft|abbr=on}} of concrete and {{convert|80000|t|abbr=on}} of steel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kingdom Tower: How The World's Next Tallest Building Will Be Built|url=http://www.gizmodo.com.au/2014/04/how-the-worlds-next-tallest-building-will-be-built/|accessdate=1 May 2014|newspaper=Gizmodo}}</ref>\n\n===Progress of construction===\nThere was steady progress but in January 2018 building owner JEC halted structural concrete work. JEC has said they plan to restart construction in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|title=Owner May Ramp Up Construction of Jeddah Tower, Planned to Be Over 1 km|url=https://www.enr.com/articles/48077-owner-may-ramp-up-construction-of-jeddah-tower-planned-to-be-over-1-km?v=preview/|accessdate=12 Jan 2020}}</ref>\n<gallery widths=\"150\" heights=\"150\" mode=\"packed\">\nFile:KT Building Progress 10-JAN-2015 04.png|12th floor (10 January 2015)\nFile:KT Building Progress 07-Jun-2015 01.jpg|23rd floor (7 June 2015)\nFile:Jeddah Tower Building Progress as of 07-Jul-2016.jpg|44th floor (7 July 2016) (42+2) at night\nFile:Jeddah Tower Building Progress as of 13-Jul-2016 002.jpg|44th floor (13 July 2016) (42+2)\nFile:Jeddah Tower Building Progress as of 02-Dec-2016 001 (cropped).jpg|47th floor (2 December 2016) (45+2)\nFile:Jeddah tower (cropped).jpg|As of June 2017\nFile:Jeddah Tower August 2019 S.Nitzold.jpg|As of August 2019\n</gallery>\n\n== Floor directory ==\nIt is estimated that the Jeddah Tower will have just over 200 floors.{{ref label|note05|E|b}}<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" />\n{| Class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Floor || Purposes\n|- More + (construction in progress)\n| > 168 || Empty Spire\n|-\n| 168 (682 m)|| [[Tuned mass damper]]\n|-\n| 158\u2013167 || Building control machines\n|-\n| 157 (637m) || Observation deck, outdoor balcony\n|-\n| 155\u2013156 || Hotel, restaurants\n|-\n| 154 ||[[Four Seasons Hotel]]\n|-\n| 144\u2013153 || Hotel rooms\n|-\n| 141\u2013143 || Building control machines \n|-\n| 140 || Hotel rooms, refuge area\n|-\n| 127\u2013139 || Hotel rooms\n|-\n| 125\u2013126 || Hotel sky lobby\n|-\n| 115\u2013124 || Hotel rooms\n|-\n| 114 || Building control machines, refuge area\n|-\n| 104\u2013113 || Residence\n|-\n| 103 || Residence, refuge area\n|-\n| 94\u2013102 || Residence\n|-\n| 93 || Residential sky lobby \n|-\n| 90\u201392 || Building control machines\n|-\n| 89 || Refuge area\n|-\n| 80\u201388 || Offices\n|-\n| 79 || Refuge area\n|-\n| 67\u201378 || Offices\n|-\n| 65\u201366 || Sky lobby\n|-\n| 64 || Refuge area\n|-\n| 51\u201363 || Offices\n|-\n| 48\u201350 || Building control machines\n|-\n| 47 || Refuge area\n|-\n| 35\u201346 || Offices\n|-\n| 33\u201334 || Sky lobby\n|-\n| 29\u201332 || Building control machines\n|-\n| 18\u201328 || Offices\n|-\n| 16\u201317 || Building control machines\n|-\n| 6\u201315 || Offices\n|-\n| 3\u20135 || Building control machines\n|-\n| 2 || Shopping mall\n|-\n| 1 ||  Office lobby, serviced hotel lobby\n|-\n| B1 || Observatory entrance, shops, and restaurants\n|-\n| B2 || Parking, Building control machines\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of tallest buildings]]\n* [[List of future tallest buildings]]\n* [[The Illinois]]\n\n==Notes==\n: '''A.''' ^ {{note label|note01|A|a}}{{note label|note01|A|b}}{{note label|note01|A|c}}The actual height of the Burj Khalifa was not revealed until the opening ceremony. The developers of Jeddah Tower are similarly keeping the final height secret, stating only that it will be at least {{convert|1000|m|ft}} high. In a television interview for WTTW in Chicago, architect Adrian Smith stated that the tower will be a little over twice the height of the [[Burj Khalifa]], which is {{convert|828|m|ft}} high counting the antennas, suggesting that Jeddah Tower may be closer to {{convert|1600|m|ft}}. Some sources have suggested that Jeddah Tower will break Burj Khalifa's record by over {{convert|740|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13crown\"/> In 2014, online sources were using the number {{convert|1008|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"CW1008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-28168-kingdom-tower-to-complete-in-december-2018/|title=Kingdom Tower to complete in December 2018|date=14 May 2014|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|author=Gibbon, Gavin|accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n: '''B.''' ^ {{note label|note02|B|a}}{{note label|note02|B|b}}This figure has been referred to as the \"total building area\" in publications, which is probably another term for [[gross floor area]]; the actual usable floor space, which is what buildings are typically measured by, will presumably be less. This area has also been reported as {{convert|540000|m2|ft2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"telegraphaugust11\" />\n\n: '''C.''' ^ {{note label|note03|C|a}}This assumes a 2012 start date and the estimated completion time of 63 months.\n\n: '''D.''' ^ {{note label|note04|D|a}}Figure attained using the formula for the area of a circle (\u03c0''r''<sup>2</sup>) and the given value of {{convert|98|ft|abbr=on|0|order=flip}} as the diameter.\n\n: '''E.''' ^ {{note label|note05|E|a}}{{note label|note05|E|b}}No official floor count has been given; however, Adrian Smith said it will be about 50 floors taller than the (163-floor) [[Burj Khalifa]].<ref name=\"constructionweekinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13607-further-kingdom-tower-details-emerge/|title=Kingdom Tower to be 50 storeys taller than Burj|author=CW Staff|date=17 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=17 August 2011}}</ref> It is uncertain but probable that this counts unoccupied [[mechanical floor]]s in the spire. One source states, \"Tower residents and visitors will occupy 160 floors within the tower.\"<ref name=\"singularityhubaugust4\" /> In November 2010, an older kilometre-high design was said to contain over 200 floors.<ref name=\"constructionweeknovember2010\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Jeddah Tower}}\n* [http://www.kingdom.com.sa/ Kingdom Holding Company website]\n* [http://skyscrapercenter.com/building/kingdom-tower/2 Jeddah Tower] on the [[CTBUH]] Skyscraper Center\n* [http://www.foxnews.com/slideshow/world/2011/08/03/kingdom-tower/#slide=1 Slideshow image gallery of renderings] by [[Fox News]]\n* [https://twitter.com/jeddah_tower Jeddah Tower on Twitter]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fQUDYWm_iUk&t=6s Construction Timelapse] on YouTube\n\n{{Supertall skyscrapers | under-construction}}{{Portal|Saudi Arabia}}\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Jeddah]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures under construction in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Neo-futurism architecture]]\n[[Category:2020 in Saudi Arabia]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect-distinguish|Kingdom Tower|Jeddah TV Tower|Kingdom Centre|Mile High Illinois}}\n{{short description|Skyscraper under construction in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox Building\n| name = Jeddah Tower\n| native_name = \u0628\u0631\u062c \u062c\u062f\u0629\n| status = On Hold<ref name=\"CNNDavosInterview\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/videos/business/2019/01/21/saudi-arabia-kingdom-holding.cnn-business|publisher=CNN|title=CNN Interview with Company Chairman|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n| image = Jeddah Tower August 2019 S.Nitzold.jpg\n| caption = Jeddah Tower in August 2019\n| location = [[Jeddah]], Saudi Arabia\n| coordinates = {{coord|21.734063|39.082758|region:SA-02_type:landmark |display=title,inline}}\n| start_date = {{Start date|df=yes|2013|04|01}}\n| architect = [[Adrian Smith (architect)|Adrian D. Smith]], [[Adrian Smith + Gordon Gill Architecture]]\n| owner = Jeddah Economic Company;\tKingdom Real Estate Development\n| cost = [[Saudi riyal|SR]]10&nbsp;billion (US$10.23&nbsp;billion)<ref name=\"wallstreetjournalaugust3\">{{cite news | author=Summer Said | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424053111903341404576483540742054836?mod=WSJ_World_LEFTSecondNews |title=Saudis Plan World's Tallest Tower|date=3 August 2011| work=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=3 August 2011}}</ref> (preliminary)\n| floor_area = {{cvt|243,866|sqm}}\n| top_floor = {{cvt|668|m|ft|0}} (if completed as planned)\n| floor_count = 200+ (2 basements)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2015/jun/04/jeddahs-kingdom-tower-how-much-higher-can-skyscrapers-go-a-history-of-cities-in-50-buildings-day-50|title=Jeddah's Kingdom Tower: how much higher can skyscrapers go? A history of cities in 50 buildings, day 50|work=the Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/style/amp/jeddah-tower-saudi-arabia-new/index.html|title=Jeddah Tower: What does the world's next tallest skyscraper look like now?|work=CNN}}</ref>\n| references = <ref name=skyscraperCenter>{{cite web|url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/jeddah/kingdom-tower/2 |title=Jeddah Tower \u2013 The Skyscraper Center |publisher=Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat}}</ref><ref name=\"milehightowerssp\">{{cite web|url=http://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=82759|title=Mile-High Tower|publisher=[[SkyscraperPage]]|accessdate=10 August 2011}}</ref>\n| building_type = Mixed-use: office, hotel, residential, apartments, observation, retail\n| architectural_style = [[Neo-futurism]]<br>\n| structural_system = Reinforced concrete and steel, all-glass fa\u00e7ade\n| architectural = At least {{cvt|1000|m}}\n| roof = At least {{cvt|1000|m}}\n| observatory = {{cvt|652|m}}\n| elevator_count = 59 (55 single deck and 4 double deck),<ref name=skyscraperCenter/><ref>{{cite web|title=Kingdom Tower Jeddah, Saudi Arabia|url=http://smithgill.com/media/pdfs/Kingdom_for_web_7.pdf|publisher=Adrian Smith + Gordon Gill Architecture LLP|accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> made by [[KONE]]<ref>{{cite web|title=KONE wins order for Saudi Arabia's Kingdom Tower, the world's tallest building|url=http://www.kone.com/en/media/releases/kone-wins-order-for-saudi-arabia-s-kingdom-tower--the-world-s-tallest-building-2014-06-05.aspx|publisher=KONE Corporation|accessdate=23 August 2017}}</ref>\n| structural_engineer = [[Thornton Tomasetti]]\n| main_contractor = [[Saudi Binladin Group]]\n| image_size = \n| est_completion = 2020\n| opening = Unknown\n| engineer = Langan International (sub-grade and transportation planning)<ref name=\"langanwebsite\">{{cite web|title=Langan Website|url=http://www.langan.com/web/|publisher=Langan International|year=2011|accessdate=5 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806204935/http://www.langan.com/web/|archivedate=6 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| developer = Jeddah Economic Company (JEC)<ref name=\"emirates24/7august2.2\">{{cite news | url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/region/kingdom-tower-to-pip-reigning-champ-burj-khalifa-by-173m-2011-08-02-1.411064 | title=Kingdom Tower to pip reigning champ Burj Khalifa by 173m | work=Emirates 24/7 | date=2 August 2011 | accessdate=3 August 2011 | author=Nambiar, Sona | publisher=Dubai Media Incorporated}}</ref>\n| management = [[CBRE Group]]\n| stop_date = 25 January 2018 (Planned to start again in 2020)<ref> https://www.enr.com/articles/48077-owner-may-ramp-up-construction-of-jeddah-tower-planned-to-be-over-1-km}} </ref>\n| completion_date = \n}}\n\n'''Jeddah Tower''' ({{lang-ar|\u0628\u0631\u062c \u062c\u062f\u0629}}),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingdom.com.sa/jec-alinma-investment-in-an-sar-8-4-billion-real-estate-fund-deal-fund-objective-is-to-develop-jeddah-tower-and-the-jeddah-economic-city-infrastructure|title=8.4&nbsp;billion real estate deal objective is to develop Jeddah Tower and the Jeddah Economic City|publisher=Kingdom Holding Company|date=29 November 2015|accessdate=30 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151130183439/http://www.kingdom.com.sa/jec-alinma-investment-in-an-sar-8-4-billion-real-estate-fund-deal-fund-objective-is-to-develop-jeddah-tower-and-the-jeddah-economic-city-infrastructure|archive-date=30 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> previously known as '''Kingdom Tower''' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0645\u0644\u0643\u0629}}) and '''Mile-High Tower''' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0644}}), is a planned skyscraper on the north side of [[Jeddah]], [[Saudi Arabia]]. It is planned to be the world's first {{convert|1|km|ft|abbr=on|0}} high building, and the centrepiece and first phase of a development and tourist attraction known as [[Jeddah Economic City]].<ref name=\"meconstruction\">{{cite web|url=http://meconstructionnews.com/story/4705/saudis-kingdom-tower-how-worlds-tallest-building-will-benefit-jeddah |title=Saudi's Kingdom Tower: How world\u2019s tallest building will benefit Jeddah |date=24 June 2015|author=Jerusha Sequeira |publisher=[[CPI Media Group]] |website=MEConstructionNews.com|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nInitial plans called for a mile-high structure,<ref name=\"arabnewsaugust2\">{{cite news|url=http://arabnews.com/saudiarabia/article481836.ece |title=Kingdom Holding to build world's tallest tower in Jeddah |work=Arab News |date=3 August 2011 |accessdate=10 August 2011 |author=Khan, Ghazanfar Ali |author2=Abbas, Maher |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319084546/http://arabnews.com/saudiarabia/article481836.ece |archivedate=19 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> but the geology of the area proved unsuitable. The current design, created by American architect [[Adrian Smith (architect)|Adrian Smith]], who also designed [[Burj Khalifa]], incorporates many unique structural and aesthetic features. The creator and leader of the project is Saudi Arabian prince [[Al-Waleed bin Talal]],<ref name=\"alarabiya1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alarabiya.net/articles/2011/04/04/144136.html|title=Bin Talal remains richest Arab in 2011: report|author=Farid, Sonia|publisher=Alarabiya.net|date=4 April 2011|accessdate=10 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123074502/http://www.alarabiya.net/articles/2011/04/04/144136.html|archive-date=23 November 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Descendants of Ibn Saud|a grandson]] of [[Ibn Saud]], and nephew of the [[King of Saudi Arabia#Kings of Saudi Arabia (1932\u2013present)|Kings of Saudi Arabia]] before him. Al-Waleed is the chairman of [[Kingdom Holding Company]] (KHC),<ref name=\"businesswireaugust5\" /> which is a partner in the Jeddah Economic Company (JEC), which was formed in 2009 for the development of Jeddah Tower and City.<ref name=\"businesswireaugust5\" />\n\n==Overview==\nThe building has been scaled down from its initial one mile high (5,280&nbsp;ft) proposal, which was never fully designed, to a height of at least {{convert|1000|m|ft|0}} (the exact height is being kept private while in development, similar to the [[Burj Khalifa]]).{{ref label|note01|A|b}}<ref name=\"arabnewsaugust2\"/> At about one kilometre,<ref name=\"miamiheraldaugust7\">{{cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2011/08/07/v-print/2348937/worlds-tallest-tower-to-go-up.html#ixzz1UNEiWijY|title=World's tallest tower to go up in Saudi in 5 years|date=7 August 2011|author=[[The Associated Press]]|publisher=The [[Miami Herald]]|accessdate=7 August 2011}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Jeddah Tower would still be by far the [[List of tallest buildings and structures in the world|tallest building or structure in the world]] to date,<ref>{{cite news |author=AFP |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,23363844-25658,00.html |title=Saudi mile-high tower plan raises bar |work=The Australian |date=13 March 2008 |accessdate=3 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307043204/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,23363844-25658,00.html |archive-date=7 March 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> standing {{convert|180|m|ft|abbr=on|0|}} taller than the Burj Khalifa in [[Dubai]], United Arab Emirates.<ref name=\"chicagotribuneaugust2\" />\nJeddah Tower's {{Convert|50|ha|acre|adj=on}} plot with surrounding buildings will be the first of a three phase Jeddah Economic City development. The three phase project proposed for a large area of undeveloped waterfront land with an area of {{convert|5.2|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"telegraphaugust11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/saudiarabia/8678426/Saudi-skyscraper-facts-and-figures.html|title=Saudi skyscraper: facts and figures|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=11 August 2011|accessdate=11 August 2011|location=London}}</ref> It was originally planned to cover {{convert|23|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} and cost SR100&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"dailymailoctober2008\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1077109/Saudi-Arabia-build-worlds-tallest-building.html|publisher=Daily Mail|date=13 October 2008|title=Saudi Arabia to build world's tallest building|accessdate=19 October 2011|location=London}}</ref> The area is located roughly {{convert|20|km|abbr=on|0}} north of the port city of Jeddah. Jeddah Economic City was designed by [[HOK Architects]],<ref name=\"globestaugust11\" /> and is estimated to cost at least SR75&nbsp;billion (US$20&nbsp;billion) and take around ten&nbsp;years to build.<ref name=\"truthdiveaugust6\">{{cite web | url=http://truthdive.com/2011/08/06/worlds-tallest-tower-to-be-built-for-1-2-bn-in-saudi-arabia.html | title=World's tallest tower to be built for $1.2 bn in Saudi Arabia | publisher=TruthDive | date=6 August 2011 | accessdate=6 August 2011 | author=Devi, Kanchana | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321234147/http://truthdive.com/2011/08/06/worlds-tallest-tower-to-be-built-for-1-2-bn-in-saudi-arabia.html | archive-date=21 March 2012 | url-status=usurped | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe development is envisioned to grow into a new district of Jeddah.<ref name=\"metroaugust11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/news/872134-kingdom-tower-in-saudi-arabia-to-be-worlds-next-tallest-building|title=Kingdom Tower in Saudi Arabia to be world's next tallest building|author=Radnedge, Aidan|publisher=[[Metro.co.uk]]|date=11 August 2011|accessdate=11 August 2011}}</ref> The second phase of the project will be the infrastructure development needed to support the city, and the third phase has not yet been revealed.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13crown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13537-crown-of-the-kingdom/|title=Crown of the Kingdom|author=Roberts, Ben|date=13 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe focal point of the development and Jeddah Tower's primary use will be to house a [[Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts|Four Seasons hotel]], Four Seasons [[serviced apartment]]s, Class A office space, and luxury condominiums. The tower will also have the world's highest [[observatory]].<ref name=\"dezeen august 2\">{{cite web|last=Etherington|first=Rose|title=First image of world's tallest building, to be built in Jeddah|url=http://www.dezeen.com/2011/08/02/first-image-of-worlds-tallest-buildingto-be-built-in-jeddah/|date=2 August 2011|publisher=Dezeen|accessdate=2 August 2011}}</ref> Although the Jeddah Economic City plot is nearly isolated from the current urban core of Jeddah, no land tracts of such size were available closer to the city.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13crown\" /> Northward is generally considered the direction in which the city will spread in the future.\n\nThe primary designer of Jeddah Tower is Chicago based architect [[Adrian Smith (architect)|Adrian Smith]] of [[Adrian Smith + Gordon Gill Architecture]] (AS + GG),<ref name=\"chicagotribuneaugust2\">{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/breaking/chi-110802-kingdom-tower-pictures,0,2908125.photogallery |title=Kingdom Tower: Tallest of the tall |author= |date=2 August 2011 |work=The Chicago Tribune |accessdate=2 August 2011}}</ref> the same architect who designed the Burj Khalifa while he was working for [[Skidmore, Owings & Merrill]] (SOM),<ref name=\"gulfnews102010\">{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/property/gulf/tallest-tower-plan-in-jeddah-on-track-1.700123|title=Tallest tower plan in Jeddah on track|date=22 October 2010|work=Gulf News|accessdate=31 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101027103105/http://gulfnews.com/business/property/gulf/tallest-tower-plan-in-jeddah-on-track-1.700123|archivedate=27 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> for which he worked almost 40 years.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13king\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13532-king-of-skyscrapers/|title=King of skyscrapers|author=Ephgrave, Oliver|date=13 August 2011|accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref> AS + GG was formed in 2006 by Adrian Smith, Gordon Gill, and Robert Forest.<ref name=\"worldpropertychannelaugust3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldpropertychannel.com/international-markets/commercial-real-estate/kingdom-tower-tallest-building-in-the-world-adrian-smith-gordon-gill-architecture-saudi-arabia-skyscrapers-burj-khalifa-prince-alwaleed-bin-talal-bin-abdulaziz-alsaud-saudi-prince-asgg-king-abdullah-kingdom-holding-company-4618.php|title=Saudi Arabia's Kingdom Tower Announced, World's Newest Tallest Tower|author=Gerrity, Michael|date=3 August 2011|publisher=WorldPropertyChannel|accessdate=13 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930081758/http://www.worldpropertychannel.com/international-markets/commercial-real-estate/kingdom-tower-tallest-building-in-the-world-adrian-smith-gordon-gill-architecture-saudi-arabia-skyscrapers-burj-khalifa-prince-alwaleed-bin-talal-bin-abdulaziz-alsaud-saudi-prince-asgg-king-abdullah-kingdom-holding-company-4618.php|archive-date=30 September 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The development of the tower is being managed by Emaar Properties PJSC.<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-22/alwaleed-picks-burj-khalifa-architect-adrian-smith-to-design-kingdom-tower.html|title=Alwaleed Picks Burj Khalifa Architect Adrian Smith to Design Kingdom Tower |date=22 October 2010 |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=22 October 2010 |first=Arif |last=Sharif}}</ref> [[Thornton Tomasetti]] has been selected as the structural engineering firm,<ref name=\"newswireaugust2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/prince-alwaleed-signs-sr46billion-contract-for-worlds-tallest-1000-meters-tower-1st-phase-of-jeddah-development-126570338.html|title= Prince Alwaleed Signs SR4.6Billion Contract for World's Tallest 1,000 meters Tower 1st Phase of Jeddah Development |date=2 August 2011 |work=PR Newswire|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> and Environmental Systems Design, Inc. (ESD)<ref name=\"CWesd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13502-kingdom-tower-esd-wins-building-systems-contract/|title=Kingdom Tower: ESD wins building systems contract|date=9 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|author=Abdulla, Hannah-Farah|accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref> is a part of the AS + GG design team that serves as the building services engineering consultants.<ref name=\"urukiaaugust3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.urukia.com/kingdom-tower/|title=Kingdom Tower World's Tallest Skyscraper in Jeddah|publisher=Urukia Magazine|date=3 August 2011|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 August 2011, it was publicly announced by Kingdom Holding, the investment company, that a contract had been signed by [[Saudi Binladin Group]] (SBG), that construction was going to start soon, and that the tower was expected to take 63 months to complete.<ref name=\"wallstreetjournalaugust2\">{{cite news|url=https://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20110802-709579.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105064534/http://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20110802-709579.html |archive-date=5 January 2012 |title=Kingdom's Alwaleed: Tallest Tower To Provide Sustainable Profit |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=2 August 2011 |accessdate=2 August 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/kerryadolan/2011/08/02/saudi-prince-alwaleed-to-build-worlds-tallest-tower-with-bin-laden-group/#2715e4857a0b1c2bf4aa6de7 Saudi Prince Alwaleed To Build World's Tallest Tower With Binladen Group] Kerry A. Dolan, [[Forbes]], 2 August 2011 @ 01:04&nbsp;pm</ref><ref>[http://www.kingdom.com.sa/building-a-landmark-jeddah-tower-the-worlds-tallest-building Building a landmark: Kingdom Tower, The world\u2019s tallest building] Kingdom Holding Company. 26 December 2011</ref>\n\n[[Besix]] Group (Belgian Six Construct), which constructed the Burj Khalifa, was previously considered for the contract, but did not win, partially because SBG invested in Jeddah Economic Company (JEC),<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13471-besix-kingdom-towers-big-challenge-is-logistics/|title=Besix: Kingdom Tower's big challenge is logistics|author=Gerhard Hope|date=7 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> contributing SR1.5&nbsp;billion (US$400&nbsp;million) towards the development of the project,<ref name=\"saudibusinessaugust7\">{{cite web|url=http://arabianbusiness.com/kingdom-eyes-loans-cash-build-world-s-tallest-tower--414491.html|title=Kingdom eyes loans, cash to build world's tallest tower|publisher=Arabian Business|date=7 August 2011|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> and holding a 16.6 percent stake in Jeddah Economic Company.<ref name=\"dailymailaugust9\" /> Besix admitted in 2010 that they expected Binladin Group to win the contract.<ref name=\"constructionweeknovember2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-10206-besix-we-expect-binladin-to-win-kingdom-tower/|date=21 November 2010|title=Besix: we expect Binladin to win Kingdom Tower|author=Broomhall, Elizabeth|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> Jeddah Economic Company is a [[closed joint stock company]] (PJSC) formed in 2009 as a financial entity for Jeddah Tower and Jeddah Economic City. It is made up primarily of financiers (stakeholders) Kingdom Holding Company (33.35%), Abrar Holding Company (33.35%), which is owned by Samaual Bakhsh and businessman Abdulrahman Hassan Sharbately (16.67%), as well as the tower's own contractor, Saudi Binladin Group (16.63%).<ref name=\"earthtechlingaugust12\">{{cite web|url=http://www.earthtechling.com/2011/08/planned-green-skyscraper-really-really-tall/|title=Planned Green Skyscraper Really, Really Tall|author=DeFreitas, Susan|publisher=EarthTechling LLC|date=12 August 2011|accessdate=12 August 2011}}</ref> JEC's assets have a book value of nearly SR9&nbsp;billion, broken down between a [[Land banking|land bank]] of over {{convert|5300000|m2|ft2|0|abbr=on}} (the Jeddah Economic City plot) with a value of SR7.3&nbsp;billion that will be used as [[collateral (finance)|collateral]] to attain bank loans, and SR1.5&nbsp;billion in cash.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13crown\" /> Kingdom Holding is an [[investment company]] founded in 1980 and 95% owned by [[Al-Waleed bin Talal]]<ref name=\"albawabaaugust8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.albawaba.com/main-headlines/alwaleed-bin-talal-companies-build-tallest-tower-world-387307|title=Alwaleed bin Talal companies to build the tallest tower in the world|publisher=[[Al Bawaba]]|date=8 August 2011|accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref> that has assets valued at over $25&nbsp;billion, with interests in many major companies such as [[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney]], [[Pepsico]], [[Kodak]], [[Apple Computers|Apple]], [[Hewlett Packard]], [[Motorola]], [[Time Warner]], [[Newscorp]], Pinnacle Infotech Solutions and [[Citigroup]], as well as real estate in London through its Songbird Estates division.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust16rollcall\" />\n\n==Construction history==\nIn May 2008, [[geotechnical investigation|soil testing]] in the area cast doubt over whether the proposed location could support a skyscraper of the proposed one-mile height, and [[MEED]] reported that the project had been scaled back, making it \"up to {{convert|500|m|ft|0}} shorter.\"<ref name=\"tallestbuildingintheworld\">{{cite web | url=http://www.tallestbuildingintheworld.com/building_id_108_Mile+High+Tower+(working+name).php | title=Mile High Tower (working name) \u2013 Jeddah | publisher=Tallest Building in the World.com | accessdate=3 August 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716192034/http://www.tallestbuildingintheworld.com/building_id_108_Mile+High+Tower+%28working+name%29.php | archive-date=16 July 2011 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nReports in 2009 suggested that the project had been put on hold due to the [[Global financial crisis of 2008\u20132009]] and that [[Bechtel]] (the former engineering firm) was \"in the process of ending its involvement with the project.\"<ref name=menainfra>{{cite news|author=Timon Singh|url=http://www.menainfra.com/news/mile-high-tower/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130128165945/http://www.menainfra.com/news/mile-high-tower/|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 January 2013|title=Has the Mile High Tower been shelved?|work=MENA Infrastructure|publisher=GDS Publishing Ltd.|accessdate=11 January 2011}}</ref><ref name=stall>{{cite web|url=http://www.nce.co.uk/news/2009/02/saudi_milehigh_tower_latest_skyscraper_to_stall.html|title=Saudi mile-high tower latest skyscraper to stall|publisher=New Civil Engineer (Emap)|accessdate=23 February 2009}}</ref> Kingdom Holding Company quickly criticized the news reports, insisting that the project had not been shelved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/547358-kingdom-holding-says-tower-not-on-hold|title=Kingdom Holding says tower not on hold|work=Arabian Business|accessdate=23 February 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091126203038/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/547358-kingdom-holding-says-tower-not-on-hold|archive-date=26 November 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Architect selected ===\nIn March 2010, Adrian Smith of Adrian Smith + Gordon Gill Architecture (AS + GG) was selected as the preliminary architect (though they deny involvement in the earlier, mile-high designs).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ameinfo.com/226876.html |title=US firm to design world's tallest tower in Saudi |date=16 March 2010 |work=AMEnfo |accessdate=11 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322204608/http://www.ameinfo.com/226876.html |archivedate=22 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Later, when the proposal was more serious, they won a design competition between eight leading architectural firms including [[Kohn Pedersen Fox]], Pickard Chilton, Pelli Clarke Pelli, and [[Foster + Partners]], as well as the firm Smith formerly worked for [[Skidmore, Owings and Merrill]],<ref name=\"azobuild\" /> which was the final competitor in the competition before AS + GG was chosen.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> In addition to Burj Khalifa, Adrian Smith has designed several other recent towers; the [[Zifeng Tower]] in [[Nanjing]], China, the [[Trump International Hotel and Tower (Chicago)|Trump International Hotel & Tower]] in Chicago, and the [[Jin Mao Tower]] in Shanghai,<ref name=\"artinfoaugust5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artinfo.com/news/story/38286/bin-laden-group-plans-to-build-the-worlds-tallest-super-skyscraper-in-jeddah/|title=Bin Laden Group Plans to Build the World's Tallest Super Skyscraper in Jeddah|author=Janelle Zara|date=5 August 2011|publisher=Art Info|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> as well as the [[Pearl River Tower]] in [[Guangzhou]], China.<ref name=\"earchitectaugust2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.e-architect.co.uk/saudi_arabia/kingdom_tower_jeddah.htm|title=Kingdom Tower Jeddah, Saudi Arabia: to be the world's tallest building|publisher=e-architect|date=2 August 2011|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> The four buildings are all among the top eleven tallest in the world. Furthermore, the Pearl River Tower is a unique tower that was originally designed to use zero net energy by drawing all its needed power from [[wind power|wind]], [[solar power|sunlight]], and [[geothermal energy|geothermal mass]],<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13king\" /> though this design goal was not fully achieved.<ref name=\"Frechette-Gilchrist\">{{cite journal|last=Frechette|first=R|authorlink=|author2=Gilchrist, R|date=March 2008|title=Towards Zero Energy: A case study of the Pearl River Tower, Guangzhou, China|trans-title=|journal=Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat|volume=|issue=|pages=pg. 9|id=|accessdate=30 March 2015|url=http://ctbuh.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=%2bpedN46s7Es%3d&tabid=486&language=en-US/|publisher=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526235034/http://ctbuh.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=%2BpedN46s7Es%3D&tabid=486&language=en-US%2F|archive-date=26 May 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, the owners (Kingdom Holding Company) signed a development agreement with [[Emaar Properties]] PJSC. The final height of the building was questionable, but it was still listed to be over 1 kilometre.<ref>{{cite news | title=Emaar Sign Agreement For 1000m Tower | url=http://www.skyscrapernews.com/news.php?ref=2682 | work=Skyscrapernews | date=22 October 2010 | accessdate=2 August 2011}}</ref> Kingdom Holding said construction was progressing.<ref name=\"gulfnews102010\" /><ref>{{cite news |author=Blair Kamin |url=http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/theskyline/2010/10/chicago-architects-working-on-a-mile-high-tower-can-it-be-built-repeat-after-me-chicago-spire-.html |title=Saudi mega-tower designed by Chicago architects moving ahead |date=22 October 2010 |work=The Chicago Tribune |accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Approvals ===\nIn March and April 2011, several news agencies reported that the Mile-High Tower design had been approved at that height and that the building would cost almost US$30&nbsp;billion (SR112.5&nbsp;billion).<ref name=sydherald>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/milehigh-building-gets-approval-20110417-1djg4.html|title=The tallest building in the world|date=17 April 2011 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=21 April 2011}}</ref> This design was going to be drastically larger than the current design, with a floor area of {{convert|38000000|ft2|m2|abbr=on|0|order=flip }} and would have used futuristic wind aversion and energy producing technology for sustainability. It and the surrounding City would have had the ability to accommodate 80,000 residents and one million visitors,<ref name=\"singularityhubmarch2011\">{{cite web|url=http://singularityhub.com/2011/03/29/jeddah%E2%80%99s-kingdom-tower-world%E2%80%99s-tallest-building-given-the-go-ahead/|title=Jeddah's Kingdom Tower, World's Tallest Building Given the Go Ahead|author=Louie Helm|publisher=SingularityHub|date=29 March 2011|accessdate=9 August 2011|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120717213006/http://singularityhub.com/2011/03/29/jeddah%E2%80%99s-kingdom-tower-world%E2%80%99s-tallest-building-given-the-go-ahead/|archive-date=17 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> according to [[RIA Novosti]].<ref name=sydherald /> Many things were rumoured about the mile-high designs, such as that it would be so high the top would freeze at night, helicopters would be used for construction, parachutes would be part of the fire escape plan, and that an elevator ride to the top would take 12 minutes (multiple transfers would be required)<ref name=\"dailymailapril12\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1375790/Saudi-Royal-family-plans-mile-high-building.html|title=Mile-high business hub: Saudi Royal family plans \u00a312billion building so tall it will take 12 MINUTES to reach top by lift|publisher=Dailly Mail|date=12 April 2011|accessdate=9 August 2011|location=London}}</ref> in a typical elevator and five minutes in a high-speed elevator.<ref name=\"singularityhubmarch2011\" /> Adrian Smith denied that he was a part of any of the earlier designs, which had been purported in the media.<ref name=\"wiredapril11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2011-04/11/mile-high-tower|title=Saudi Arabia's mile-high Kingdom Tower gets green-lit|date=11 April 2011|publisher=Wired.co.uk|author=Mark Brown|accessdate=6 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723225443/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2011-04/11/mile-high-tower|archive-date=23 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> One source even corrected its article and clarified the misunderstanding.<ref name=\"dviceapril72011\">{{cite web|url=http://dvice.com/archives/2011/04/kingdom-tower-w.php|title=Kingdom Tower will make the Burj Khalifa look short, reach one mile up|publisher=[[Dvice.com]]|author=Wong, Raymond|date=7 April 2011|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Contractors selected ===\nIn early August 2011, the [[Binladin Group]] was chosen as the main construction contractor with the signing of an SR4.6&nbsp;billion ({{US$|1.23 billion}}) contract,<ref name=\"wallstreetjournalaugust3\" /> which is less than it cost to build the Burj Khalifa (US$1.5&nbsp;billion).<ref name=\"constructionweekcheap\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13451-kingdom-tower-cheaper-to-build-than-burj-khalifa/|title=Kingdom Tower cheaper to build than Burj Khalifa|author=CW Staff|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|date=4 August 2011|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> New renderings were revealed, and on 2 August it was widely reported that the project was a go at the {{convert|1000|m|ft|abbr=on|0}} height{{ref label|note01|A|c}} with a building area of {{convert|530000|m2|ft2|0}},{{ref label|note02|B|b}}<ref name=\"economictimesaugust2\">{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/et-cetera/kingdom-holding-co-signs-12-billion-deal-with-saudi-binladen-group-to-build-worlds-tallest-tower/articleshow/9456039.cms|title=Kingdom Holding Co signs US$1.2&nbsp;billion deal with Saudi Binladen Group to build world's tallest tower|date=2 August 2011 |work=The Economic Times |accessdate=2 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"tradenewswireaugust2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tradenewswire.net/2011/binladen-group-awarded-1-2bn-contract-awarded-to-build-worlds-tallest-tower/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120419001107/http://www.tradenewswire.net/2011/binladen-group-awarded-1-2bn-contract-awarded-to-build-worlds-tallest-tower/|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 April 2012|title=Binladen Group Awarded $1.2bn Contract Awarded to Build World's Tallest Tower|work=Trade Newswire|date=2 August 2011|accessdate=2 August 2011}}</ref> and will take 63 months to complete.<ref name=\"arabnewsaugust2\" /> The announcement of the main construction contract signing caused Kingdom Holding Company's stock to jump 3.2% in one day,<ref name=\"bloombergstock\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-02/kingdom-holding-s-stock-jumps-on-contract-for-record-high-tower.html|title=Kingdom Holding's Stock Jumps on Contract for Record-High Tower|author=Zahra Hankir|date=2 August 2011|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=2 August 2011}}</ref> in addition to KHC already having reported a 21% rise in second-quarter net profit.<ref name=\"financialtimesaugust\">{{cite web|url=http://ft.com/cms/s/0/71eef532-bcf6-11e0-bdb1-00144feabdc0.html|title=Saudi Arabia plans world's tallest tower|author=Abeer Allam|publisher=[[Financial Times]]|date=2 August 2011|accessdate=4 August 2011}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Also, for the first time, architects Gordon Gill and Adrian Smith officially announced their involvement in the project.<ref name=\"smithaugust2\">{{cite press release | url=http://smithgill.com/#/news/kingdom_tower_announcement/|title=AS+GG Designs Kingdom Tower, to Be the World's Tallest Building|date=2 August 2011| publisher=Adrian Smith + Gordon Gill Architecture |accessdate=3 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 August 2012, it was announced that the [[landscape design|landscaping contract]] for the Jeddah Tower was to be awarded to Landtech Designs, a US-based company, who will be responsible for irrigating {{convert|8.5|acre|ha|order=flip}} of green space by using the latest technology in sustainable irrigation. The supply of water to irrigate the green space would be collected through rainwater.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-18126-landtech-wins-kingdom-tower-irrigation-contract/|title=Landtech wins Kingdom Tower irrigation contract|author=CW Staff|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://landtechdesign.com/2012/08/landech-to-design-irrigation-system-for-kingdom-tower-to-be-the-worlds-tallest-building/|title=Landech to Design Irrigation System for Kingdom Tower, Soon to be the World's Tallest Building|work=Landtech Design}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 September 2012, it was announced that financing for the Jeddah Tower was complete. Talal Al Maiman, chief executive officer and managing director of Kingdom Real Estate Development Co. said in an interview \"We have all the investors, all the finance, all the money we need,\" Al Maiman said. \"It took us beyond 20 months to convince investors, working every detail and aspect of financing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/property/general/kingdom-tower-financing-complete-1.1079352 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-10-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001203020/http://gulfnews.com/business/property/general/kingdom-tower-financing-complete-1.1079352 |archivedate= 1 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn 10 October 2012, Kingdom Holding awarded contracts totalling $98&nbsp;million. Kingdom Holding Co. has signed a deal with Subul Development Company for the sale of land in the Kingdom Riyadh Land project for $66.5&nbsp;million. The Kingdom Riyadh Land project, a mixed-use commercial and residential development, will generate more than $5.33&nbsp;billion of total investment and will house up to 75,000 people. The final master plan contract was awarded to Omrania & Associates and Barton Willmore.<ref name=\"USSA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.us-sabc.org/custom/news/details.cfm?id=1356|title=Kingdom Holding Awards Contracts Worth $98 Million|publisher=U.S.-Saudi Arabian Business Council|date=10 October 2012|accessdate=7 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108013729/http://www.us-sabc.org/custom/news/details.cfm?id=1356|archive-date=8 November 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bauer, a German Foundations equipment manufacturer and contractor was awarded a US$32&nbsp;million contract to support the initial phases of construction of the Jeddah Tower. This includes the installation of 270 bored piles with diameters of 1.5 metres and 1.8 metres. The enabling works are expected to begin before the end of 2012 and take about 10 months to complete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khl.com/magazines/international-construction/detail/item79730/Bauer-awarded-Kingdom-Tower-contract|title=Bauer awarded Kingdom Tower contract \u2013 KHL Group|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 February 2013, the Jeddah Economic Company (JEC) announced that it had appointed an [[EC Harris]]/[[Mace (construction company)|Mace]] joint venture team to project manage the iconic Jeddah Tower project. The team will be providing project, commercial and design management for the Jeddah Tower development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echarris.com/reference/news/kingdom_tower.aspx|title=We are now Arcadis|publisher=}}</ref> CEO of JEC, Waleed Abduljaleel Batterjee said that the reason Mace was hired is to use the same team that worked for [[The Shard]] in London. On the other hand, EC Harris also has a long list of projects in the region including the Grand Millenium Al-Wahda Hotel, [[Abu Dhabi]]'s largest hotel complex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingdomtowerskyscraper.com/EC-Harris-and-Mace-will-manage-Kingdom-Tower-project.html|title=EC Harris and Mace will manage Kingdom Tower project|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 April 2013, news was reported that the Saudi Water Company had signed a 2.2&nbsp;billion-riyal ($587&nbsp;million) supply deal with Jeddah Economic Co. for the Jeddah tower project. The 25-year agreement to supply 156,000 cubic metres of treated and drinking water a day, enough for 62 Olympic-size pools, was signed by the chief executive of the Jeddah-based developer, Waleed Batraji, and Loay al-Musallam, head of National Water Company.<ref name=\"BloombergBusiness\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-04-29/saudi-water-company-signs-587-million-jeddah-tower-deal|title=Saudi Water Company Signs $587 Million Jeddah Tower Deal|author=Deema Almashabi|date=29 April 2013|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Construction begins ===\nConstruction started on 1 April 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/emaar-considering-tower-higher-than-1km-tall-kingdom-tower-2013-05-01-1.504820|title=Emaar 'considering' tower higher than 1km-tall Kingdom Tower|author=Staff|work=Emirates 24-7}}</ref> Piling was completed in December 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingdom.com.sa/jeddah-economic-company-board-of-directors-appoints-new-ceo-jec-announces-completion-of-pilling-of-tallest-tower-in-the-world|title=Jeddah Economic Company Board of Directors Appoints New CEO JEC Announces Completion of Pilling of Tallest Tower in the World|date=4 December 2013|publisher=Kingdom Holdings|accessdate=9 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215020859/http://www.kingdom.com.sa/jeddah-economic-company-board-of-directors-appoints-new-ceo-jec-announces-completion-of-pilling-of-tallest-tower-in-the-world|archive-date=15 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Above ground construction commenced in September 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url =http://www.ctbuh.org/News/GlobalTallNews/tabid/4810/Category/37/language/en-US/Saudi-Arabia.aspx|title =Jeddah's Kingdom Tower to use World's Tallest Construction Crane|last = |first = |date =19 September 2014|work  = |publisher =CTBUH|accessdate =9 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2017, the owner of Kingdom Holding Co, which owns 33% of the tower, and the chairman of the Saudi Binladen Group, which owns 17% and is the primary contractor, were arrested as part of the [[2017 Saudi Arabian purge]]. Construction of the tower continued,<ref>{{cite news|title=Jeddah Tower going ahead after Saudi corruption purge|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/construction/389437-jeddah-tower-going-ahead-after-saudi-corruption-purge|website=[[Arabian Business]]|publisher=[[ITP Media Group]]|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=23 April 2018|language=en|date=8 February 2018}}</ref> although some senior managers at Kingdom Holding were redirected to other projects.<ref name=Parasie>{{cite news|last1=Parasie|first1=Nicolas|last2=Said|first2=Summer|title=Crown Prince's Decision-Making Power Reaches Deep into Companies|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/crown-prince-takes-decision-making-power-over-saudi-arabias-biggest-businesses-1520856082|accessdate=23 April 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|date=12 March 2018|quote=At his Kingdom Holding conglomerate, Prince al-Waleed and his team remain nominally in charge. But the Saudi government demonstrated its new influence in February when it ordered some of his senior managers to leave his biggest new project, Jeddah Tower, slated to be the tallest building in the world at over 3,000 feet high. The government directed them instead to work on construction of Neom, a new, high-tech Saudi city envisioned by Prince Mohammed, said people familiar with the directive, who understood it to be in line with the prince's wishes.}}</ref> In February 2018, Mounib Hammoud, CEO of Jeddah Economic City, said that construction is continuing and that they hoped to open the tower by 2020.<ref name=ict />\n\nIn March 2018, Kingdom Holding Company signed a deal with [[Orange Business Services]] to provide [[IT infrastructure|information and communication technology (ICT) infrastructure]] to Jeddah Tower.<ref name=ict>{{cite web |title=Smart services deal signed for $1.5bn Jeddah Tower project |url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/technology/391920-smart-services-deal-signed-for-15bn-jeddah-tower-project |website=ArabianBusiness.com |accessdate=11 June 2018 |language=en |date=23 Mar 2018}}</ref> On March 12 construction of the tower moved forward after the delay.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2018/03/12/worlds-tallest-skyscraper-jeddah-tower-adrian-smith-gordon-gill/|title=Construction of world's tallest tower restarts after delays|date=2018-03-12|work=Dezeen|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Building freeze ===\nIn mid-2018, all work was paused with the tower about one-third completed due to labor issues with a contractor following the [[2017\u201319 Saudi Arabian purge]].<ref name=\"CNNDavosInterview\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/videos/business/2019/01/21/saudi-arabia-kingdom-holding.cnn-business|publisher=CNN|title=CNN Interview with Company Chairman|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Kingdom Tower, Jeddah, render 2.jpg|thumb|left|135px|Detailed rendering of Jeddah Tower cut out to show floors]]\n\n=== Challenges ===\nSustainability of such a tall building would include issues such as vertical transportation limitations, with elevators only being able to go so far; building sway, caused by wind; and super column settling, which occurs because concrete tends to shrink as it hydrates and settles under load, whereas steel is dimensionally stable, thereby causing the floors to become uneven.<ref>Wells, Matthew. ''Skyscrapers: Structure and Design.'' Laurence King Publishing, 2005 (p. 154)</ref> Additionally, a very large core size is required in very tall buildings to support the structure as well as to house the [[Skyscraper design and construction#The elevator conundrum|large number of elevators needed]]. The core size consumes a significant amount of the space on the lower and middle floors.<ref name=\"independent2008\" /> One of the ways Jeddah Tower attempts to overcome these issues is with its smooth, sloped-exterior design, which, although more expensive to build, offers superior aerodynamic performance over \"stepped\" designs such as the Burj Khalifa, allowing it to have a more conservative core overall. This was determined by wind tunnel tests performed at Burj Khalifa. Jeddah Tower will also use copious stiffening materials to prevent the excessive sway that would otherwise make the occupants of upper floors nauseated on windy days,<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13tallorder\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13533-tall-order/|title=Tall order|author=Ephgrave, Oliver|date=13 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref> including very high strength concrete that will be up to several metres thick in certain parts of the core. This, along with the highly integrated steel frame and [[shear wall]]s, is also intended to prevent catastrophic failure of the structure in the event of a terrorist attack.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> Traditionally, the space consumed by elevators was considered to make a building become increasingly less profitable past 80 floors or so. More recently, it has been the advent of truly mixed-use design such as [[Shanghai Tower]] and Burj Khalifa, as well as improved building technology, that have outdated this rule of thumb, which generally applied to single use buildings.<ref name=\"nymagaugust14\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/arts/architecture/reviews/supertall-davidson-review-2011-8/|title=Higher: At the Skyscraper Museum, a reminder of why we keep reaching for the clouds|author=Davidson, Justin|date=14 August 2011|publisher=[[NY Mag]]|accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nLike Burj Khalifa, Jeddah employs a similar Y-shaped, triangular footprint which promotes stability<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> and increases window views,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/columnists/kamin/ct-ae-lake-point-tower-anniversary-0923-story.html |title=50 years later, Lake Point Tower is a singular achievement \u2014 and let's hope it stays that way |last=Kamin |first=Blair |work=Chicago Tribune |access-date=2018-09-23 |language=en-US}}</ref> as well as a tapering form,<ref name=\"constructionweektapering\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13521-experts-tapered-form-of-kingdom-tower-is-ideal/|title=Experts: tapered form of Kingdom Tower is ideal|author=Oliver Ephgrave|date=10 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=11 August 2011}}</ref> with the sheer height and wind being the biggest structural design challenge.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust7\" /> The smooth, sloped fa\u00e7ade of Kingdom Tower particularly induces a beneficial phenomenon known as \"wind vortex shedding.\"<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13hypertall\" /> Normally when wind swirls around the [[leeward]] side of a building, rushing in from both sides to fill the low pressure zone, it would create tornado like vortices, which would rock the building from side to side due to variations in pressure, direction and velocity. The dynamic fa\u00e7ade of Kingdom Tower, however, creates an infinite timing differential (whereas Burj Khalifa is limited by the number of steps) in air pressure exertion in any one particular direction, thus creating a more stable structure, as there is no broad area of outstanding pressure or depression at any given time.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> Put simply, a smooth taper is more aerodynamic than an irregular or jagged taper, while both are advantageous over rectangular geometries. At Jeddah Tower's height, it is considered essentially unfeasible to use a traditional square design.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13tallorder\" />\n\n=== External form ===\nThe triangular footprint and sloped exterior of Jeddah Tower is designed to reduce [[wind load]]s; its high surface area also makes it ideal for residential use.<ref name=\"khlaugust4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.khl.com/magazines/international-construction/detail/item66227/AS-GG-named-as-architect-for-1-km-Kingdom-Tower/|title=AS+GG named as architect for 1 km Kingdom Tower|author=Chris Sleight|date=4 August 2011|publisher=KHL Group|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> The overall design of the tower, which will be located near both the [[Red Sea]] and the mouth of the [[Obhur Creek]] (Sharm Ob'hur) where it widens as it meets the Red Sea,<ref name=\"azobuild\">{{cite web|url=http://www.azobuild.com/news.asp?newsID=14284|title=Kingdom Holding Contracts Construction of World's Tallest Tower|author=Joel Scanlon|publisher=AZoBuild|date=4 August 2011|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> as well as having frontage on a man-made waterway and harbour that will be built around it,<ref name=\"businessinsideraugust4\" /> is intended to look like a desert plant shooting upwards as a symbol of Saudi Arabia's growth and future, as well as to add prominence to Jeddah's status as the gateway into the holy city of [[Mecca]].<ref name=\"arabnewsaugust4\">{{cite web|url=http://arabnews.com/opinion/editorial/article483104.ece|title=Exciting project|publisher=Arab News|date=4 August 2011|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> The designer's vision was \"one that represents the new spirit in Saudi Arabia\" (Smith).<ref name=\"industryleadersaugust5\" /> The 23 hectare (57 acre) area around Jeddah Tower will contain public space and a shopping mall, as well as other residential and commercial developments, and be known as the Jeddah Tower Water Front District,<ref name=\"azobuild\" /> of which, the tower's site alone will take up {{convert|500000|m2|ft2|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13hypertall\" /> As with many other very tall skyscrapers, including the [[Kingdom Centre]] in [[Riyadh]], which is generally considered to have sparked the recent significant commercial developments around it in the district of [[Olaya (Riyadh)|Olaya]],<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13crown\" /> much of the intention of Jeddah Tower is to be symbolic as well as to raise the surrounding land value rather than its own profitability.<ref name=\"chicagotribuneaugust3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-xpm-2011-08-03-ct-biz-0803-chicago-architects-talles20110803-story.html|title=Chicago firm's design towers over the rest|author=Ryan Haggerty|date=21 October 2018|work=The Chicago Tribune|accessdate=3 August 2011}}</ref> To that effect, the tower's architect, Adrian Smith, said that the tower \"evokes a bundle of leaves shooting up from the ground; a burst of new life that heralds more growth all around it\".<ref name=\"industryleadersaugust5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.industryleadersmagazine.com/kingdom-tower-by-bin-laden-group-will-be-the-worlds-tallest-building/|title=Kingdom Tower by Bin Laden Group will be the World's Tallest Building|author=Vrushti Mawani|publisher=Industry Leaders Magazine|date=5 August 2011|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> Smith states that the tower will create a landmark in which it and the surrounding Jeddah Economic City are interdependent.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> Talal Al Maiman, a board member of Jeddah Economic Company, said, \"Jeddah Tower will be a landmark structure that will greatly increase the value of the hundreds of other properties around it in Jeddah Economic City and indeed throughout North Jeddah.\"<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13hypertall\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13530-city-of-the-hyper-tall/|title=City of the hyper tall|author=Matthews, Stuart|date=13 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref> The concept of profitability derived from building high density developments and malls around such a landmark was taken from the Burj Khalifa, where it has proven successful, as its surrounding malls, hotels and condominiums in the area known as [[Downtown Dubai]]<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13kingdombeckons\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13535-the-kingdom-beckons/|title=The Kingdom beckons|author=Hope, Gerhard|date=13 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref> have generated the most considerable revenue out of that project as a whole,<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13hypertall\" /> while the Burj Khalifa itself made little or no profit.<ref name=\"bdonlineaugust16\">{{cite web|url=http://bdonline.co.uk/5022966.article?|title=Should the Kingdom Tower be built?|date=16 August 2011|publisher=bdonline.com|accessdate=16 August 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Kingdom Tower sky terrace fair use.jpg|thumb|right|235px|A rendering showing the bottom of the unique, glass-floored, circular sky terrace that will overlook the Red Sea from over {{convert|2000|ft|m|0|order=flip}}]]\n\n=== Elevators ===\n[[File:Kingdom Tower balcony fair use.jpg|thumb|right|170px|The large, outdoor sky terrace will overlook the Red Sea and have an area of over {{convert|7500|ft2|m2|0|order=flip}}{{ref label|note04|D|a}}]]\n\nThe building will have a total of 59 elevators, five of which will be [[double-deck elevator]]s, as well as 12&nbsp;escalators. The elevators are made by the Finnish company [[Kone]]. It will also have the highest observation deck in the world, to which high speed elevators will travel at up to 10 metres (33&nbsp;feet) per second (slightly over {{convert|22|mph|abbr=on|0|order=flip|disp=x|, or }}) in both directions.<ref name=\"ASGGpdf\" /> The elevators cannot go faster because the change in air pressure at such a rapid speed could cause [[nausea]]; at {{convert|3000|ft|m|abbr=on|0|order=flip}}, the air pressure is over 10 kPa (1.5 psi) lower than at ground level (a 10% reduction in air pressure).<ref name=\"engineeringtoolboxairpressure\">{{cite web|url=http://www.engineeringtoolbox.com/air-altitude-pressure-d_462.html|title=Air Pressure and Altitude above Sea Level|publisher=The Engineering ToolBox|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> They must also be efficient so the cables are not unbearably heavy.<ref name=\"independent2008\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/features/milehigh-tower-wars-how-tall-is-too-tall-849088.html|title=Mile-high tower wars: How tall is too tall?|publisher=The Independent|date=18 June 2008|accessdate=6 August 2011|location=London}}</ref> Jeddah Tower will have three [[sky lobby|sky lobbies]] where elevator transfers can be made, and no elevator will go from the bottom to the highest occupied floor.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> No official floor count has been given; however, Smith stated in a television interview that it will be about 50 floors more than the Burj Khalifa, which has 163&nbsp;occupied floors,<ref name=\"ctbuhburjkhalifa\">{{cite web|url=http://buildingdb.ctbuh.org/?do=building&building_id=3|title=Burj Khalifa|publisher=[[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]]|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> leading to the inference that Jeddah Tower will have over 200&nbsp;floors.{{ref label|note05|E|b}}<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> The tower will also feature a large, roughly {{convert|30|m|ft|abbr=on}} diameter outdoor balcony, known as the sky terrace, on one side of the building for private use by the penthouse floor at level 157;<ref name=\"ASGGpdf\">{{cite web |url=http://smithgill.com/media/pdfs/Kingdom_for_web4.pdf |title=Kingdom Tower |publisher=Adrian Smith+Gordon Gill Architecture | format=.PDF |accessdate=3 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"worldarchitecturenewsaugust2\">{{cite news | author=Sian Disson |url=http://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/index.php?fuseaction=wanappln.projectview&upload_id=17218 |title=After months of rumour and suspicion, AS+GG confirms it is designing a $1.2bn, 1000+m tower in Jeddah |work=World Architecture News |date=2 August 2011 |accessdate=3 August 2011}}</ref> it is not the observation deck.<ref name=\"gizmodoaugust8\">{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/5828801/the-new-images-of-the-kingdom-tower-are-simply-insane/gallery/|title=The New Images of the World's Newest Tallest Building Are Simply Insane|author=Jesus Diaz|publisher=[[Gizmodo]]|date=8 August 2011|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref> It was originally intended to be a [[helipad]], but it was revealed to be an unsuitable landing environment by helicopter pilots.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\">{{cite web|url=http://chicagotonight.wttw.com/2011/08/04/architect-adrian-smith|title=4 August 2011 -Architect Adrian Smith -Chicago Tonight Video -WTTW|publisher=[[WTTW]]|date=4 August 2011|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> The building's large notches will also serve as shaded terraces for other areas of the tower and the exterior of the building will use low-conductivity glass to save on cooling costs by reducing thermal loads.<ref name=\"singularityhubaugust4\" /> In addition, the lower air density, exacerbated by the thin desert atmosphere, will cause the outdoor air temperature towards the top of the tower to be lower than the ground level air, which will provide natural cooling. There is also significantly more air flow (wind) at heights, which is very strong at one kilometre and had a large impact on the structural design of the tower.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> The Burj Khalifa actually takes in the cooler, cleaner air from the top floors and uses it to air condition the building.<ref name=\"timeoutdubaijanuary2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.timeoutdubai.com/knowledge/features/12706-khalifa-creators|title=Burj Khalifa: We speak to the people who made it possible|publisher=Time Out Dubai|author=Lucas, Becky|date=11 January 2010|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> Jeddah Tower will be oriented such that no fa\u00e7ade directly faces the sun; it will also use the condensate water from the air conditioning system for [[irrigation]] and other purposes throughout the building.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust27\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13708-kingdom-tower-to-mimise-stack-effect-says-eds/|title=Kingdom Tower to minimise stack effect, says ESD|author=Davids, Gavin|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|date=27 August 2011|accessdate=27 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nTo overcome elevator issues, the tower will use its large number of efficient elevators as well as its three [[sky lobby|sky lobbies]], which allows transfers to be made between elevators serving a specific area with no elevator being overburdened. Much was learned from Burj Khalifa that helped with the design of Jeddah Tower<ref name=\"constructionweektapering\" /> not only structurally, but in methods for designing practical mechanical, electrical, and plumbing (MEP) systems, as well as adhering to local regulations and international [[building code]]s.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust24\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13693-burj-khalifa-provides-kingdom-tower-mep-template/|title=Burj Khalifa provides Kingdom Tower MEP template|author=Davids, Gavin|date=24 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref> Despite all the physical challenges, Adrian Smith states that practicality is still the greater challenge over structural durability, even in such super-tall designs, and that as with all buildings, Jeddah Tower's form was primarily derived respective of what the building's uses would be, then in accordance with the structural factors that would have to be considered to deliver it.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> [[Orange S.A.]] are designing the [[Information and communications technology|information and communications]] infrastructure of the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/sectors/technology/digital-transformation-is-key-to-future-development-1.2204217|title=Digital transformation is \u2018key to future development\u2019|last=Reporter|first=Naushad K. CherrayilStaff|date=12 April 2018|website=Gulfnews.com|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Internal systems ===\nChicago-based<ref name=\"investigesd\">{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=4393963|title=Environmental Design Systems, Inc.|publisher=Bloomerg|year=2011|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> Environmental Systems Design, Inc. will provide mechanical, plumbing, electrical and fire protection engineering,<ref name=\"businesswireaugust5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110805005139/en/ESD-Designing-Building-Systems-Kingdom-Tower|title=ESD Designing Building Systems for Kingdom Tower|publisher=Business Wire|date=5 August 2011|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> as well as teledata, audio/visual, security systems, and acoustics.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust9\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13502-kingdom-tower-esd-wins-building-systems-contract/|title=Kingdom Tower: ESD wins building systems contract|author=Hannah-Farah Abdulla|date=9 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=9 August 2011}}</ref> Langan International will be responsible for [[geotechnical engineering]] as well as some ground level site work such as [[transportation engineering]] and parking,<ref name=\"langanwebsite\" /> including the design of the proposed 3,000\u20134,700 car underground parking garage<ref name=\"langanpdf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.langan.com/web/tour/pdf/1502|title=Portfolio (PDF)|year=2011|publisher=Langan International|accessdate=5 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929031557/http://www.langan.com/web/tour/pdf/1502|archive-date=29 September 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> that will be located near, but not under the tower for terrorism reasons.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> Langan also designed the tower's foundation, which has to be able to support the tower despite the less than optimal subsurface conditions, such as soft rock and permeable coral, which could cause the piles to settle.<ref name=\"prnewswireaugust16\">{{cite news|url=http://prnewswire.com/news-releases/langan-international-designs-foundation-for-worlds-tallest-tower-127864738.html|title=Langan International Designs Foundation for World's Tallest Tower|date=16 August 2011|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=16 August 2011}}</ref> Thornton Tomasetti has provided the structural engineering for two of the previous world's tallest building title holders, the [[Petronas Towers]] in Kuala Lumpur, and the [[Taipei 101]] in Taiwan, as well as the under construction [[Ping An Finance Centre]] in [[Shenzhen]], which will be the second tallest building in China after completion.<ref name=\"newswireaugust2\" /> [[Saudi Binladin Group]] is the largest construction firm in the Middle East, with over 35,000 workers and hundreds of projects. They recently constructed the topped-out {{convert|1972|ft|m|0|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[Abraj Al-Bait]] Clock Tower in Mecca, which is the tallest building in Saudi Arabia and third tallest in the world, as well as the largest skyscraper in the world by floor area and volume. Aside from buildings, the firm has also constructed many major infrastructure projects, such as the [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|King Abdulaziz (Jeddah) International Airport]] expansion and the {{convert|775|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} six lane Al Qassim Expressway through Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust16rollcall\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13592-role-call/2/|title=Roll call|author=CW staff|date=16 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=16 August 2011}}</ref> Saudi Binladin Group is owned by the family of the late al-Qaeda leader [[Osama bin Laden]].<ref name=\"newsfeedresearcher\">{{cite web|url=http://newsfeedresearcher.com/data/articles_b32/tower-kingdom-saudi.html |title=Saudi prince developing world's tallest building |publisher=NewsFeed Researcher |date=3 August 2011 |accessdate=9 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014161147/http://newsfeedresearcher.com/data/articles_b32/tower-kingdom-saudi.html |archivedate=14 October 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> As a result, it has sparked some minor media buzz.<ref name=\"chicagodailyheraldaugust7\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20110807/business/708079963/|title=Alwaleed hires Saudi Binladin to build world's tallest tower|author=Bloomberg News|date=7 August 2011|publisher=[[Chicago Daily Herald]]|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> When asked his thoughts about this in an interview, Adrian Smith simply stated that they are the largest construction firm in the Middle East, most significant work in Saudi Arabia was done by them, and that it is a very large family that shouldn't be stereotyped by one of its members.<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" /> Furthermore, in January 2012, New York City judge [[George B. Daniels]] ruled that no charges could be filed against SBG to repay the victims of 9/11 as there is no evidence of the construction firm financially supporting bin Laden after he was removed as a shareholder following the [[1993 World Trade Center bombing|1993 World Trade Centre bombing]].<ref name=\"nochargesbinladen\">{{cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/01/11/2584568/ny-judge-drops-binladen-group.html |title=NY judge drops Binladen Group as 9/11 defendant |date=11 January 2012 |publisher=[[The Miami Herald]] |author=Neimeister, Larry |accessdate=11 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121202128/http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/01/11/2584568/ny-judge-drops-binladen-group.html |archivedate=21 January 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n=== Economic viability ===\nIn addition to its primary functions, the building is slated to include a significant amount of retail as well as a wide variety of other unique amenities with the intention that it functions as a nearly self-sustaining entity, approaching the concept of a \"[[vertical city]]\".<ref name=\"businessinsideraugust4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/waleeds-mega-tower-is-even-cooler-than-you-think-2011-8|title=Waleed's Saudi Mega Tower is Even Cooler Than You Think|author=Jeffery Townson|publisher=[[The Business Insider]]|date=3 August 2011|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> The building's design has been applauded as simple and feasible, yet bold, brilliantly sculpted, and high-tech,<ref name=\"worldarchitecturenewsaugust2\" /> with AS + GG describing it as \"an elegant, cost-efficient and highly constructible design.\"<ref name=\"khlaugust4\" /> The estimated construction cost of US$1.23&nbsp;billion, which is less than that of the Burj Khalifa (US$1.5&nbsp;billion), can be attributed to cheap labour in the Middle East, particularly Saudi Arabia, and that three shifts will work around the clock to expedite the process.<ref name=\"constructionweekcheap\" /> Construction costs have also declined since the global financial crisis.<ref name=\"arabianbusinessaugust15\">{{cite web|url=http://arabianbusiness.com/no-hurdle-kingdom-tower-hitting-2km-415705.html|title=No hurdle to Kingdom Tower hitting 2km|author=Staff writer|date=15 August 2011|publisher=ArabianBusiness.com|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, a report by consultancy EC Harris found that Saudi Arabia is the cheapest country in the Middle East to build in, half as expensive as [[Bahrain]], and 34% cheaper than the [[United Arab Emirates]], where Burj Khalifa is located.<ref name=\"arabbusinesscheaper\">{{cite web|url=http://arabianbusiness.com/kingdom-tower-cheaper-build-than-burj-khalifa-414170.html|title=Kingdom Tower cheaper to build than Burj Khalifa|publisher=Arab Business|date=4 August 2011|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> The future towers' site is located in very close proximity to [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|King Abdulaziz (Jeddah) International Airport]], whose runways nearly align with the towers' site, which will have an effect on the airspace.<ref name=\"businessinsideraugust4\" /> While skyscraper experts have stated that towers well over one kilometre, even two kilometres (6,562 feet) high, are technically feasible, physical sustainability and practicality issues come into play in towers of this height.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13463-skyscraper-expert-says-2km-tower-is-now-possible/|title=Skyscraper experts say 2km tower is now possible|author=Oliver Ephgrave|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|date=4 August 2011|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> As for physical restraints, Bart Leclercq, head of structures for WSP Middle East recently said, \"I truly believe that 1 mile, 1.6 kilometres, is within range. Over that, it may be possible if there are improvements in concrete quality. But 2&nbsp;km is too big a figure; it's just a step too far at the moment.\"<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13tallorder\" />\n\n==Impact==\nThere is an impending [[real estate bubble|real estate boom]] in Saudi Arabia, with increasing demand and rising prices due to high population growth and a short supply of housing, which may include a demand for high-end luxury units, such as those in Jeddah Tower. To boost growth, the Saudi Arabian government is going to invest US$67&nbsp;billion (SR251&nbsp;billion) in building 500,000&nbsp;homes throughout the country.<ref name=\"gulfnewsmidnight\">{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/property/saudi-real-estate-market-poised-for-boom-1.847379|title=Saudi real estate market poised for boom|date=5 August 2011|author=Aya Lowe|publisher=Gulf News|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> According to Saudi officials, about 900 new homes are needed a day to meet the demand of the rapidly growing population, which has nearly quadrupled in the past four decades.<ref name=\"hautelivingaugust10\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hauteliving.com/2011/08/the-kingdom-tower-to-overtake-burj-khalifa-as-dubais-tallest-tower/|title=The Kingdom Tower To Overtake Burj Khalifa As Dubai's Tallest Tower|author=Mahbubani, Rhea|publisher=Haute Living|date=10 August 2011|accessdate=10 August 2011}}</ref> Jeddah Tower is also an attempt to diversify Saudi Arabia's economy, which, holding a quarter of the world's [[oil reserve]]s and being one of the founding [[OPEC]] states, is currently largely dependent on its [[crude oil]] exports,<ref name=\"singularityhubaugust4\">{{cite web|url=http://singularityhub.com/2011/08/04/saudi-arabia-begins-construction-of-world%E2%80%99s-tallest-building-the-kingdom-tower/|title=Saudi Arabia Begins Construction of World's Tallest Building \u2013The Kingdom Tower|author=Peter Murray|date=4 August 2011|publisher=Singularity Hub|accessdate=5 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807115627/http://singularityhub.com/2011/08/04/saudi-arabia-begins-construction-of-world%E2%80%99s-tallest-building-the-kingdom-tower/|archive-date=7 August 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> which accounts for nearly 75% of government revenues and 90% of exports. This generates enough income to support Saudi Arabia as a [[welfare state]],<ref name=\"welfarestate\">{{cite web|url=http://portal.mofa.gov.sa/Detail.asp?InSectionID=1516&InNewsItemID=1746|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824235352/http://portal.mofa.gov.sa/Detail.asp?InSectionID=1516&InNewsItemID=1746|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 August 2011|title=The Kingdom of Saudi Arabia -A Welfare State|author=Royal Embassy of Saudi Arabia London|publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs]]|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> which spends billions of dollars on job creation and housing for its lower income residents.<ref name=\"dailymailaugust9\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2024188/Kingdom-Tower-Stunning-new-images-worlds-tallest-tower-Saudi-Arabia.html?ito=feeds-newsxml|title=High and mighty: Stunning new images of world's tallest tower|author=Lee Moran|publisher=Daily Mail|date=9 August 2011|accessdate=9 August 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nJust as the Jeddah Tower will complement the Jeddah Economic City development that will be built around it, there are many infrastructure and revitalisation projects underway and planned throughout Saudi Arabia, such as the US$7.2&nbsp;billion (SR27.1&nbsp;billion) new airport terminal under construction at [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|King Abdulaziz (Jeddah) International Airport]],<ref name=\"googlenewsjanuary\">{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iaYHQfKsttfAgoHg0m006s46K4dA?docId=CNG.1ec18a5caf14b98341da0879e29e0574.7f1|title=Saudi begins building new $7.2 bn Jeddah airport|date=11 January 2011|publisher=[[Google News]]|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> that will complement the Jeddah Economic City as well as develop Saudi Arabia, which has been likened to a Third World country with crumbling infrastructure and widespread disasters, including severe flooding,<ref name=\"forbesaugust2\">{{cite news|url=https://blogs.forbes.com/jamesmarshallcrotty/2011/08/02/kingdom-tower-worlds-tallest-building-coming-to-saudi-arabia-is-real-education-soon-to-follow/|title=World's Tallest Building Coming to Saudi Arabia. Is Education Soon To Follow?|author=James Marshall Crotty|publisher=Forbes|date=2 August 2011|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> such as the flash floods in early 2011 that damaged 90% of the roads and over 27,000 buildings in Jeddah.<ref name=\"msnbcaugust2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/43988244|title=World's tallest building coming to Saudi Arabia|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=2 August 2011|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> According to a representative of [[Standard Chartered]], which invested US$75&nbsp;million in Saudi Binladin Group, Saudi Arabia is going to spend over US$400&nbsp;billion (SR1.5&nbsp;trillion) on infrastructure over the next few years.<ref name=\"gulfnewsaugust9\">{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/construction/standard-chartered-buys-equity-stake-in-saudi-bin-laden-unit-1.849093|title=Standard Chartered buys equity stake in Saudi Bin Laden unit|author=Bloomberg|publisher=Gulf News|date=8 August 2011|accessdate=9 August 2011}}</ref> According to reports by [[Citi Investment Research & Analysis]], $220&nbsp;billion worth of development, accounting for 36% of all construction spending in the [[MENA]] region, will be directly or indirectly beneficial to Jeddah Tower.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13kingdombeckons\" /> Jeddah Tower and City themselves are intended to set an example of green development, using modern technology and having a low [[carbon footprint]] relative to the number of people they will support.<ref name=\"bdonlineaugust16\" /> However, there is also an increasing problem of poor education levels in Arab countries due to a lack of spending in research and education, which it is argued should be invested in rather than building skyscrapers,<ref name=\"dawnaugust5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/2011/08/05/we-need-education-not-skyscrapers.html|title=We need education, not skyscrapers|date=5 August 2011|author=Khawaja Umer Farooq|publisher=Dawn.com|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> and that the tower is nothing more than a symbol of [[hubris]].<ref name=\"nymagaugust14\" /> It has even been likened to the [[Tower of Babel]].<ref name=\"winnipegfreepressaugust6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/opinion/fyi/the-world-has-forgotten-what-happened-in-babel-127059103.html?device=mobile&c=y|title=The world has forgotten what happened in Babel|author=Tom Oleson|publisher=[[Winnipeg Free Press]]|date=6 August 2011|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, economists have found large new skyscrapers to be a negative economic indicator,<ref name=\"moneyweek2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moneyweek.com/news-and-charts/economics/a-recession-indicator-thats-hard-to-miss|title=A recession indicator that's hard to miss|publisher=[[MoneyWeek]]|date=11 February 2008|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref> with several instances of new tallest buildings being finished and opening into a bad economy,<ref name=\"theatlanticaugust8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2011/08/a-new-tallest-building-another-sign-of-economic-doom/243284/|title=A New Tallest Building, Another Sign of Economic Doom|author=Rebecca J. Rosen|publisher=[[The Atlantic]]|date=8 August 2011|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref> as they generally start during a financial boom when money is easy and investment is strong, but do not finish until the bubble has burst. Examples include the [[Singer Building]] and [[Metropolitan Life Insurance Company Tower|Metropolitan Life Insurance Building]] after the [[Panic of 1907]], [[40 Wall Street]], the [[Chrysler Building]] and the [[Empire State Building]] built during the [[Great Depression]], the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] and [[Sears Tower]] built during the 1970s economic downturn, the [[Petronas Towers]] built during the [[1997 Asian financial crisis|Asian Crisis]] of the late 1990s and the Burj Khalifa built during the [[Great Recession]].<ref name=\"marketurbanism2008\">{{cite web|url=http://marketurbanism.com/2008/08/26/skyscrapers-as-economic-indicators/|title=Skyscrapers as Economic Indicators|date=26 August 2008|publisher=Market Urbanism|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref> Much of the study on this phenomenon was done in 1999 by Andrew Lawrence, a research director at [[Deutsche Bank]] who created the \"skyscraper index,\" originally as a joke; however, it illustrated the observation that many of the world's tallest buildings have been built on the eve of financial collapse.<ref name=\"chicagomagaugust11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/The-312/August-2011/The-Kingdom-Tower-Skyscraper-for-the-Next-Financial-Collapse/|title=The Kingdom Tower: Skyscraper for the Next Financial Collapse?|author=Moser, Whet|date=11 August 2011|accessdate=11 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\nThe developers' theory is that the international attention gained through large developments and having the world's tallest building will incur [[gentrification]] of the country<ref name=\"arabianomics\">{{cite web|url=http://arabianomics.com/2011/04/15/%E2%80%98world%E2%80%99s-tallest-building%E2%80%99-crown-is-coming-to-saudi-arabia/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429061811/http://arabianomics.com/2011/04/15/%E2%80%98world%E2%80%99s-tallest-building%E2%80%99-crown-is-coming-to-saudi-arabia/|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 April 2014|title='World's Tallest Building' Crown is Coming to Saudi Arabia|publisher=Arabianomics|date=15 April 2011|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref> and even be a financial success in the long run. Rory Olcayto, deputy editor of ''The Architects\u2019 Journal,'' said \"The race to build the highest skyscraper is quite futile; where do you stop? These buildings are a symbol of an old-fashioned way of thinking,\"<ref name=\"singularityhubaugust4\" /> while architect Adrian Smith, the designer of the tower, states, \"...this tower symbolizes the Kingdom as an important global business and cultural leader, and demonstrates the strength and creative vision of its people. It represents new growth and high-performance technology fused into one powerful iconic form.\"<ref name=\"industryleadersaugust5\" /> However, Bob Sinn, principal engineer at Thornton Tomasetti, stated that the practical challenges of building very tall buildings are greater than the structural challenges.<ref name=\"constructionweekchallenges\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13529-engineer-kingdom-tower-is-practical-challenge/|date=11 August 2011|title=Engineer: Kingdom Tower is practical challenge|author=Oliver Ephgrave|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=11 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n\"We intend [Jeddah] Tower to become both an economic engine and a proud symbol of the kingdom's economic and cultural stature in the world community,\" said Talal Al Maiman, a board member of both Kingdom Holding Company and Jeddah Economic Company.<ref name=\"msnbcaugust2\" /> He continued, \"We envision [Jeddah] Tower as a new iconic marker of Jeddah's historic importance as the traditional gateway to the holy city of Mecca.\"<ref name=\"singularityhubaugust4\" /> The project's primary proponent, [[Prince Al-Waleed]] said, \"Building this tower in Jeddah sends a financial and economic message that should not be ignored. It has a political depth to it to tell the world that we Saudis invest in our country.\"<ref name=\"wallstreetjournalaugust3\" />\n\n[[Alain Robert]], also known as the French Spiderman, expressed his willingness to climb Jeddah Tower after completion if he were given official approval, despite the fact that he would be well into his fifties. When he heard that it might be up to 1,600 metres, he said, \"That doesn't make much sense,\" but he said that if the height were 1,000 metres, then it would be achievable.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust10\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13514-french-spiderman-up-for-challenge-of-kingdom-tower/|title=French spiderman up for challenge of Kingdom Tower|author=Carlin Gerbich|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|date=10 August 2011|accessdate=10 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Jeddah Tower Building Progress 2016-04-14 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Construction site as seen from a plane, April 2016]]\nWhile the official construction estimate is five years and three months (63 months), others calculate that it will take significantly longer, over seven years, based on the duration of Burj Khalifa's construction,<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13458-how-long-will-kingdom-tower-take-to-construct/|title=How long will Kingdom Tower take to construct?|author=Stuart Matthews|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|date=3 August 2011|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> which was over six years (with the help of CQC Department).\n\n[[Geotechnical investigation]] (soil testing) took place in 2008. Work on the foundation was scheduled to begin towards the end of 2012.<ref name=\"Bauer\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bauer.de/en/investor_relations/releases/press/2012_10_08_kingdomtower.html |title=BAUER Group again provides foundations for world's tallest building in Saudi Arabia |publisher=Bauer group |accessdate=14 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013010552/http://www.bauer.de/en/investor_relations/releases/press/2012_10_08_kingdomtower.html |archivedate=13 October 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Statements that construction would soon begin were made starting in 2008. In August 2011, the start of construction was slated as \"no later than December,\"<ref name=\"chicagotribuneaugust3\" /> with some saying \"immediately,\" and that construction was imminent.<ref name=\"singularityhubaugust4\" /> This meant the tower was expected to be completed in 2017, though at that time it was also possible that it could still have been completed by the date the media continued to publish, which was the prior estimate of late 2016.<ref name=\"hautelivingaugust10\" /> Only if construction had begun promptly and gone smoothly could a late 2016 completion have been achieved.<ref name=\"globestaugust11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globest.com/news/1975_1975/middleeast/313018-1.html|title=JEC ASSEMBLES TEAM FOR $1.2B TOWER|author=Carr, Robert|date=11 August 2011|publisher=Globest.com|accessdate=11 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927182401/http://www.globest.com/news/1975_1975/middleeast/313018-1.html|archive-date=27 September 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDesigns for the foundation were in place by early August 2011 and the contract for the [[piling]] was tendered.<ref name=\"khlaugust4\" /> On 16 August 2011, Langan International officially announced their involvement and that the foundation and piling had to be uniquely designed to overcome subsurface issues such as soft [[bedrock]] and [[Porosity|porous]] coral rock, which normally could not support a skyscraper without settling.<ref name=\"prnewswireaugust16\" /> The foundation is similar to that of the Burj Khalifa, but larger; it is expected to average around {{convert|4.5|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} deep with a concrete pad of area around {{convert|7500|m2|ft2|abbr=on}}. The concrete must have low [[Permeation|permeability]] to keep out corrosive [[Seawater|salt water]] from the Red Sea. Its depth and size are also considered to be an indicator of what the tower's final height will be.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust14higherandfaster\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13534-higher-and-faster/|title=Higher and faster|author=White, Stephen|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|date=14 August 2011|accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref> The piles will be up to {{convert|200|m|ft|abbr=on}} deep and the pad over {{convert|90|m|abbr=on}} across, yet the building, which will weigh over {{convert|900000|t}}, is expected to settle. The idea is that it settles evenly enough so that the building doesn't tip or put undue stress on the [[superstructure]]. Computer modelling programmes performed tests at the site to confirm that the foundation design would work.<ref name=\"huffingtonaugust25\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jacob-slevin/kingdom-tower-worlds-newe_b_935861.html|title=Kingdom Tower: World's Newest Tallest Building for 2016|author=Slevin, Jacob|publisher=Huffington Post|date=25 August 2011|accessdate=25 August 2011}}</ref> A later design for the foundation, to be constructed by Bauer in 2013, calls for 270 bored piles up to {{convert|110|m|ft|abbr=on}} deep which have to be installed into the difficult ground conditions.<ref name=\"Bauer\" /> Some materials needed for the structure are {{convert|500000|m3|cuft|abbr=on}} of concrete and {{convert|80000|t|abbr=on}} of steel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kingdom Tower: How The World's Next Tallest Building Will Be Built|url=http://www.gizmodo.com.au/2014/04/how-the-worlds-next-tallest-building-will-be-built/|accessdate=1 May 2014|newspaper=Gizmodo}}</ref>\n\n===Progress of construction===\nThere was steady progress but in January 2018 building owner JEC halted structural concrete work. JEC has said they plan to restart construction in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|title=Owner May Ramp Up Construction of Jeddah Tower, Planned to Be Over 1 km|url=https://www.enr.com/articles/48077-owner-may-ramp-up-construction-of-jeddah-tower-planned-to-be-over-1-km?v=preview/|accessdate=12 Jan 2020}}</ref>\n<gallery widths=\"150\" heights=\"150\" mode=\"packed\">\nFile:KT Building Progress 10-JAN-2015 04.png|12th floor (10 January 2015)\nFile:KT Building Progress 07-Jun-2015 01.jpg|23rd floor (7 June 2015)\nFile:Jeddah Tower Building Progress as of 07-Jul-2016.jpg|44th floor (7 July 2016) (42+2) at night\nFile:Jeddah Tower Building Progress as of 13-Jul-2016 002.jpg|44th floor (13 July 2016) (42+2)\nFile:Jeddah Tower Building Progress as of 02-Dec-2016 001 (cropped).jpg|47th floor (2 December 2016) (45+2)\nFile:Jeddah tower (cropped).jpg|As of June 2017\nFile:Jeddah Tower August 2019 S.Nitzold.jpg|As of August 2019\n</gallery>\n\n== Floor directory ==\nIt is estimated that the Jeddah Tower will have just over 200 floors.{{ref label|note05|E|b}}<ref name=\"awesomevideointerviewaugust4\" />\n{| Class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Floor || Purposes\n|- More + (construction in progress)\n| > 168 || Empty Spire\n|-\n| 168 (682 m)|| [[Tuned mass damper]]\n|-\n| 158\u2013167 || Building control machines\n|-\n| 157 (637m) || Observation deck, outdoor balcony\n|-\n| 155\u2013156 || Hotel, restaurants\n|-\n| 154 ||[[Four Seasons Hotel]]\n|-\n| 144\u2013153 || Hotel rooms\n|-\n| 141\u2013143 || Building control machines \n|-\n| 140 || Hotel rooms, refuge area\n|-\n| 127\u2013139 || Hotel rooms\n|-\n| 125\u2013126 || Hotel sky lobby\n|-\n| 115\u2013124 || Hotel rooms\n|-\n| 114 || Building control machines, refuge area\n|-\n| 104\u2013113 || Residence\n|-\n| 103 || Residence, refuge area\n|-\n| 94\u2013102 || Residence\n|-\n| 93 || Residential sky lobby \n|-\n| 90\u201392 || Building control machines\n|-\n| 89 || Refuge area\n|-\n| 80\u201388 || Offices\n|-\n| 79 || Refuge area\n|-\n| 67\u201378 || Offices\n|-\n| 65\u201366 || Sky lobby\n|-\n| 64 || Refuge area\n|-\n| 51\u201363 || Offices\n|-\n| 48\u201350 || Building control machines\n|-\n| 47 || Refuge area\n|-\n| 35\u201346 || Offices\n|-\n| 33\u201334 || Sky lobby\n|-\n| 29\u201332 || Building control machines\n|-\n| 18\u201328 || Offices\n|-\n| 16\u201317 || Building control machines\n|-\n| 6\u201315 || Offices\n|-\n| 3\u20135 || Building control machines\n|-\n| 2 || Shopping mall\n|-\n| 1 ||  Office lobby, serviced hotel lobby\n|-\n| B1 || Observatory entrance, shops, and restaurants\n|-\n| B2 || Parking, Building control machines\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of tallest buildings]]\n* [[List of future tallest buildings]]\n* [[The Illinois]]\n\n==Notes==\n: '''A.''' ^ {{note label|note01|A|a}}{{note label|note01|A|b}}{{note label|note01|A|c}}The actual height of the Burj Khalifa was not revealed until the opening ceremony. The developers of Jeddah Tower are similarly keeping the final height secret, stating only that it will be at least {{convert|1000|m|ft}} high. In a television interview for WTTW in Chicago, architect Adrian Smith stated that the tower will be a little over twice the height of the [[Burj Khalifa]], which is {{convert|828|m|ft}} high counting the antennas, suggesting that Jeddah Tower may be closer to {{convert|1600|m|ft}}. Some sources have suggested that Jeddah Tower will break Burj Khalifa's record by over {{convert|740|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"constructionweekaugust13crown\"/> In 2014, online sources were using the number {{convert|1008|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"CW1008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-28168-kingdom-tower-to-complete-in-december-2018/|title=Kingdom Tower to complete in December 2018|date=14 May 2014|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|author=Gibbon, Gavin|accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n: '''B.''' ^ {{note label|note02|B|a}}{{note label|note02|B|b}}This figure has been referred to as the \"total building area\" in publications, which is probably another term for [[gross floor area]]; the actual usable floor space, which is what buildings are typically measured by, will presumably be less. This area has also been reported as {{convert|540000|m2|ft2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"telegraphaugust11\" />\n\n: '''C.''' ^ {{note label|note03|C|a}}This assumes a 2012 start date and the estimated completion time of 63 months.\n\n: '''D.''' ^ {{note label|note04|D|a}}Figure attained using the formula for the area of a circle (\u03c0''r''<sup>2</sup>) and the given value of {{convert|98|ft|abbr=on|0|order=flip}} as the diameter.\n\n: '''E.''' ^ {{note label|note05|E|a}}{{note label|note05|E|b}}No official floor count has been given; however, Adrian Smith said it will be about 50 floors taller than the (163-floor) [[Burj Khalifa]].<ref name=\"constructionweekinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-13607-further-kingdom-tower-details-emerge/|title=Kingdom Tower to be 50 storeys taller than Burj|author=CW Staff|date=17 August 2011|publisher=ConstructionWeekOnline|accessdate=17 August 2011}}</ref> It is uncertain but probable that this counts unoccupied [[mechanical floor]]s in the spire. One source states, \"Tower residents and visitors will occupy 160 floors within the tower.\"<ref name=\"singularityhubaugust4\" /> In November 2010, an older kilometre-high design was said to contain over 200 floors.<ref name=\"constructionweeknovember2010\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Jeddah Tower}}\n* [http://www.kingdom.com.sa/ Kingdom Holding Company website]\n* [http://skyscrapercenter.com/building/kingdom-tower/2 Jeddah Tower] on the [[CTBUH]] Skyscraper Center\n* [http://www.foxnews.com/slideshow/world/2011/08/03/kingdom-tower/#slide=1 Slideshow image gallery of renderings] by [[Fox News]]\n* [https://twitter.com/jeddah_tower Jeddah Tower on Twitter]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fQUDYWm_iUk&t=6s Construction Timelapse] on YouTube\n\n{{Supertall skyscrapers | under-construction}}{{Portal|Saudi Arabia}}\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Jeddah]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures under construction in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Neo-futurism architecture]]\n[[Category:2020 in Saudi Arabia]]\n", "name_user": "Renek78", "label": "safe", "comment": "Completion date unknown", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeddah_Tower"}
{"title_page": "Yangzhou", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = {{raise|0.2em|Yangzhou}}\n| official_name           = <!-- Official name in English if different form 'name' -->\n| other_name              = Yangchow\n| native_name             = {{lower|0.1em|{{nobold|{{lang|zh|\u626c\u5dde\u5e02}}}}}}\n| native_name_lang        = zh-hans\n| settlement_type         = [[Prefecture-level city]]\n| image_skyline           = The Five Pavilion bridge.jpg\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = Five Pavilion Bridge at the [[Slender West Lake]]\n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = \n| image_map              = {{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=shape|stroke-width=2|stroke-color=#000000|zoom=7|frame-lat=32.71|frame-long=119.41}}\n| image_map1              = ChinaJiangsuYangzhou.png\n| map_alt1                = \n| map_caption1            = Yangzhou's location within Jiangsu province\n| pushpin_map             = China Jiangsu#Eastern China#China\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in China\n| coordinates             = {{coord|32|24|N|119|25|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[China|People's Republic of China]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Province (China)|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Jiangsu]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#County level|County-level&nbsp;divisions]]\n| subdivision_name2       = 6 (3 Districts, 2 County-level cities, 1 County)\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = \n| seat                    = \n| government_footnotes    = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            =[[Communist Party Chief]]\n| leader_name             = Xie Zhengyi ({{lang|zh-hans|\u8c22\u6b63\u4e49}})\n| leader_title1           = Mayor\n| leader_name1            = Xia Xinmin ({{lang|zh-hans|\u590f\u5fc3\u65fb}})\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 6678\n| area_land_km2           = \n| area_water_km2          = \n| area_water_percent      = \n| area_metro_km2          = 2310\n| area_note               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| area_urban_km2                  = 363\n|area_urban_footnotes = &nbsp;(2018)<ref name=\"demog14\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.demographia.com/db-worldua.pdf|title=Demographia World Urban Areas. 14th Annual Edition|last=Cox|first=Wendell|publisher=Demographia|year=2018|isbn=|location=St. Louis|page=22}}</ref>\n| population_urban                = 1665000\n| population_urban_footnotes      = &nbsp;(2018)<ref name=\"demog14\"/>\n| population_density_urban_km2   = auto\n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 4459760\n| population_as_of        = 2010 census\n| population_metro        = 2146980\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_metro_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_note         = Includes only those with Hukou permits\n| timezone1               = [[Beijing Time]]\n| utc_offset1             = +8\n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = 225000\n| area_code_type          = Telephone\n|area_code = (0)514\n|iso_code = [[ISO 3166-2:CN|CN-JS-10]]\n| website                 = {{URL|yangzhou.gov.cn/english}} {{in lang|en}}\n| footnotes               = \n| blank_name = Licence plate prefixes\n| blank_info ={{lang|zh-cn|\u82cfK}}\n}}\n{{infobox Chinese\n|pic=Yangzhou (Chinese characters).svg\n|piccap=\"Yangzhou\" in Simplified (top) and Traditional (bottom) Chinese characters\n|picupright=0.425\n|s=\u626c\u5dde |t=\u63da\u5dde |w=Yang<sup>2</sup>-chou<sup>1</sup>|p=Y\u00e1ngzh\u014du|mi={{IPAc-cmn|yang|2|.|zh|ou|1}}|wuu=Yang-tseu |j=joeng<sup>4</sup>zau<sup>1</sup> |l=\"[[Yang Province|Yang]] [[Zhou (country subdivision)|Prefecture]]\"|order=st}}\n'''Yangzhou''', [[Postal Map Romanization|postal romanization]] '''Yangchow''', is a [[prefecture-level city]] in central [[Jiangsu]] Province, China. Sitting on the north bank of the [[Yangtze]], it borders the provincial capital [[Nanjing]] to the southwest, [[Huai'an]] to the north, [[Yancheng]] to the northeast, [[Taizhou, Jiangsu|Taizhou]] to the east, and [[Zhenjiang]] across the river to the south. Its population was 4,414,681 at the 2010 census and its urban area is home to 2,146,980 inhabitants, including three urban districts, currently in the agglomeration.\n\nHistorically, Yangzhou was one of the wealthiest cities in China, known at various periods for its great merchant families, poets, artists, and scholars. Its name (<small>lit.</small> \"Rising Prefecture\") refers to its former position as the capital of the ancient [[Yangzhou (ancient China)|Yangzhou]] prefecture in [[History of the administrative divisions of China before 1912|imperial China]]. Yangzhou was one of the first cities to benefit from one of the earliest world bank loans in China, used to construct Yangzhou [[thermal power station]] in 1994.<ref name=\"wb\">{{cite web |title=Project documents and reports - Yangzhou thermal power project |url=http://projects.worldbank.org/P003641/yangzhou-thermal-power-project?lang=en |website=www.projects.worldbank.org/ |publisher=World Bank |accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Worldbank report - 1994 - Yangzhou thermal power plant loan |url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/712531468743979065/pdf/multi0page.pdf |website=www.documents.worldbank.org |publisher=World bank |accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Administration==\n{{See also|List of administrative divisions of Jiangsu}}\n\nCurrently, the [[prefecture-level city]] of Yangzhou administers six [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#County level|county-level divisions]], including three [[District (PRC)|districts]], two [[county-level cities]] and one [[County (People's Republic of China)|county]]. Accordingly, they are further divided into 98 [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#Township level|township-level divisions]], including 87 [[town of China|towns]] and [[Township (People's Republic of China)|townships]], and 11 [[subdistrict]]s.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"6\" | Map\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" | <div style=\"position: relative\" class=\"center\">\n{{Image label begin|image=Administrative Division Yangzhou.png|width={{{1|415}}}|link=}} \n{{Image label|x=580|y=1330|scale={{{1|415}}}/1660|text=[[Gaoyou Lake|''Gaoyou<br>Lake'']]}}\n{{Image label|x=890|y=2340|scale={{{1|415}}}/1660|text=[[Guangling District|'''Guangling''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=620|y=2130|scale={{{1|415}}}/1660|text=[[Hanjiang District, Yangzhou|'''Hanjiang''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1150|y=1970|scale={{{1|415}}}/1660|text=[[Jiangdu District|'''Jiangdu''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=790|y=470|scale={{{1|415}}}/1660|text=[[Baoying County|'''Baoying<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=250|y=2270|scale={{{1|415}}}/1660|text=[[Yizheng|'''Yizheng<br>{{small|(city)}}''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1010|y=1240|scale={{{1|415}}}/1660|text=[[Gaoyou|'''Gaoyou<br>{{small|(city)}}''']]}}\n</div>\n|-\n! align=left          | Subdivision\n! align=left          | Simplified Chinese\n! align=left          | Hanyu Pinyin\n! align=left          | Population {{small|([[Sixth National Population Census of the People's Republic of China|2010]])}}\n! align=left          | Area {{small|(km<sup>2</sup>)}}\n! align=left          | Density {{small|(/km<sup>2</sup>)}}\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"\n| colspan=\"6\"  style=\"text-align:center; \"| '''City Proper'''\n|-\n| align=left | [[Guangling District]]\n| align=left | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u5e7f\u9675\u533a}}\n| align=right | Gu\u01cengl\u00edng Q\u016b\n| align=right| 340,977\n| align=right| 423.09\n| align=right| 805.92\n|-\n| align=left | [[Hanjiang District, Yangzhou|Hanjiang District]]\n| align=left | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u9097\u6c5f\u533a}}\n| align=right | H\u00e1nji\u0101ng Q\u016b\n| align=right| 1,051,322\n| align=right| 552.68\n| align=right| 1,902.23\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"\n| colspan=\"6\"  style=\"text-align:center; \"| '''Suburban'''\n|-\n| align=left | [[Jiangdu District]]\n| align=left | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u6c5f\u90fd\u533a}}\n| align=right | Ji\u0101ngd\u016b Q\u016b\n| align=right| 1,006,780\n| align=right| 1,329.90\n| align=right| 757.03\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"\n| colspan=\"6\"  style=\"text-align:center; \"| '''Rural'''\n|-\n| align=left | [[Baoying County]]\n| align=left | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u5b9d\u5e94\u53bf}}\n| align=right | B\u01ceoy\u00ecng Xi\u00e0n\n| align=right| 752,074\n| align=right| 1,461.55\n| align=right| 514.57\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"\n| colspan=\"6\"  style=\"text-align:center; \"| '''Satellite cities ([[County-level city|County-level cities]])'''\n|-\n| align=left | [[Yizheng]]\n| align=left | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u4eea\u5f81\u5e02}}\n| align=right | Y\u00edzh\u0113ng Sh\u00ec\n| align=right| 563,945\n| align=right| 902.20\n| align=right| 625.08\n|-\n| align=left | [[Gaoyou]]\n| align=left | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u9ad8\u90ae\u5e02}}\n| align=right | G\u0101oy\u00f3u Sh\u00ec\n| align=right| 744,662\n| align=right| 1,921.78\n| align=right| 387.49\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"\n| colspan=3 style=\"text-align:center; \"|'''Total'''\n| align=right|'''4,459,760'''\n| align=right|'''6,591.21'''\n| align=right|'''676.62'''\n|-\n| colspan=6 style=\"text-align:center; \"| In November 2011, [[Weiyang District, Yangzhou|Weiyang District]] ({{linktext|\u7ef4|\u626c|\u533a}}) was merged into Hanjiang District,<br>while the former county-level Jiangdu City became Jiangdu District.<ref>{{cite web\n  |url = http://news.cntv.cn/china/20111114/106430.shtml\n  |script-title=zh:\u6c5f\u82cf\u626c\u5dde\u884c\u653f\u533a\u5212\u8c03\u6574 \u6c5f\u90fd\u5e02\u6539\u533a\u7ef4\u626c\u533a\u88ab\u64a4\u9500\n  |publisher = China Network Television\n  |language = Chinese\n  |date = 14 November 2011\n  |accessdate = 2012-01-10}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==History==\nGuangling ({{zh|s={{linktext|\u5ee3|\u9675}}|hp=Gu\u01cengl\u00edng|w=Kuang-Ling|links=no}}), the first settlement in the Yangzhou area, was founded in the [[Spring and Autumn period]]. After the defeat of [[Yue (state)|Yue]] by [[King Fuchai of Wu]], a garrison city was built {{Convert|12|m|abbr=on}} above the water level on the north bank of the Yangtze c.&nbsp;485&nbsp;BC.  This city in the shape of a three by three ''[[Li (unit)|li]]'' square was named Hancheng.<ref>Schinz, 1996</ref>  The newly built Han canal formed a moat around the south and east sides of the city. The purpose of Hancheng was to protect [[Suzhou]] from naval invasion from [[Qi (state)|Qi]]. During the [[Han dynasty]], Guangling was the seat of [[Guangling Commandery]]. It constituted a part of the [[Xu Province]], rather than the [[Yang Province]] (Yangzhou), which was covered the entire southeastern part of China then. In 590, the city was made the capital of a newly established [[Yang Prefecture (Jiangsu)|Yang Prefecture]], and began to be referred to with its current name.\n\nUnder [[Emperor Yang of Sui]] (r. 604\u2013617), Yangzhou was the southern capital of China. It was called Jiangdu upon the completion of the [[Grand Canal (China)|Grand Canal]] until the fall of the [[Sui dynasty]]. By the mid 610s, a combination of fruitless attempts to conquer the Korean kingdom of Goguryeo, together with natural disasters and provincial unrest, ensured many people Emperor Yang had lost the legitimacy of his monarchy. As revolts spread across China in 616, the Emperor abandoned the North and meanwhile withdrew to Jiangdu, where he remained until his assassination in 618.\n\n===Tang Dynasty===\nThe city has remained a leading economic and cultural center and major port of foreign trade and external exchange since the [[Tang dynasty]] (618\u2013907). Many Arab and Persian merchants lived in the city in the 7th century, but they were massacred in the thousands in 760 during the [[An Lushan Rebellion]] by Tian Shengong's ({{zh|s=\u7530\u795e\u529f|hp=Ti\u00e1n Sh\u00e9ng\u014dng|w=T'ien Shen-kung|links=no}}) rebel insurgents during the [[Yangzhou massacre (760)]].<ref name=\"Perkins\">{{Cite book|last=Perkins|first=Dorothy|title=Encyclopedia of China: The Essential Reference to China, Its History and Culture|publisher=Roundtable Press|year=2000|isbn=978-0-8160-4374-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|accessdate=2012-01-10|quote=Probably by the 7th century Persians had joined with Arabs to create the foreign emporium on the Grand Canal at Yangchou mentioned by the New T'ang History. The same source records a disturbance there in 760 in which a thousand of the merchants were killed.|title=The Cambridge History of Iran, Volume 3|year=1993|volume=|author=Yarshater|editor=William Bayne Fisher |editor2=Yarshater, Ilya Gershevitch|edition=reprint|location= |publisher=Cambridge University Press |page=553|isbn=0-521-20092-X|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ko_RafMSGLkC&pg=PA553&dq=Probably+by+the+7th+century+Persians+had+joined+with+Arabs+to+create+the+foreign+emporium+on+the+Grand+Canal+at+Yangchou+mentioned+by+the+New+T'ang+History.+The+same+source+records+a+disturbance+there+in+760+in+which+a+thousand+of+the+merchants+were+killed&hl=en&sa=X&ei=0jIWT_PtLpCctwe0_MH7Ag&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Probably%20by%20the%207th%20century%20Persians%20had%20joined%20with%20Arabs%20to%20create%20the%20foreign%20emporium%20on%20the%20Grand%20Canal%20at%20Yangchou%20mentioned%20by%20the%20New%20T'ang%20History.%20The%20same%20source%20records%20a%20disturbance%20there%20in%20760%20in%20which%20a%20thousand%20of%20the%20merchants%20were%20killed&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |accessdate=2012-01-10|quote=The wealth of the foreign merchants established in the big cities may have provoked the xenophobia that became apparent during rebellions. In 760 several thousand Arab and Persian merchants were massacred at Yangchow by insurgent bands led by T'ien Shen-kung, and a century later, in 879, it was also the foreign merchants who were attacked at Canton under the troops of Huang Ch'ao.|title=A history of Chinese civilization|year=1996|volume=|author=Jacques Gernet|edition=2, illustrated, revised|location= |publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/historyofchinese00gern/page/292 292]|isbn=0-521-49781-7|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofchinese00gern|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|accessdate=2012-01-10|quote=these manliao ( j\u00a7 w) [Southern barbarians] would pollute the Chinese culture through intermarriage and upset the land ownership system through land acquisition. . .For example, in AD 760, Yangzhou was attacked by a nearby garrison troop led by Tian Shengong (HJ^ff-w), who was ironically invited by the local authorities to help crush a local uprising. Consequently, a few thousand Arab and Persian merchants were robbed and killed (Jin Tangshu, ch. 110). In the 830s, a mandarin in Guangzhou took steps to control the Arab and Persian Muslims by ordering that Chinese and barbarians must live in separate quarters and must not intermarry; barbarins were also not allowed to own land and paddy fields (Jin Tangshu, ch. 177) Thereafter, Arab and Persian traders lived in designated quarters . . .they also enjoyed religious freedom and kept their Islamic lifestlye intact. . .the Arab and Persian Muslims were also contented to stay out of the Confucian Chinese world so long as the authorities concerned pledged to provide aman [security] for them to lead a peaceful life according to the Islamic doctrines.|title=Cheng Ho and Islam in Southeast Asia|year=2009|volume=|author1=Tan Ta Sen |author2=Dasheng Chen |edition=illustrated, reprint|location= |publisher=Institute of Southeast Asian Studies|page=104|isbn=981-230-837-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vIUmU2ytmIIC&pg=PA104&dq=tian+shengong+yangzhou&hl=en&sa=X&ei=iDcWT6f8C8m2gwfUtKn2DQ&ved=0CD8Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=tian%20shengong%20yangzhou&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|accessdate=2012-01-10|quote=en 760, varios millares de mercaderes \u00e1rabes y persas fueron masacrados en Yangzhou por bandas insurgentes dirigidas por Tian Shengong; un siglo m\u00e1s tarde las tropas de Huang Chao la emprendieron tambi\u00e9n en Cant\u00f3n con los mercaderes extranjeros.|language=Spanish|title=El mundo chino|year=2007|volume=|author=Jacques Gernet|edition=|location= |publisher=Editorial Critica|page=263|isbn=84-8432-868-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jd9WP1TKtVYC&pg=PA263&dq=tian+shengong+yangzhou&hl=en&sa=X&ei=iDcWT6f8C8m2gwfUtKn2DQ&ved=0CEYQ6AEwAg#}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|accessdate=2012-01-10|quote=Deng Jingshan f\u00dfJSlll , the governor of Yangzhou, ordered general Tian Shengong \u0428 to lead his forces to suppress the rebels. Shengong entered Yangzhou in 760 and sacked the city, plunderSino-Arab|title=\u5510\u7814\u7a76|year=1999|volume=|author=\u65b0\u6c5f\u8363|edition=|location= |publisher=\u5317\u4eac\u5927\u5b78\u51fa\u7248\u793e|page=334|isbn=7-301-04393-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IGgzAQAAIAAJ&q=tian+shengong+yangzhou&dq=tian+shengong+yangzhou&hl=en&sa=X&ei=iDcWT6f8C8m2gwfUtKn2DQ&ved=0CEwQ6AEwAw}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|accessdate=2012-01-10|quote=But, Yangzhou was also a famous trade center with a large foreign community. Chinese sources record several thousand Arabs, Persians, and other foreigner merchants being killed in 760 AD when General Tian Shengong sacked the city during|title=\u5510\u7814\u7a76|year=1999|volume=|author=\u65b0\u6c5f\u8363|edition=|location= |publisher=\u5317\u4eac\u5927\u5b78\u51fa\u7248\u793e|page=344|isbn=7-301-04393-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IGgzAQAAIAAJ&q=tian+shengong+yangzhou&dq=tian+shengong+yangzhou&hl=en&sa=X&ei=iDcWT6f8C8m2gwfUtKn2DQ&ved=0CEwQ6AEwAw}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|accessdate=2012-01-10|quote=Misalnya, pada 760, Yangzhou diserang oleh pasukan tentara di bawah pimpinan Tian Shengong (ffltt^d) yang ironisnya diminta oleh penguasa setempat untuk membantu menumpas pemberontakan daerah. Akibatnya, ribuan saudagar Arab dan Persia dirampok dan dibunuh.22 Pada tahun 830-an, seorang pejabat tinggi di Guangzhou mengambil langkah untuk mengawasi orang orang Muslim Arab dan Persian degan memerintahkan orang China dan orang barbar harus tinggal di pemukiman terpisah dan tidak boleh kawin campur; kaum barbar tidak boleh memiliki tanah dan ladang sawah.|language=Malay|title=Cheng Ho|year=|volume=|author1=Tan Ta Sen |author2=Abdul Kadir |author3=Abdul Kadir |edition=|location= |publisher=Penerbit Buku Kompas|page=143|isbn=979-709-492-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=V-TbryZleo0C&pg=PA143&dq=tian+shengong+yangzhou&hl=en&sa=X&ei=iDcWT6f8C8m2gwfUtKn2DQ&ved=0CFEQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=tian%20shengong%20yangzhou&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|accessdate=2012-01-10|quote=milliers de marchands arabes et persans sont massacr\u00e9s \u00e0 Yangzhou par les bandes insurg\u00e9es que m\u00e8ne Tian Shengong; un si\u00e8cle plus tard, c'est aussi aux marchands \u00e9trangers que s'en prennent \u00e0 Canton les troupes de Huang Chao en 879.|language=Spanish|title=Le monde chinois|year=1972|volume=|author=Jacques Gernet|edition=2|location= |publisher=A. Colin|page=|isbn=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZdwxAQAAIAAJ&q=tian+shengong+yangzhou&dq=tian+shengong+yangzhou&hl=en&sa=X&ei=iDcWT6f8C8m2gwfUtKn2DQ&ved=0CFcQ6AEwBQ}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|accessdate=2012-01-10|quote=They dealt in a vast variety of commodities, and their numbers were not small.9 For example, Tian Shengong's soldiers killed thousands of Dashi and Bosi at Yangzhou in a Tang battle against local rebels. When Huang Chao's rebel army |title=Familiar strangers: a history of Muslims in Northwest China|year=1997|volume=|author=Jonathan Neaman Lipman|edition=illustrated|location= |publisher=University of Washington Press|page=27|isbn=0-295-97644-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=90CN0vtxdY0C&pg=PA27&dq=tian+shengong+yangzhou&hl=en&sa=X&ei=iDcWT6f8C8m2gwfUtKn2DQ&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=tian%20shengong%20yangzhou&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|accessdate=2012-01-10|quote=Ouyang, Xin Tang Shu 182.6b--a records the order of Lu Jun, governor of Lingnan at Canton, that foreigners and Chinese could not intermarry (Ch. Fan Hua bu de tong hun), in order to prevent conflict.|title=Familiar strangers: a history of Muslims in Northwest China|year=1997|volume=|author=Jonathan Neaman Lipman|edition=illustrated|location= |publisher=University of Washington Press|page=26|isbn=0-295-97644-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=90CN0vtxdY0C&pg=PA26&dq=Ouyang+Xin+Tang+Shu+records+the+order+of+Lu+Jun,+governor+of+Lingnan+at+Canton,+that+foreigners+and+Chinese+could+not+intermarry&hl=en&sa=X&ei=8DgWT6_4K9S_gAeQuIyhAw&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Ouyang%20Xin%20Tang%20Shu%20records%20the%20order%20of%20Lu%20Jun%2C%20governor%20of%20Lingnan%20at%20Canton%2C%20that%20foreigners%20and%20Chinese%20could%20not%20intermarry&f=false}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Tang dynasty, many merchants from [[Silla]] also lived in Yangzhou.\n\nThe city, still known as Guangling, was briefly made the capital of [[Wu (Ten Kingdoms)|Wu]] during the [[Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms period]].\n\n===From Song to Ming===\nYangzhou was briefly the temporary seat of the [[Song dynasty]] government between 1128 and 1129,<ref name=mote/> when most of [[North China]] had been conquered by the [[Jurchen people|Jurchens]] during the [[Jin\u2013Song Wars]].<ref>{{cite book|first=Charles|last=Holcombe|title=A History of East Asia: From the Origins of Civilization to the Twenty-First Century|year=2011|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-51595-5|page=129}}</ref> The Song had retreated south to the city from their original capital in [[Kaifeng]] after it was captured by the Jurchen in the [[Jingkang Incident]] of 1127.\n\nFrom Yangzhou, the Song moved to [[Hangzhou]] in 1129, later establishing it as the capital of the [[Southern Song]].<ref name=mote>{{cite book|first=Frederick W.|last=Mote|title=Imperial China: 900\u20131800|year=2003|publisher=Harvard University Press|page=293|isbn=978-0-674-01212-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Herbert|last=Franke|editor=Denis C. Twitchett|editor2=Herbert Franke|editor3=John King Fairbank|title=The Cambridge History of China: Volume 6, Alien Regimes and Border States, 710\u20131368|year=1994|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=229 |isbn=978-0-521-24331-5}}</ref>\n\nIn 1280, Yangzhou was the site of a massive [[gunpowder]] explosion when the bomb store of the [[Weiyang District, Yangzhou|Weiyang]] arsenal accidentally caught fire. This blast killed over a hundred guards, hurled debris from buildings into the air that landed ten ''li'' away from the site of the explosion, and could be felt 100 ''li'' away as tiles on roofs shook (refer to [[gunpowder]] article).\n\n[[Marco Polo]] claimed to have served the [[Yuan dynasty]] in Yangzhou under [[Kubilai Khan]] in the period around 1282\u20131287 (to 1285, according to Perkins<ref name=\"Perkins\" />). Although some versions of Polo's memoirs imply that he was the governor of Yangzhou, it is more likely that he was an official in the salt industry, if indeed he was employed there at all. Chinese texts offer no supporting evidence for his claim. The discovery of the 1342 tomb of [[Katarina Vilioni]], member of an Italian trading family in Yangzhou, does, however, suggest the existence of a thriving Italian community in the city in the 14th century. Moreover, both in [[The Travels of Marco Polo]] and in the [[History of Yuan]] there is documentation about a [[Nestorianism|Nestorian Christian]], who funded two churches in China during the three years he served as an official of the emperor: this functionary is named \"Mar Sarchis\" by Marco Polo and \"Ma Xuelijisi\" in the History of Yuan. He served as a supervisor in the province of Zhenjiang, a region neighboring Yangzou.<ref>Giulio Busi, \"Marco Polo. Viaggio ai confini del Medioevo\", Collezione Le Scie. Nuova serie, Milano, Mondadori, 2018, {{ISBN|978-88-0470-292-4}}, \u00a7 \"Boluo, il funzionario invisibile</ref> In fact, it is well-documented that [[Kublai Khan]] trusted foreigners more than Chinese subjects in internal affairs.<ref>Giulio Busi, \"Marco Polo. Viaggio ai confini del Medioevo\", Collezione Le Scie. Nuova serie, Milano, Mondadori, 2018, {{ISBN|978-88-0470-292-4}}, \u00a7 \"Boluo, il funzionario invisibile</ref>\n\nThere were also Arabic inscriptions from the 13th and 14th centuries, indicating the presence of a Muslim community.<ref>{{cite book\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=__Q1gOeoJZcC&pg=PA228&dq=mosque+ningpo&hl=en&ei=fwncTbrtFce90AG2uM3GDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC0Q6AEwATge#v=onepage&q=mosque%20ningpo&f=false\n|title=Islam: an illustrated history\n|volume=\n|year=2006\n|author1=Greville Stewart Parker Freeman-Grenville |author2=Stuart C. Munro-Hay |publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group\n|edition=illustrated, revised\n|location=\n|isbn=0-8264-1837-6\n|page=228\n|pages=\n|accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Ming dynasty]] (1368\u20131644) until the 19th century Yangzhou acted as a major trade exchange center for salt (a government regulated commodity), rice, and silk. The Ming were largely responsible for building the city as it now stands and surrounding it with {{Convert|9|km|abbr=on}} of walls.\n\n===Early Qing===\n[[File:Yangzhou massacre.jpg|thumb|A late Qing artist conception of the [[Yangzhou massacre]].]]\n\nAfter the fall of Beijing and northern China to the [[Manchu people|Manchus]] in 1644, Yangzhou remained under the control of the short-lived [[Southern Ming]] based in [[Nanjing]]. [[Qing dynasty|Qing]] forces led by [[Dodo (prince)|Prince Dodo]] reached Yangzhou in the spring of 1645, and despite the heroic efforts of its chief defender, [[Shi Kefa]], the city fell on May 20, 1645, after a brief siege. The ten-day [[Yangzhou massacre]] followed, Wang alleged that the number of victims was allegedly close to 800,000, that number is now disproven and considered by modern historians and researchers to be a ridiculous exaggeration.<ref name = \"Finnane\">{{cite book | author=Antonia Finnane,|title=''Speaking of Yangzhou: A Chinese City, 1550-1850''|  url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6-hxAAAAMAAJ | publisher=Harvard University Asia Center|date=2004 |page=453 | isbn=978-0674013926}}</ref><ref>\u8c22\u56fd\u6862\uff0c\u300a\u5357\u660e\u53f2\u7565\u300b\uff0c\u7b2c72\u201473\u9875</ref> Shi Kefa himself was killed by the Manchus when he refused to switch his allegiance to the Qing regime.<ref>\"Horrid beyond description\": The massacre of Yangzhou\", in ''Voices from the Ming-Qing Cataclysm: China in Tigers' Jaws'', ed. Struve, Lynn A. ale University Press, 1998, {{ISBN|0-300-07553-7}}. Pages 28-48.</ref>\n\nThe city's rapid recovery from these events and its great prosperity through the early and middle years of the Qing dynasty were due to its role as administrative center of the Lianghuai sector of the government salt monopoly. As early as 1655, the Dutch envoy [[Johan Nieuhof]] described the city (''Jamcefu'', i.e. Yangzhou-Fu, in his transcription) commented on the city's salt trade as follows:<ref>[[Johan Nieuhof]],\n''[http://digicoll.library.wisc.edu/cgi-bin/DLDecArts/DLDecArts-idx?type=turn&entity=DLDecArts.Nieuhof.p0108 An embassy from the East-India Company of the United Provinces, to the Grand Tartar Cham, emperor of China: delivered by their excellencies Peter de Goyer and Jacob de Keyzer, at his imperial city of Peking wherein the cities, towns, villages, ports, rivers, &c. in their passages from Canton to Peking are ingeniously described by John Nieuhoff; ... Englished and set forth with their several sculptures by John Ogilby]'', 1673, p.82</ref>\n{{blockquote|This Trade alone has so very much enrich'd the Inhabitants of this Town, that they have re-built their City since the last destruction by the ''[[Manchu people|Tartars]]'', erecting it in as great splendor as it was at first.}}\n\nFamed at that time and since for literature, art, and the gardens of its merchant families, many of which were visited by the Kangxi and Qianling emperors during their Southern Tours, the Qing-era Yangzhou has been the focus of intensive research by historians.\n\n===Late Qing and Republican era===\nThe [[Yangzhou riot]] in 1868 was a pivotal moment of [[China\u2013United Kingdom relations|Anglo-Chinese relations]] during late Qing China that almost led to war.<ref>Austin (2007), p. 129</ref> The crisis was fomented by the [[scholar-official]]s of the city, who opposed the presence of foreign [[Mission (Christianity)|Christian missionaries]] there. The riot that resulted was an angry crowd estimated at eight to ten thousand who assaulted the premises of the British [[OMF International|China Inland Mission]] in Yangzhou by looting, burning and attacking the missionaries led by [[Hudson Taylor]]. No one was killed, however several of the missionaries were injured as they were forced to flee for their lives. As a result of the report of the riot, the British consul in [[Shanghai]], [[Walter Henry Medhurst (consul)|Sir Walter Henry Medhurst]] took seventy [[Royal Marines]] in a [[man-of-war]] and steamed up the Yangtze to Nanjing in a controversial show of force that eventually resulted in an official apology from [[Viceroy]] [[Zeng Guofan]] and financial restitution made to the injured missionaries.\n\nFrom the time of the [[Taiping Rebellion]] (1853) to the beginning of the Reform Era (1980) Yangzhou was in decline, due to war damage, neglect of the Grand Canal as railways replaced it in importance, and stagnation in the early decades of the PRC. During the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]], it endured eight years of enemy occupation and was used by the Japanese as a site for internment camps. About 1200 civilians of Allied nationalities (mostly British and Australian) from Shanghai were transported here in 1943, and located in one of three camps (A, B, and C). Camps B and C were closed down in September, 1943, after the second American-Japanese prisoner exchange, and their inhabitants transferred back to Shanghai camps.  Camp C, located in the former American Mission in the north-west of the city, was maintained for the duration of the war.<ref>Leck, Greg, ''Captives of Empire: The Japanese Internment of Allied Civilians in China'' Shandy Press, 2006; Antonia Finnane, ''Far From Where? Jewish Journeys from Shanghai to Australia'' (Melbourne University Press, 1999), 106-7.</ref>\n\nAmong early plans for railways in the late Qing was one for a line that would connect Yangzhou to the north but this was jettisoned in favour of an alternative route. The city's status as a leading economic centre in China was never to be restored. Not until the 1990s did it begin to regain some semblance of prosperity, benefitting from national economic growth and a number of targeted development projects. With the canal now partially restored, and excellent rail and road connections, Yangzhou is once again an important transportation and market center. It also has some industrial output, chiefly in cotton and textiles. In 2004, a railway linked Yangzhou for the first time with Nanjing.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Yangzhou five pavilion bridge.JPG|thumb|250px|The Five Pavilion Bridge over Shouxi Lake.]]\nYangzhou is located on a plain north of the Yangtze. The Grand Canal, also known as the  [[Beijing|Jing]]-[[Hangzhou|Hang]] Canal, crosses the prefecture-level from the north to the south; its modern route passes through the eastern outskirts of Yangzhou's main urban area, while its old route runs through the city center. Other major bodies of water within the prefecture-level city include the [[Baoshe River]], [[Datong River]], [[Beichengzi River]], [[Tongyang Canal]], [[Xintongyang Canal]], [[Baima Lake]], [[Baoying Lake]], [[Gaoyou Lake]] and [[Shaobo Lake]].\n\nLike much of the entire prefecture-level city, Yangzhou's main urban area (the \"city proper\") is criss-crossed by an intricate network of canals and small lakes. The historic city center  (the former waled city) is surrounded by canals on all sides: the Old Grand Canal forms its eastern and southern boundaries; the City Moat Canal runs along the former walled city's northern edge, connecting the Old Grand Canal with the [[Slender West Lake]]; the Erdaohe Canal runs along the old city's western edge, from the Slender West Lake to the [[Hehuachi Park|Lotus Flower Pond]] (Hehuachi), which in its turn is connected by the short Erdaogou canal with the Old Grand Canal.<ref>[http://yangzhou.yztm.net/tnewsshow.asp?id=450 \u53e4\u8fd0\u6cb3\u2014\u8377\u82b1\u6c60\u2014\u7626\u897f\u6e56\u6c34\u4e0a\u6e38\u89c8\u7ebf\u5168\u90e8\u8d2f\u901a] (The Old Grand Canal - Hehua Pond - Thin West Lake tourist waterway is fully open), 2010-09-20</ref> It is possible to sail a small water craft from the Thin West Lake, via the Erdaohe, the Hehua Pond, and the Erdaogou into the Old Grand Canal.<ref>[http://www.yzcn.net/broadcast/pic/2011/0329/124850.shtml \u7eff\u6768\u57ce\u90ed\u6c34\u4e0a\u6e384\u00b718\u4eae\u76f8],  2011-3-29; see the map in this article</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nYangzhou has a subtropical monsoon climate with humid changeable wind; longer winters for about 4 months, summers 3 months and shorter springs and autumns, 2 months respectively; frost-free period of 222 days and annual average sunshine of 2177 hours.\n\nThe mean annual temperature is {{convert|15.72|\u00b0C|1}} annually; the normal monthly mean 24-hour temperature ranges from {{convert|2.5|\u00b0C}} in January to {{convert|28.0|\u00b0C}} in July.\n\nThe annual average precipitation is {{convert|1043|mm|abbr=on}}, and about 45 percent of rainfall is concentrated in the summer. The rainy season known as \"plum rain season\" usually lasts from mid-June to late July. During this season, the plums are ripening, hence the name plum rain.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Yangzhou (1981\u20132010 normals)\n|collapsed =\n|single line = Y\n|metric first = Y\n|Jan high C =  6.8\n|Feb high C =  8.9\n|Mar high C = 13.7\n|Apr high C = 20.2\n|May high C = 25.9\n|Jun high C = 28.8\n|Jul high C = 31.9\n|Aug high C = 31.3\n|Sep high C = 27.4\n|Oct high C = 22.3\n|Nov high C = 15.9\n|Dec high C =  9.5\n\n|Jan mean C =  2.5\n|Feb mean C =  4.6\n|Mar mean C =  9.0\n|Apr mean C = 15.2\n|May mean C = 20.9\n|Jun mean C = 24.6\n|Jul mean C = 28.0\n|Aug mean C = 27.4\n|Sep mean C = 23.2\n|Oct mean C = 17.6\n|Nov mean C = 10.9\n|Dec mean C =  4.7\n\n|Jan low C = \u22120.8\n|Feb low C =  1.2\n|Mar low C =  5.2\n|Apr low C = 10.8\n|May low C = 16.5\n|Jun low C = 20.9\n|Jul low C = 24.8\n|Aug low C = 24.3\n|Sep low C = 19.8\n|Oct low C = 13.6\n|Nov low C =  6.8\n|Dec low C =  1.0\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm =  45.1\n|Feb precipitation mm =  47.8\n|Mar precipitation mm =  74.8\n|Apr precipitation mm =  71.4\n|May precipitation mm =  82.9\n|Jun precipitation mm = 138.1\n|Jul precipitation mm = 207.4\n|Aug precipitation mm = 141.3\n|Sep precipitation mm =  87.8\n|Oct precipitation mm =  56.3\n|Nov precipitation mm =  60.2\n|Dec precipitation mm =  30.3\n|year precipitation mm=\n|Jan humidity = 74\n|Feb humidity = 73\n|Mar humidity = 71\n|Apr humidity = 70\n|May humidity = 71\n|Jun humidity = 76\n|Jul humidity = 80\n|Aug humidity = 81\n|Sep humidity = 78\n|Oct humidity = 75\n|Nov humidity = 76\n|Dec humidity = 73\n|source 1 = China Meteorological Administration<ref name=\"cma graphical\">{{cite web\n|url=http://data.cma.cn/data/weatherBk.html\n|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u6c14\u8c61\u6570\u636e\u7f51 - WeatherBk Data\n|publisher=[[China Meteorological Administration]] |language = zh-cn\n|accessdate=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Transportation==\n[[File:Yangzhou Railway Station - P1070063.JPG|thumb|300px|Yangzhou Railway Station]]\nYangzhou has one [[Yangtze River bridges and tunnels|Yangtze River crossing]], the [[Runyang Yangtze River Bridge|Runyang Yangtze River Bridge complex]], which has one of the [[List of longest suspension bridge spans|one of the longest suspension bridge spans in the world]], and carries the [[G4011 Yangzhou\u2013Liyang Expressway]] to [[Zhenjiang]].\n\n===Air===\nThe [[Yangzhou Taizhou International Airport]], completed in 2012 to serve Yangzhou and neighbouring [[Taizhou, Jiangsu|Taizhou]], is located in Jiangdu district.  The [[Nanjing Lukou International Airport]] is over {{convert|100|km|mi|abbr=on}} away; it takes one hour and 40 minutes to get there from central Yangzhou. Prior to the completion of the Yangzhou Taizhou Airport, Lukou Airport in Nanjing was the primary air gateway for passengers destined for Yangzhou. There are over 10 airline ticket offices in Yangzhou, providing convenient service for foreign and domestic tourists. domestic and international fight are available with 10 international airlines and more than 20 domestic ones\n\n===Rail===\nUntil 2004, Yangzhou was not served by passenger rail. [[Yangzhou Railway Station]] began construction in 2003 and was completed a year later. It is located on the western outskirts of the city, and is a major station on the [[Nanjing\u2013Qidong Railway]], and provides direct passenger service to the provincial capital as well as a number of major cities to the west, north, and south (such as [[Xi'an]], [[Wuhan]], and [[Guangzhou]]), including an overnight [[Z-series trains|Z-series express train]] to [[Beijing]].<ref>[http://www.tielu.org/ tielu.org], schedule search for Yangzhou</ref> Later, frequent high-speed (D-series) service has been introduced on this line as well.\n\nThere is no direct rail service between Yangzhou and [[Shanghai]], however; to travel to Shanghai, or elsewhere in the [[Yangtze Delta]] regions, travelers cross the Yangtze over the new [[Runyang Bridge]] to Zhenjiang (frequent commuter bus service is available) and take a train from the [[Zhenjiang Railway Station]], which is located on the main Nanjing-Shanghai rail line.\n\nIn 2016, construction work started on a new north-south rail line, the Lianyungan-Huai'an-Yangzhou-Zhenjiang Railway. The new Yangzhou station will be located on the east side on the city, between Yangzhou main urban area and [[Jiangdu District]], {{convert|16.5|km|abbr=on}} east of the existing Yangzhou Railway Station.<ref name=gaotie20161215>{{cite web |url=http://news.gaotie.cn/tielu/2016-12-25/368045.html |script-title=zh:\u8fde\u6dee\u626c\u9547\u94c1\u8def\u626c\u5dde\u7ad9\u573a\u5f00\u5efa \u626c\u5dde\u53bb\u5317\u4eac\u4ec54.5\u5c0f\u65f6 |trans-title=Construction work starts at the site of the Yangzhou station of the Lianyungan-Huai'an-Yangzhou-Zhenjiang Railway. Just 4.5 hours from Yangzhou to Beijing |date=2016-12-25}}</ref> The new rail line is expected to open in 2020, while the new train station will gradually become the ciy's transportation hub, and its surrounding area, Yangzhou's new central business district.<ref name=gaotie20161215/>\n\n=== River transport ===\nYangzhou harbour, {{convert|11.5|km|abbr=on}} south from the city center, is located at the junction of the [[Grand Canal (China)|Beijing\u2013Hangzhou Canal]] and the [[Yangtze]] River. The average water depth is 15\u201320 meters. In 1992, the State Council approved it to become a first-grade open state harbour, and General Secretary [[Jiang Zemin]] inscribed its name. Now, it has developed into a comprehensive [[inland harbor]], integrating passenger, freight, container transportation and harbour trade, and has become the main distribution center of northern Jiangsu province, eastern [[Anhui]] Province and southeast [[Shandong]] Province. There are several dozen categories of goods including iron and steel, timber, minerals, coal, grain, cotton, container, products of light industry and machinery. The passenger routes reach Nanjing, Wuhu, [[Jiujiang]], [[Huangshi]] and [[Wuhan]] in the west, and [[Nantong]] and [[Shanghai]] in the east. Some well-known luxury international liners also anchor here. The harbour has greatly promoted the development of exports and the overall local economy.\n\n===Expressways===\n\nThe Ningyang (Nanjing\u2013Yangzhou) Expressway crosses the southern part of Yangzhou's metropolitan area while the Ningtong (Nanjing\u2013Nantong) Expressway is connected to Yangzhou at Liaojiagou. In recent years, local government have attached great importance to the development of the tourism, in conjunction with a greater effort dedicated to the improvement of the local road transport system. With a total investment of 680 million yuan, the Yangzhou section of the Ningyang Expressway was completed on December 18, 1998 and opened to traffic in June 1999. Stretching nearly {{convert|18|km|abbr=on}}, the section of the expressway starts from the Bazi Flyover as the entry/exit, via the Yanggua Highway, the Tonggang Highway, an ancient canal, the Yangwei Highway, the Beijing\u2013Hangzhou Grand Canal and the Yangling Highway, to Liqojiagou Entry/Exit of Yangjiang Highway. It then passes the Jiangdu Flyover to directly link up with the Huaijiang Expressway. In addition, the section of Huaijiang Expressway within the territory of Yangzhou began construction on March 22, 1997, which will be commonly used by the state planned Tongjiang\u2013Sanya and Beijing\u2013Shanghai trunk lines. The section of Huaijiang Expressway in Yangzhou totals {{convert|112.04|km|abbr=on}}in length, starting from Jinghe Town of Baoying in the north to the entry/exist of Zhuanqiaozhen Flyover of Jiangdu in the south. It then links with Ningtong Expressway, passing by three counties (cities) such as Baoying, Gaoyou and Jiangdu and 26 towns, at a total cost of 3.7 billion yuan. It is expected to be open to traffic by the year 2000.\n[[File:Yangzhou-Modern-Grand-Canal-barge-caravan-3342.JPG|thumb|The modern route of the [[Grand Canal (China)|Grand Canal]] passes within a few kilometers east of the city's main urban area]]\n\n===Intercity bus service===\nDuring the daytime, frequent bus service operates between Yangzhou and nearby cities. There are several bus stations on the city's outskirts; most of the buses from [[Nanjing]] (Nanjing West Bus Station) and Zhenjiang (where the bus station is adjacent to the [[Zhenjiang Railway Station]]) arrive to Yangzhou South Bus Station, located a few kilometers southwest from downtown. Most of the intercity bus service stops in the early evening.\n\n===Transportation in the Urban Area===\nThe city is served by an extensive network of public bus routes.\n\nYangzhou's taxi industry began in 1982, and has developed rapidly since 1993. the city has over 40 taxi companies of various ownership structures, with a total of 1,571 vehicles. Parking lots were established at key stations and hotels, and eight taxi companies have opened round-the-clock telephone service. The construction department of the municipal government has strengthened the management of taxi services, providing education in the relevant laws, professional ethics and safety aspects.\n\nIn 2014, Yangzhou's government approved plans for the construction of a subway system, which will initially include two lines. Line 1 will run in the general east-west direction, from Yangzhou Railway Station in the west to the historic central city to the future high-speed railway station (east of the Grand Canal) to [[Jiangdu District]]. Line 2 will run in the general north-south direction.<ref>[http://www.yznews.com.cn/09zjyz/jr/2014-06/06/content_5228300.htm \u626c\u5dde\u5730 1\u30012\u53f7\u7ebf\u8d70\u5411\u521d\u5b9a], 2014-06-06</ref>\n\n===Tourist Transportation===\n\nTo develop tourism in Yangzhou, sightseeing buses have been introduced in the city run by the Tianma travel agency under the Yangzhou Tourist Bureau. There is a tour guide on each bus. The route, starting from Yangzhou station, has eight stops, and passes by such scenic spots of the Slender West Lake, Daming Temple, Imperial Dock, Siwang Pagoda, Wenchang Pagoda and Shita Temple. Yangzhou Public Transit also operates No.1, No.5 and No.2 special tourist lines. No.1 bus departs from the bus station and goes by the Slender West Lake, Shigong Temple, Geyuan Garden and Heyuan Garden; No.5 bus starts from the bus station and goes by the Crane Temple, Wenchang Pagoda, Slender West Lake, Five-Pavilion Bridge, and Pingshan Hall. A sight-seeing route on Slender West Lake has opened, connecting Imperial Dock, Yichun Garden, Hong Garden, Dahong Bridge, Xiaojinshan, Diaoyutai, Five-Pavilion Bridge, and the 24-bridge, finally reaching Daming Temple and Pingshan Hall.<ref>[http://www.tourochina.com/guide/Yangzhou/transportation-index.html]</ref>\n\n==Industries and Shipyards==\nYangzhhou is the site of Chengxi shipyard, large shipyard where bulk carriers and other types of large ships are built.<ref>{{cite web |title=CSSC Official website |url=http://www.cssc.net.cn/en/ |website=www.cssc.net.cn |publisher=CSSC |accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Shipyards in Jiangsu China |url=https://www.shipyards.gr/shipyards/search-by/state?value=Jiangsu |website=www.shipyards.gr |publisher=Shipyard directory |accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref> Owned partly by the state owned [[CSSC]] holdings, through Jiangsu Xinrong shipyard, Chengxi Yangzhou shipyard builds ships from 25,000 dwt to 170,000 dwt in size.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chengxi Xinrong shipyard |url=https://www.shipyards.gr/shipyards/ship-repair-shipyards/Shiprepairs-fareast-pacific-ocean/Shiprepairs-fareast-china-sea/chengxi-shipyard-xinrong-china |website=www.shipyards.gr |publisher=Shipyard directory |accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jiangsu Chengxi shipyard |url=http://www.cccme.org.cn/shop/cccme2164/introduction.aspx |website=www.cccme.org.cn |publisher=Official website CCCME |accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Chengxi shipyard Jiangsu |url=https://ecmarine.com/jiangyin.html |website=www.ecmarine.com |publisher=East coast marine alliance |accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=China's white listed shipyards |url=https://www.tradewindsnews.com/incoming/article362564.ece5 |accessdate=6 December 2018 |publisher=Trade Winds}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Our expereince |url=http://tymvios.digital/projects/shipyard-experience/ |website=www.tymvios.digital |publisher=Shulte marine concepts |accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Cuisine==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2014}}\nYangzhou dishes may be one of the reasons why the people of Yangzhou are so infatuated with their city. They have an appealing color, aroma, taste and appearance. The original color of each ingredient is preserved after cooking, and no oily sauce is added, so as to retain the fresh flavour of the food.\n\nIn Yangzhou all dishes, whether cheap or expensive, are elaborate. Cooks will not scrimp on their work, even with [[dazhu gansi]] ({{zh|c=\u5927\u716e\u5e72\u4e1d|p=d\u00e0zh\u01d4 g\u0101ns\u012b}}), a popular dish that costs only a few yuan. Dry bean curd is made by each restaurant that serves it, so the flavor is guaranteed. The cook slices the 1-cm-thick curd into 30 shreds, each one paper-thin but none broken, and then stews them for hours with chopped bamboo shoots and shelled shrimps in chicken soup. In this way the dry bean curd shreds can soak up the flavor of the other ingredients, and the soup is clear but savory. Not only Yangzhou cooks, but also the ordinary people are conscientious about cooking.\n\n* [[Fu Chun Teahouse]]\n* [[Yangzhou fried rice]], is said {{by whom|date=May 2014}} to have been invented by a person who was a former Yangzhou [[magistrate]].\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Yangzhou-childrens-library-scooter-parking-3411.jpg|thumb|Children's Library building, on the premises of Yangzhou Public Library]]\nThe Yangzhou dialect ({{zh|c=\u626c\u5dde\u8bdd|p=Y\u00e1ngzh\u014du hu\u00e0|links=no}}) of Chinese is representative of [[Lower Yangtze Mandarin]], and is particularly close to the [[Mandarin (late imperial lingua franca)|official language]] of the [[Ming Dynasty|Ming]] and [[Qing Dynasty|Qing]] courts, which was based on the [[Nanjing dialect]]. However, it does differ considerably from modern [[Standard Chinese]], although they are still moderately [[mutually intelligible]].\n\nDialect has also been used as a tool for regional identity and politics in the [[Jiangbei region|Jiangbei]] and [[Jiangnan]] regions. While the city of Yangzhou was the center of trade, flourishing and prosperous, it was considered part of Jiangnan, which was known to be wealthy, even though Yangzhou was north of the Yangzi river. Once Yangzhou's wealth and prosperity were gone, it was then considered to be part of Jiangbei, the \"backwater\". After Yangzhou was removed from Jiangnan, its residents decided{{dubious|date=January 2016}} to replace [[Jianghuai Mandarin]], which was the dialect of Yangzhou, with [[Taihu Wu dialects]]. In Jiangnan itself, multiple subdialects of Wu fought for the position of prestige dialect.<ref>{{cite book\n | url=https://archive.org/details/teachersofinnerc00kodo\n | url-access=registration\n | title=Teachers of the inner chambers: women and culture in seventeenth-century China\n | volume=\n | year=1994\n | author=Dorothy Ko\n | publisher=Stanford University Press\n | edition=illustrated, annotated\n | location=\n | isbn=0-8047-2359-1\n | page=[https://archive.org/details/teachersofinnerc00kodo/page/21 21]\n | pages=\n | quote=With the exclusion of Yangzhou came the denigration of its dialect, a variant of Jianghuai \"Mandarin\" (guanhua). The various Wu dialects from the Lake Tai area became the spoken language of choice, to the point of replacing guanhua...\n | accessdate=23 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring a period of prosperity and Imperial favour, the arts of storytelling and painting flourished in Yangzhou. The innovative painter-calligrapher [[Shitao]] lived in Yangzhou during the 1680s and again from 1697 until his death in 1707. A later group of painters from that time called the [[Eight Eccentrics of Yangzhou]] are famous throughout China.\n\nFormer General secretary of CPC, President of China [[Jiang Zemin]] was born and raised in Yangzhou. His middle school is located right across from the public notary's office in Yangzhou.\n\nYangzhou is famous for its carved [[lacquerware]] and [[jade]].\n\nSome of China's most creative and eye catching dishes come from the Yangzhou school of cuisine called [[Huaiyang cuisine|Huaiyang]] (also commonly known as the Weiyang school). Along with [[Sichuan cuisine]], [[Cantonese cuisine]], and [[Shandong cuisine]], Huaiyang cuisine ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6dee\u626c\u83dc}}) is a distinctive and masterful skill that locals are quite proud of.\n\nThe city is famous for its [[public bath]] houses, [[lacquerware]], jadeware, embroidery, paper-cut, art & crafts velvet flavers.\n\nThe city was awarded [[Habitat Scroll of Honour]] in 2006.\n\nYangzhou is also very famous for its toy industry (especially stuffed animals). Many tourists from neighboring cities travel to the city for its good-quality and low-priced toys.\n\nIt is worth mentioning that the city is also famous for an ancient folk art called Yangzhou storytelling ({{lang|zh-hans|\u626c\u5dde\u8bc4\u8bdd}}), which is like [[Xiangsheng]]\u2014the traditional Chinese comedic performance. It rose as a performing act during the [[Ming Dynasty]]. In the performance, the artist details an interesting historical story to audiences, using Yangzhou dialect. These stories have been edited by artists, so they sound very soul-stirring and funny. The best known artist of Yangzhou storytelling was [[Wang shaotang]]. His most famous works are The 10 chapters of [[Wu Song]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6b66\u5341\u56de}}), The 10 chapters of [[Song Jiang]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5b8b\u5341\u56de}}), The 10 chapters of [[Lu Junyi]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5362\u5341\u56de}}), and The 10 chapters of [[Shi Xiu]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u77f3\u5341\u56de}}).<ref>Vibeke B\u00f8rdahl, The Oral Tradition of Yangzhou Storytelling, London: Routledge, 1996; Vibeke B\u00f8rdahl and Jette Ross, Chinese Storytellers: Life and Art in the Yangzhou Tradition, Cheng and Tsui 2002.</ref>\n[[File:Chinese snowball.jpg|right|thumb|Chinese snowball flowers]]\n\n===Literary references===\nYangzhou was frequently referenced in Chinese literature.  Poet [[Li Bai]] (c.700\u2013762) wrote in ''Seeing Meng Haoran off to Yangzhou from Yellow Crane Pavilion'':\n\n:At Yellow Crane Pavilion in the west\n:My old friend says farewell;\n:In the mist and flowers of spring\n:He goes down to Yangzhou;\n:Lonely sail, distant shadow,\n:Vanish in blue emptiness;\n:All I see is the great river\n:Flowing into the far horizon.\n\n[[Du Mu]] wrote the famous lines on Yangzhou:<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h8fWf7pYOIUC&pg=PA218&lpg=PA218#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=How to Read Chinese Poetry: A Guided Anthology|author= Zong-qi Cai |page= Columbia University Press|date=30 November 2007 |isbn=9780231511889 }}</ref>\n\n:After ten years, I awoke from my Yangzhou dream,\n:All I gained was a fickle reputation in the green mansions.\n\nThe \"green mansions\" or \"green/black lofts\" (''qinglou'') refers to the pleasure districts for which Yangzhou became known.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dvFJQ6WE1agC&pg=PA287#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= Lifestyle and Entertainment in Yangzhou|authors= Lucie B. Olivov\u00e1, Vibeke B\u00f8rdah |pages=287\u2013288 |publisher= : NIAS Press|date=1 October 2009|isbn= 978-8776940355 }}</ref>\n\n==Tourism==\n\nTourist sights include [[Slender West Lake]] and old residences in the moated town, such as the Wang Residence and the Daming temple. Yangzhou is famous for its many well preserved Yangzhou style gardens.  Most of the Historic city is in the Guangling District.\n\n===Slender West Lake===\n{{main|Slender West Lake}}\nNamed after Hangzhou's famous West Lake, this long, narrow stretch of water which meanders through Yangzhou's western limits is a well-known scenic spot. A long bank planted with weeping willows spans the lake; at its midpoint stands a square terrace with pavilions at each of the corners and one in the center. Around the lake is a park in which are found several attractions: Lotus Flower Pagoda (Lianhua SO), a white structure reminiscent of the White Pagoda (Baita) in Beijing's Beihai Park; Small Gold Mountain (Xiao Jin Shan); and the Fishing Platform (Diaoyutai), a favorite retreat of the Qing emperor Qian Long. The emperor was so gratified by his luck in fishing at this spot that he ordered additional stipends for the town. As it turns out, his success had been augmented by local swimmers who lurked in the lake busily attaching fish to his hook.\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160px\">\nImage:Serene and Fragrant Study.JPG|Study hall\nImage:Si Qiao Yan Yu Building.jpg|Four bridges in rain and mist\nImage:The Sunny Spring Stage.jpg|Imperial birthday celebration stage\nImage:Du Mu 24 bridge poem.JPG|Mao Zedong's calligraphy of Tang dynasty poet Du Mu poem\nImage:Twenty four bridge.JPG|24 ancient beauties played flute on this bridge\nImage:White pagoda clear sky and cloud garden.JPG|Entrance to a garden\nImage:Jinjingge copy.JPG|The jinjingge bridge\nImage:Xu Garden.jpg|The Xu Garden\n</gallery>\n\n===Daming Temple===\n{{main|Daming Temple}}\nLocated on Shugang Hill, in the city's northwest, is Fajing Temple, formerly known as DaMing Temple. The original temple was built in Liu Song Dynasty  (420\u2013479). A nine-story pagoda, the Qilingta, was built on the temple grounds in the year of Sui Dynasty (589\u2013618) . A recent addition to the temple complex is the [[Jianzhen]] Memorial Hall, built according to Tang Dynasty methods and financed with contributions raised by Buddhist groups in Japan.\nWhen Qing Emperor Qian Long visited Yangzhou in 1765, he was troubled by The temple's name DaMing (which literally means \"Great Ming') fearing that it might revive nostalgia for the Ming Dynasty, which was overthrown by his Manchu predecessors. He had it renamed Fajing Temple.\nThe temple was seriously damaged during the Taiping Rebellion at the beginning of the 20th century. The present structure is a reconstruction dating from the 1930s.\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160px\">\nImage:Daming temple.JPG|Da Ming Temple\nImage:Jianzhen memorial hall.jpg|Memorial Hall of monk Jianzhen\nImage:QilingP.jpg|Da Ming temple pagoda\n</gallery>\n\n===Flat Hills (Ping Shan) Hall===\nBuilt by the Song Dynasty writer Ouyang Xiu when he served as prefect of the city, this hall stands just west of Fajing Temple. Looking out from this hall, the mountains to the south of the Yangtze River appear as a line at the viewer's eye level, hence the name Flat Hills Hall. When Ouyang Xiu's student Su Dongpo moved to Yangzhou, he too served as prefect of the city. He had a hall built directly behind the one erected by his master, and called it Guling Hall.\n\n===Pavilion of Flourishing Culture ({{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u6587\u660c\u9601}}}}, W\u00e9nch\u0101ng G\u00e9)===\n[[File:Yangzhou-WenchangGe-traffic-3417.jpg|thumb|Wenchang Ge]]\nThis round, three-story pavilion in Yangzhou's eastern sector was built in 1585 and celebrates the city's rich cultural traditions. It is also the de facto center of the city.\n\nBuilt during [[Ming dynasty]], it is located on the cross of Wenchang Road and Wenhe Road. The whole building is about 79 foot high, and looks like [[Temple of Heaven]] in Beijing. Today, bordered by many shopping stores, Wenchange had been a symbol of commercial center to residents.\n\n===Stone Pagoda ===\nStanding west of the Pavilion of Flourishing Culture is a five-story Tang Dynasty pagoda ({{zh|s=\u77f3\u5854|hp=Sh\u00edt\u01ce|links=no}}). Built in 837, it is the oldest pagoda still standing in Yangzhou.\n\n===Tomb of Puhaddin===\n[[File:Yangzhou-Minaret-3284.jpg|thumb|left|The mosque complex at the tomb of Puhaddin]]\nThis is essentially a Ming Dynasty graveyard that includes the tomb of [[Puhaddin]]. According to information at the tomb, he was a 16th generation descendant of [[Muhammad]], The Prophet. The tomb is on the eastern bank of the (Old) Grand Canal in the eastern sector of the city and is adjacent to a mosque which houses a collection of valuable materials documenting China's relations with Muslim countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fodors.com/world/asia/china/beijing-to-shanghai/review-434792.html|title=Garden Tomb of Puhaddin Beijing to Shanghai Review|website=www.fodors.com}}</ref>\n\n===Ge Garden ({{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u4e2a\u5712}}}}, G\u00e8 Yu\u00e1n)===\nThe entrance to this typical southern style garden with its luxuriant bamboo groves, ponds, and rock grottoes is on Dongguan St. in the city's northeast section. Designed by the great Qing Dynasty landscape painter Shi Tao for Wang Yingtai, an officer of the Qing imperial court, this garden takes its name from the shape of bamboo leaves which resemble the Chinese character ge, meaning \"a\" or \"an.\"\n\n===He Garden ({{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u4f55\u56ed}}}}, H\u00e9 Yu\u00e1n)===\nThis garden, also called Jixiao Shan Zhuang, was built by He Zhidao, a 19th-century Qing government official, this garden home is famous for a {{convert|430|m|ft|abbr=on}}, two storied winding corridor, the walls of which are lined with stone tablets carved with lines of classical poetry, In the garden is also an open-air theater set on an island in the middle of a fish pond.\n\n===Yechun Garden (Yechun Yuan)===\nIn this garden, which lies on the banks of the Xiading River at the city's northern limits, the Qing Dynasty poet Wang Yuyang and a circle of friends used to gather to recite their works. The thatched roofs of the pavilions in this garden give it a quaint, rustic air.\n\n===[[Yangzhou Museum]] & Yangzhou Block Printing Museum ===\n[[File:Yangzhou-Double-Museum-2869.jpg|thumb|Yangzhou Museum / China Block Printing Museum]]\nSituated on the west side of the Bright Moon Lake, the Yangzhou Chinese Block Printing Museum ({{lang|zh-hans|\u626c\u5dde\u4e2d\u56fd\u96d5\u7248\u5370\u5237\u535a\u7269\u9986}}) and Yangzhou Museum ({{lang|zh-hans|\u626c\u5dde\u535a\u7269\u9986}}) look into the distance of Yangzhou International Exhibition Centre and covers an area of 50,000 square meters, with a construction space of 25,000 square meters, and an exhibition area of 10,000 square metres. Its unique architectural form embodies the harmony of man nature, structure and natural environment. In August, 2003, over 300,000 ancient books blockings were collected from Guangling Press of Yangzhou and China Block Printing Museum was established under the approval of the State Council, over 300,000 ancient book blockings collected by Guangling Press of Yangzhou were included in the new museum.\n\n===Jiangdu Hydro Project===\nConstruction of this multiple-purpose water control project, the biggest in China, started in 1961 and was completed in 1975. The project includes facilities for irrigation, drainage, navigation, and power generation. It consists of four large modern electric pumping stations, six medium-sized check gates, thrice navigation locks, and two trunk waterways.\n\n==Education==\n*[[Yangzhou University]]\n*[[Sima Primary School]]\n*[[Yangzhou Polytechnic College]]\n*[[Yangzhou Polytechnic Institute]]\n\n==Sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in China}}\n* {{flagdeco|Russia}} [[Balashikha]], Moscow Oblast, Russia\n* {{flagdeco|USA}} [[Kent, Washington]], US<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kentwa.gov/SisterCity-YangzhouChina.html |title=Yangzhou, China |website=City of Kent, Washington}}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|Malaysia}} [[Malacca City]], Malaysia\n* {{flagdeco|Germany}} [[Neubrandenburg]], Germany<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neubrandenburg.de/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=192:partnerste&catid=34:partnerste&Itemid=184 |title=Yangzhou, China - sister city|website=Neubrandenburg, Germany website}}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|Germany}} [[Offenbach am Main]], Germany (since 1997)<ref>{{cite web|title=Offenbach und seine Partnerst\u00e4dte|url=http://www.offenbach.de/rathaus/stadtinfo/staedtepartnerschaften/staedtepartnerschaften-intro.php|publisher=City of Offenbach|accessdate=25 September 2016|date=21 April 2010}}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|France}} [[Orl\u00e9ans]], France\n* {{flagdeco|New Zealand}} [[Porirua]], New Zealand<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sistercities.org.nz/index.php?s=cities | title=About Sister Cities | website=Sister Cities New Zealand}}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|Canada}} [[Vaughan]], Ontario, Canada\n* {{flagdeco|USA}} [[Westport, Connecticut]], US<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westportct.gov/index.aspx?page=190 |title=Sister Cities Committee |website=Westport, Connecticut}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Iranians in China]]\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book | first = Alvyn | last = Austin | authorlink = Alvyn Austin | year = 2007 | title = China\u2019s Millions: The China Inland Mission and Late Qing Society | publisher = Eerdmans | location = Grand Rapids, Michigan | isbn =978-0-8028-2975-7}}\n*{{cite book | first = Antonia | last = Finnane | authorlink = Antonia Finnane| year = 2004 | title = Speaking of Yangzhou: A Chinese City, 1550 - 1850| publisher = Harvard Asia Center | location = Cambridge, Massachusetts | isbn =0674013921}}\n* {{cite book | first = Jonathan | last = Hay | authorlink = Jonathan Hay (author)| year = 2001 | title = Shitao: Painting and Modernity in Early Qing China| publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = New York| is